<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0670 11-25 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0719</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds Orr, McReynolds, Gerson. AMs separates moved on Alexander
as a0564 and Herzfelde as a0597.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Herbert W. Alexander</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert W. Alexander, retired publisher and
editor in chief of Pocket Books, died Wednesday. He was 78.
   Alexander, who retired on Jan. 1, 1974, also was a director and
vice president of Simon & Schuster, which has owned Pocket Books
since the late 1950's. Under his editorship, Pocket Books built a
strong list of mysteries by acquiring reprints of books by Agatha
Christie, Raymond Chandler, Ellery Queen, Dashiell Hammett and
others.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Wieland Herzfelde</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wieland Herzfelde, a publisher and writer whose
communist views made him a target of the Nazis, died Wednesday in
East Berlin. He was 93.
   The Swiss-born writer and intellectual founded a publishing house
in Berlin in 1917, which printed Dadaist and anti-war literature and
the works of young Soviet writers. The publishing house was banned
by the Nazis in 1933, and Herzfelde, a member of the German
Communist Party, fled the country.
   He published a magazine in Prague until 1939, when he fled to New
York. There he founded the Aurora Verlag publishing house, working
with noted German writers such as Bertolt Brecht, Heinrich Mann and
Alfred Doeblin. He emigrated to communist-ruled East Germany in
1949, where he continued his work as a writer and publisher and was
a literature professor at the University of Leipzig.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>David Moxley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Moxley, a former managing director of
Touche Ross International who served as a political adviser to Sen.
Robert Dole, R-Kansas, died Monday of a heart attack. He was 57.
   Moxley joined Touche Ross, a major accounting and management
consulting firm, after getting his masters degree from the
University of Kansas in 1958. He moved up to become a managing
partner of Touche Ross USA and was managing director of Touche Ross
International from 1982 until his retirement in 1985. He then worked
as a senior adviser to Dole until Dole withdrew from the
presidential race earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Irmgard Seefried</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soprano Irmgard Seefried, best known for
singing the role of Susanna in Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro,''
died Thursday at age 69, Austrian radio reported. The cause of death
was not given.
   Ms. Seefried, a native of Bavaria, studied at the music
conservatory in Augsburg. In 1943 she joined the Vienna opera, and
she stayed with the opera for the rest of her career.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Wallace E. Orr</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Florida labor secretary Wallace
E. Orr, who rose from being a farmworker to high government service,
died Wednesday at 64. The hospital where he died did not give the
cause of death.
   Orr served eight years as head of the state Department of Labor
and Employment Security, one of the top-ranking black officials in
state government. As a younger man, Orr worked as a fruit picker, a
waiter and a house servant before entering the University of Miami
and becoming a teacher. He was elected president of the Broward
Classroom Teachers Association union and later became state
president of the Florida Teaching Profession-National Education
Association.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Guy E. McReynolds</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guy E. McReynolds, a nationally recognized
breeder of purebred Hampshire swine, died Wednesday of pneumonia. He
was 84 and had been ill with Alzheimer's disease.
   McReynolds began raising purebred Hampshires in 1933, and in 1959
the McReynolds and Sons breeding herd became the first purebred
swine herd to participate in the Specific Pathogen Free program
developed at the University of Nebraska as a means to break the
cycle of several swine diseases.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Noel Gerson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noel Gerson, a former Chicago journalist and
author of 325 books, including ``55 Days in Peking'' and ``The Naked
Maja,'' died Sunday of a heart attack in Boca Raton, Fla. He was 75.
   Gerson was a reporter for the Chicago Herald-Examiner and a
scriptwriter at WGN-TV before turning to fiction in 1950. His novels
included ``The Imposter,'' ``The Forest Lord,'' ``The Mohawk
Ladder,'' ``The Golden Eagle,'' and ``The Highwayman,'' as well as
``55 Days in Peking'' and ``The Naked Maja'' which were made into
movies.
</TEXT>
