<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--RodinHeist     11-25 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Rodin Heist,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rodin-Sculpted Mask Stolen From Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No trace has been found of a gunman who
handcuffed three museum guards and made off with a 10\-inch tall
bronze mask by French sculptor Auguste Rodin, police said Thursday.
   The gunman fired a warning shot and handcuffed the guards
Wednesday evening before fleeing the Rodin Museum in downtown
Philadelphia with the 19th-century sculpture, Man With the Broken
Nose, police said.
   The theft was the third at a Philadelphia museum in the past two
weeks.
   Detective John McNamee said Thursday officers were trying to find
a woman who had left the museum just before the robbery occurred.
``One of the guards saw her out there. We don't think she was
involved at all,'' McNamee said.
   The mask is valued at more than $75,000, according to John
Erickson, head of museum security. The robber was described as a
white man in his early to mid-20s, wearing jeans, white sneakers and
a long, gray tweed overcoat.
</TEXT>
