<2ND_LINE>PM-Khomeini-Musavi,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Confirms Support For Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's
revolutionary patriarch, reiterated his support for Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi two months after Musavi tried to resign.
   In a lengthy statement broadcast Thursday on Tehran television,
the 87-year-old Khomeini said he had to confirm his support of
Musavi because some people might want to ``harm your relentless and
tireless efforts, especially on the issue of the war.''
   ``As before, I regard you as a qualified and sympathetic
individual for the Islamic Revolution,'' Khomeini said. He also
asked Musavi to form an organization to care for disabled war
veterens.
   Musavi thanked Khomeini for his support, calling it ``an
encouragement,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   In September, Musavi submitted his letter of resignation.
Khomeini rejected it and rebuked him for attempting to resign.
   Long-simmering differences within the leadership are believed to
have prompted Musavi's attempt.
   He is regarded as one of the more conservative leaders in the
split between the conservative and pragmatic camps. He advocated
continuing the eight-year war with Iraq, which pragmatics headed by
parliamentary speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani opposed.
   Musavi also advocates a more centralized economy and tight
controls on foreign imports, which Iran has to finance with scarce
hard currency. Rafsanjani opposes Musavi on both issues.
   The prime minister has had to defer to the will of the pragmatic
leaders on the war, and his views on the economy also are unlikely
to be implemented as Iran moves toward a more laissez-faire economy.
   Relations with the West and the Persian Gulf states, strained
during the war, are being improved, a move which Rafsanjani favored
but Musavi opposed.
</TEXT>
