<HEAD>Dollar Unchanged, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar. Pick
up 4th pvs, `The dollar...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed unchanged against the Japanese yen
Friday, and share prices gained ground on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
reversing Thursday's decline.
   The dollar closed at 121.15 yen, unchanged from Thursday's close
of 121.15 yen. After opening at 120.88 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 120.67 yen to 121.20 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 90.09-point
loser Thursday, gained 66.62, or 0.23 percent, to close at 29,406.65.
   The dollar opened lower after declining in London overnight.
   Exchange dealers said intervention by the Bank of Japan and
bullish comments by Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa had slowed but
not stopped the dollar's decline.
   Miyazawa told reporters Friday that Japan is ready to intervene
in the currency market to stem volatility in exchange rates.
   He also said he sees no need for a meeting of the Group of Seven
(G-7) monetary nations based on fluctuations in the currency market.
His comments followed calls from finance ministers Gerhard
Stoltenberg West Germany and Pierre Beregovoy of France for a G-7
meeting after President-elect George Bush's inauguration.
   Exchange dealers said market sentiment toward the dollar remains
bearish.
   ``The best explanation about the dollar's bearishness is that the
market cannot find reasons to buy the dollar,'' said a dealer at a
major U.S. bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   It was the first time since Jan. 4 that the dollar opened at the
120-yen level.
   Prices meanwhile remained firm in the stock market. Securities
dealers said most shares are rising, including export-oriented
shares, despite the strong yen.
   ``The general sentiment of the market is still bullish,'' said
Ichitaro Watanabe of Nikko Securities Co.
</TEXT>
