<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     11-25 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiites Clash In South Beirut, Seven Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias, backed by
Syria and Iran, battled with tanks, rockets and mortars in the slums
of south Beirut today.
   Police said seven people were killed and 20 wounded before a
cease-fire ended the worst fighting in six months.
   A police spokesman said most casualties were residents caught in
crossfire after skirmishes broke out Thursday night between the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the pro-Syrian Amal.
Amal is Arabic for ``hope.''
   Both sides accused each other of provoking the clash, the
fiercest since Syrian troops were deployed in south Beirut in May to
end two weeks of Amal-Hezbollah fighting.
   The spokesman said stray shells hit several apartments in the
densely populated slum area, driving panic-stricken residents to
spend the night in basements and bomb shelters.
   The exchanges died down at 3:30 a.m. after a cease-fire was
called by a Syrian army contingent in charge of security in west and
south Beirut, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Exploding shells and bursts of machine-gun fire echoed around the
city during the night as the two factions fired mortar rounds and
rocket-propelled grenades.
   ``I was preparing dinner when the clashes broke out,'' said Umm
Mohammed, a housewife in south Beirut's Haret Hreik district. ``My
daughter, three grandchildren and I rushed to the basement for
cover. We didn't have dinner.'' She said that during a lull in the
fighting, ``when I tried to fetch some food from the apartment I saw
Amal tanks rumbling across the narrow alley and the Hezbollahis
started shooting at them.''
   She said she ventured out this morning to buy food. ``I don't
trust the cease-fire, they will fight again,'' she said.
   Shortly after midnight, fighting spread to the west Beirut
districts of Basta, Nouwairi and Zokat Blatt when a rocket-propelled
grenade slammed into the apartment of Ayoub Homayed, a ranking Amal
leader.
   The police spokesman said Homayed and his family were unhurt.
   Amal and Hezbollah are longtime rivals for dominance of the 1
million Shiites, the largest single sect in Lebanon.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah blamed Amal for a failed car-bomb
assassination attempt against four senior Hezbollah leaders Monday
in east Lebanon.
   Amal had accused Hezbollah of assassinating the militia's three
top commanders for south Lebanon in a Sept. 22 ambush in south
Beirut.
   The police spokesman said Amal fighters, backed by six
Soviet-made T-54 tanks, advanced about 500 yards across the northern
flank of Hezbollah-controlled territory in south Beirut's Mouawad
district.
   He said the two sides were observing a ``cease-fire-in-place,''
with Amal militiamen refusing to withdraw from the area they gained.
   ``The gunmen are still there. God knows when they will start
shooting again,'' the spokesman said.
   Schools, banks, shops, restaurants and other businesses stayed
closed for the day in south Beirut, and traffic was sparse on the
usually crowded streets.
   Schools in west Beirut also stayed closed and only a few
employees turned up for work at banks, restaurants and government
offices.
   ``We do not want to be responsible for the students if
large-scale hostilities break out,'' said Khalaf Wihbeh, a
schoolteacher in west Beirut.
</TEXT>
