<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0447,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Sinn Fein Councilman's Brother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with details, police comment. Pick up graf
6 pvs, `Earlier Thursday ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen apparently targeting a
Sinn Fein councilman shot and killed his brother instead, police
said.
   Phelim McNally, 28, was slain Thursday night while he was playing
an accordion in the kitchen of the home of his brother, local Sein
Fein councilman Francis McNally, police said. Sinn Fein is the legal
political wing of the outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attack, which
the British domestic news agency Press Association said occurred
near Coagh, 30 miles west of Belfast.
   An officer at Belfast police headquarters confirmed a man was
killed but refused to elaborate. A press officer in Belfast later
said the gunmen may have been seeking to kill the councilman, not
his brother.
   The press officer said the gunmen, believed to number three,
fired through the kitchen window from outside the house. The
brothers were the only ones at home at the time, police and news
reports said.
   The news agency said the victim had been to the hospital to visit
his wife, who is expecting their sixth child, and then visited his
brother's house. The news agency also said it appeared he may have
been mistaken for his brother.
   Earlier Thursday night, a British soldier suffered leg injuries
in a bomb attack on an army patrol in the Roman Catholic area of
west Belfast.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the bomb attack,
but suspicion fell on the IRA, which is fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland. The mainly Catholic IRA wants to unite the
predominantly Protestant province with the 95 percent Catholic
Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
   On Wednesday night, an IRA bomb attack on an unmanned part-time
police station at Benburb, 35 miles west of Belfast, killed a
67-year-old Catholic and his 13-year-old granddaughter. Eight
civilians were wounded.
   The IRA, claiming responsibility, called the deaths of Barney
Lavery and Emma Donnelly ``tragic.'' Their deaths bring the total of
innocent civilians killed in bungled IRA attacks the last 12 months
to at least 19.
   In London on Thursday, the British government proposed
legislation that among other things requires Northern Ireland
election candidates to sign a declaration disavowing terrorism.
   Northern Ireland has been plagued by political and sectarian
violence since August 1969 and more than 2,700 people have been
killed. The IRA is outlawed in both Britain and Ireland.
   The anti-violence oath applies to all candidates in the province
but is believed aimed mainly at Sinn Fein. The law is likely to take
effect before the municipal elections in May.
   Sinn Fein commands about one-third of the Roman Catholic vote in
the troubled province and won about 10 percent of the seats on 17 of
the province's 26 local authorities in May 1985 elections.
   Under its terms, elected candidates must sign the declaration
before they can take their seats. If they then voice support for
violence, they can be disqualified from office for five years if
successfully prosecuted by fellow council members or members of the
public.
   In other proposed measures, a law on prison sentences would
require a prisoner to serve two-thirds of his time instead of being
eligible for parole at midpoint in his term, as under current law.
The Northern Ireland Office says one-fifth of offenders released in
1984 committed offenses within two years.
   Another measure limits banking secrecy and empower courts to
seize funds believed to be earned from racketeering related to
terrorism.
   Last month, Britain banned broadcast interviews with members of
the IRA and 10 other militant Northern Ireland groups, Catholic and
Protestant. The government also plans to end the right of suspects
to remain silent under police interrogation.
   The laws are virtually certain to pass in the House of Commons,
where Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has a huge majority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
