<DOCNO> AP881125-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea 2ndLd-Writethru   11-25 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0459,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Monks Battle Police; Demand Arrest Of Chun</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY that not all 2,000 students involved
in fighting. Pick up 3rd pvs, ``Arrest Chun...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students and Buddhist monks
demanding the arrest of former President Chun Doo-hwan hurled
hundreds of firebombs today at riot police in street clashes after
authorities blocked a protest march.
   Radicals battled police in streets and alleyways around Dongguk
University in eastern Seoul about some 2,000 students from 10 Seoul
colleges tried to march out despite freezing temperatures. About
1,000 protesters stormed out of the college to bombard troopers with
rocks and firebombs that exploded in showers of blazing gasoline.
   ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan,'' protesters shouted. ``Yankee go home''
   Several thousand riot police in green combat fatigues and black
visored helmets ringed the campus to stop students breaking through.
Troopers fired volleys of choking tear gas and hurled back rocks and
other missiles.
   Police had no immediate word on casualties or arrests.
   Student leaders at an earlier campus rally denounced Chun's
apology on Wednesday for corruption and human rights abuses. Leaders
demanded the former president be arrested and prosecuted for
numerous alleged crimes.
   Protesters also denounced President Roh Tae-woo and demanded he
also be punished. Speakers told the cheering crowd that Roh was
guilty of corruption and was trying to protect Chun.
   Protesters burned an effigy of Roh before marching out with
banners and flags to try and parade through the city. ``Punish Roh
Tae-woo,'' protesters chanted.
   Buddhisht monks armed with firebombs joined the students in the
fighting. Chun has taken refuge in a remote Buddhist monastery on
the east coast, and the monks claimed his presence there was a
desecration of a holy place.
   ``Drive out Chun from our sacred temple,'' the monks chanted.
   Chun, in a nationally televised speech Wednesday, apologized for
abuses under his seven-year authoritarian rule. Chun said he was
surrendering his personal property and going into internal exile.
   Chun has denied any personal corrutpion, but some of his
relatives and associates have been convicted of or charged with
embezzlement and other offenses.
   Dissident groups refused to accept the apology as sufficent and
said Chun must be prosecuted. The main opposition parties have also
said further explanation is necessary.
   Roh, a former close associate of Chun, is scheduled to make a
statement Saturday in which he may pardon the former president or at
least ask for public mercy. The announcement probably would trigger
further outbursts from radicals and other opposition groups.
   Earlier, the presidential office said Roh would appear on
national television tonight to make the statement, but it changed
the day.
   ``Enough has been done,'' Roh told governing party officials on
Thursday. ``As a long friend, I felt deep sorrow for the former
president, who had to leave in such a way.''
   Roh is trying to defuse public anger against Chun without
damaging himself and his government. Many Koreans see the Roh
administration as a continuation of the Chun government.
   Roh, a former general who took power in February after winning
elections in December, has introduced broad, democratic reforms. He
has dismantled many of the authoritarian controls imposed by Chun,
who took power with military backing in 1980.
   North Korea today called Chun's apology ``an offspring of
conspiracy and compromise'' between Chun and the South Korean
government.
   The official (North) Korean Central News Agency quoted a
spokesman of the Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the
Fatherland as saying Chun ``tried to gloss over his shocking
murderous atrocities, including the Kwangju bloodbath and all kinds
of irregularities, with the monosyllable word, `I apologize.'''
   A 1980 civil uprising in the southern city of Kwangju was
violently quashed by the military, resulting in the deaths of about
200 people.
   ``It is preposterous, indeed, to try to dispose of Chun's crimes
with something like an `apology,''' the unidentified spokesman was
quoted as saying.
   The two Koreas have remained bitter rivals since the Korean
peninsula was divided into the communist north and pro-Western south
at the end of World War II. Both sides fought the bloody Korean war
in 1950-53.
</TEXT>
