<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0600EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GoldenTriangle     11-25 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Golden Triangle,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge US Heroin Shipment Expected From Bumper Poppy Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An expected bumper crop of poppies in the Golden
Triangle of Southeast Asia probably will lead to a huge shipment of
heroin into the United States, a top U.S. drug enforcement official
said today.
   Thomas C. Kelly, deputy administrator of the Drug Enforcement
Agency, also said shipment of heroin from the Golden Triangle
through China has become a serious problem that Beijing authorities
are working to control.
   Much of the heroin smuggled into the United States, where about
500,000 people are believed addicted to the drug, comes from the
remote territory where Burma, Laos and Thailand meet.
   ``The past couple of years we've had bumper crops coming out of
the Golden Triangle,'' Kelly told reporters in Hong Kong. ``This
year ... appears to be no exception to the bumper crop of the poppy
and we are projecting there is going to be a tremendous shipment of
heroin into the U.S.,'' he said.
   Chinese officials are still learning how to fight the smuggling
and have talked to U.S. drug enforcement agents about the
possibility of additional training, he said.
   Kelly, who is visiting Hong Kong after attending an Interpol
meeting in Thailand, said the role of this British colony in
international heroin trafficking has increased because it is a major
transportation hub near the Golden Triangle.
   The amount of heroin coming through Hong Kong is likely to rise
with the continued good harvests, he added.
   Kelly said there were no reliable estimates of the amount of
heroin shipped from Hong Kong to the United States or what
percentage of the drug reaching America is shipped through this
British colony.
   But he said ethnic Chinese have captured much of the U.S. market
because of their business acumen, their contacts in Asia and
crackdowns on the traditional Mafia.
   U.S. and Hong Kong drug enforcement agencies have cooperated in a
number of major heroin busts in the past year.
   Hong Kong police announced Thursday they have seized 596 pounds
of No. 4 grade heroin so far this year, more than double the 1987
total of 286 pounds. No. 4 heroin is the grade used in the United
States.
</TEXT>
