<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhiteHouseHelp     11-25 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-White House Help,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Helps Reunite Dying Man's Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Vest said he had just about given up
hope on finding a way to bring his sister home from Alaska so she
could be with their dying father. Then, from a hospital pay phone,
he called the White House.
   Vest's 71-year-old father, Lester, a farmer from Trimble County,
was dying of lung and bone cancer and the family couldn't scrape
together enough money for the elder daughter, Teresa Vest, to fly in
from Anchorage, Alaska.
   It had been 14 years since Teresa had seen her family.
   ``By the time I called the White House, I was to the point that I
didn't think there was a person in the world that cared _ that
unless you were a really big shot, it didn't matter,'' Vest said.
   ``I called her (Teresa) the night that I took Daddy to the
hospital, and it was hard on her,'' said the 28-year-old Vest, who
quit his job at a small plant in Madison, Ind., a month ago to care
for his father and 65-year-old mother, who is recuperating from
open-heart surgery.
   The next day, Vest began calling charitable organizations and
churches for help to bring his sister home to this northern Kentucky
town, but without success.
   Finally, through Gov. Wallace Wilkinson's office, Vest was put in
touch with a social-services worker who persuaded an airline to
reduce its Alaska-to-Kentucky round-trip fare by about half. But
that was still too expensive.
   It was late in the day, and Vest and another sister, Velvet, sat
quietly discussing what to do next.
   ``I said, `Well, it probably won't do a bit of good, but I'm
going to call the White House. Maybe the president could do
something, if he would,' '' Vest said.
   A long distance operator helped Vest reach the White House, where
his call was finally transferred to Charlene Cozart, one of several
special liasons to the president.
   ``She called me back the next morning and said, `The ticket's at
the airport. All you have to do is pick it up.' ''
   Ms. Cozart said the White House gets several thousand similar
requests each year, and they are evaluated on a case-by-case basis.
   Teresa Vest arrived from Alaska on Nov. 4, one week before her
father died.
   ``When I told him she was on her way, he said, `I'll have to see
her walk through that door before I believe it,' '' Vest remembers
his father saying. ``It was a real happy moment, right in the middle
of a really sad moment.''
</TEXT>
