<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Iran     11-25 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Iran,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister To Visit Iran Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since the Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini took power in Iran, a French foreign minister will meet
with officials in Tehran next year, the government announced today.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas will travel to Tehran at an
unspecified date in 1989, a foreign ministry spokesman said,
confirming a report carried Thursday by the official Iranian news
agency IRNA.
   In November, Dumas told reporters, ``This voyage (to Iran) will
take place. I cannot say when, but I am completely ready to
undertake it.''
   The foreign minister has a trip to Iraq planned for mid-December,
although an exact date has not yet been announced. France has been a
major supplier of arms to Iraq throughout the Iran-Iraq war.
   The visit to Iran, the first since the 1979 overthrow of Shah
Muhammad Reza Pahlavi, comes at the end of a turbulant period in
French-Iranian relations.
   In June 1987, French investigators sought to question Iranian
Embassy translator Wahid Gordji about possible links to people
accused in the September 1986 bombings in Paris that left 11 people
dead and more than 150 people injured.
   Gordji took refuge in the embassy, whose officials asserted he
had diplomatic immunity. The French disagreed and blockaded the
embassy. The standoff continued and relations further deteriorated
until a final diplomatic rupture on July 17.
   At the end of November, two French hostages were released in
Beirut and shortly afterward Gordji was questioned and put on a
plane for home.
   Diplomatic relations were restored June 16.
   In November, a French parliamentary delegation visited Tehran to
meet with Iranian deputies from the foreign ministry and the prime
minister's office.
   A group of French businessmen accompanied the politicians,
including representatives from drug firms and construction companies.
   Since the cease-fire was declared in the war, West Germany, Italy
and Britain also have sent sizeable delegations to negotiate for the
millions of dollars worth of work that will be needed to reconstruct
the country following the eight-year war.
   A second French delegation of businessmen is expected to make a
trip to Iran this month.
   Iran's deputy foreign minister for European and U.S. Affairs
Mohammad Larijani has visited Paris twice since early August in
connection with ongoing peace negotiations in Geneva to end the
Persian Gulf war.
</TEXT>
