<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0738EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     11-25 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paratroopers Sentenced For Rampage In Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army sentenced 21 paratroopers to up to two
weeks in prison after a rampage in which soldiers smashed windows of
homes and damaged cars in a Palestinian refugee camp, a military
spokesman said today.
   Right-wing politicians demanded the soldiers be immediately
pardoned, and one leading left-wing leader blamed government
policies for the rampage, instead of the soldiers.
   An Israeli officer, meanwhile, testified at the trial of four
soldiers in the beating death of a Palestinian in the Gaza Strip
that the soldiers were obeying orders, the Hebrew-language daily
Hadashot reported.
   ``The order to beat Arab rioters came straight from the commander
of the Gaza Strip, Brig. Gen. Zvi Poleg, and the soldiers were
carrying out the spirit of the order,'' the paper quoted Lt. Rafil
Tawil as saying.
   Another soldier, Haim Teferberg, was quoted in the newspaper
Haaretz as testifying he saw the victim, Hani El Shemi, beaten in
the Jebaliya refugee camp. El Shemi, 43, died Aug. 22.
   Teferberg said, ``He was hunched over as he walked and blood was
dropping from his mouth. I saw him up close. They put him into the
camp, his breathing was heavy. He kept saying, `I want to die.'''
   ``When they put him on the floor I saw a soldier in the Jebaliya
refugee camp run quickly toward him and kick him, as though in a
karate move,'' the paper quoted him as saying. ``After that he no
longer had a pulse.
   ``This is customary. Many soldiers beat up prisoners,'' Teferberg
was quoted as testifying.
   During the early days of the Palestinian uprising, which began
Dec. 8, the army had a policy of clubbing protesters instead of
shooting to stop violent demonstrations. But army officials have
repeatedly denied that the policy allowed soldiers to beat prisoners
in custody.
   At least 315 Palestinians have been killed, most by army gunfire,
since the uprising started. Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Today in the Gaza Strip, a 16-year-old boy was shot and seriously
wounded in the Buriej refugee camp, hospital officials said. They
quoted camp refugees as saying the boy was hit when soldiers opened
fire on stone-throwing youths.
   In the West Bank, Jewish settlers set tires ablaze to block the
road into the Arab town of Qalqilya after a 52-year-old woman
settler was injured when someone hit her from a stone, the radio
said. Radio reports said the woman victim was hit in the eye and was
to undergo surgery today.
   The 21 soldiers sentenced to jail after the rampage Sunday in the
Kalandia refugee camp confessed to smashing windows and doors of
houses and damaging cars, Israel radio said.
   They were sentenced to a week to two weeks in jail, an army
spokesman said. He said three sergeants were given two-week
sentences with a further two weeks suspended. Their squadron leader
was sentenced Tuesday to two weeks in prison.
   Reports at the time said the soldiers went on a rampage after
their bus was stoned as it went through the camp. Witnesses said at
least four cars and 20 houses were damaged.
</TEXT>
