<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Retarded     11-25 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Retarded,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Province Bans Mentally Retarded From Having Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One province has barred mentally retarded people
from having children, and the Ministry of Public Health said today
it is drafting a law that would extend the ban nationwide.
   The People's Congress of Gansu province in northwestern China
this week passed a law ordering all mentally retarded people who
marry to be sterilized and mentally retarded women who become
pregnant to have abortions, the official People's Daily said.
   The State Family Planning Commission said it was the first law of
its kind in China. It requires sterilization for mentally retarded
people who are already married or planning to marry.
   ``Anyone responsible for allowing mentally retarded people to
give birth will be fined and subject to adminstrative discipline,''
the People's Daily said. ``The mentally retarded lack productive
capability and live on relief funds and grain. They are a great
burden to society.''
   A woman in the Ministry of Public Health's Department for Women
and Children, who refused to give her name, said the proposed
national law would affect people who are mentally retarded due to
hereditary factors, and not those impaired by accidents.
   She said draft work has been in progress for several years. No
date has been set for submission to the National People's Congress,
which must approve all national legislation.
   China has no figures on the percentage of retarded people
nationwide, but a recent survey of children under 14 indicated 1.07
percent were retarded.
   The People's Daily said more than 270,000 people, or about 1.3
percent of Gansu's population, are mentally retarded.
   A report on Gansu radio in July, when the sterilization law first
was proposed, said there was heated argument over the legislation.
Some congress delegates suggested the government first experiment
with such restrictions on a limited basis.
   The People's Daily, which did not mention any controversy, said
the law will ``raise the quality of the population'' in Gansu and
help the arid mountain region shed its traditional poverty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
