<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lisa `Was The World To Me,' Steinberg Writes From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg, accused of killing his illegally
adopted daughter, says the 6-year-old girl ``was the world'' to him
and that her loss is ``more than I can bear,'' New York Newsday
reported today.
   In a one-page letter written in response to questions submitted
by the newspaper, Steinberg also talked about his love for his
longtime companion, Hedda Nussbaum, who is expected to testify
against him in his murder trial when it resumes next week.
   Steinberg, jailed since his arrest in the death of Lisa Steinberg
more than a year ago, wrote by hand, ``My feelings for Lisa are
almost inexpressible.
   ``She was the world to me,'' he wrote. ``Just once, look at her
smile in one of those photographs and you will understand my
feelings. My sadness and sense of loss are more than I can bear at
times.''
   Steinberg declined to answer any questions about the events
leading up to the child's death on Nov. 5, 1987. He wrote the letter
over the objections of his defense lawyers, Newsday said.
   Steinberg indicated that he believes Nussbaum, whom the
prosecution says he allegedly abused physically and mentally during
their 12 years together, has changed.
   ``Regarding Hedda, I must tell you that I loved her very much.
All that has occurred since, has not changed the feeling I held for
her,'' Steinberg wrote.
   ``I can only hope that she is capable of the truth in relating
the events of Lisa's life and the events of Lisa's last night with
us.
   ``Given what I have read, I fear Hedda may no longer be the
person I knew and loved.''
   Steinberg, 47, is charged with second-degree murder and
first-degree manslaughter, stemming from Lisa's fatal head injury.
Although Lisa and another child, now known as Travis Christian
Smigiel, lived with Steinberg and Nussbaum in their Greenwich
Village apartment, they were never legally adopted.
   Nussbaum, 46, has told psychiatrists that Steinberg beat Lisa
into unconsciousness on the afternoon of Nov. 1, 1987, and then went
out to dinner with a friend, sources close to the case have said.
   The sources said Nussbaum told psychiatrists that she heard
sounds ``like Joel throwing Lisa'' in the apartment bedroom, but did
not see the alleged beating.
   Medical aid was not summoned until the following morning, after
Lisa stopped breathing.
   Steinberg told police and paramedics that Lisa had choked on her
vomit after eating vegetables. His attorneys have suggested that
Lisa may have suffered her injuries in an accidental fall or at the
hands of Nussbaum.
   Nussbaum, who has been hospitalized since her arrest on Nov. 2,
1987, is receiving psychiatric treatment at the Four Winds Hospital
in Westchester County. Prosecutors last month dropped all criminal
charges against her.
</TEXT>
