<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CruseLawsuits     11-25 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cruse Lawsuits,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shooting Victims Agree To Cap Damages At $100,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight victims in a 1987 shooting spree
have agreed to seek no more than $100,000 each from Allstate
Insurance Co., which issued a homeowner policy to the accused gunman.
   The cases had been scheduled to go to trial Monday in front of
Circuit Judge John Antoon. However, Allstate contends in a pending
federal suit that the policy doesn't cover William Cruse's actions
on April 23, 1987.
   Cruse, 61, a retired librarian, still faces a criminal trial in
March on six counts of murder, 28 charges of attempted murder and
two charges of kidnapping. More than 100 witnesses are preparing to
identify Cruse as the gunman who strode resolutely through two
supermarket parking lots, shooting an automatic rifle
indiscriminately.
   The central question in the civil case is much the same as a key
question in the criminal case: Was Cruse insane on the day of the
shootings?
   Allstate maintains in its suit that Cruse was sane and that he
knowingly shot at neighbors in his Palm Bay neighborhood and at
people in the shopping centers. As a result, the company said, the
victims pressing the suit should not be able to collect from the
insurance policy.
   Cruse's attorneys hope to prove to jurors that he was insane on
the day of the shootings and therefore have him cleared of the 36
felony charges.
   In the compensation case, the amount each victim will receive is
open to further negotiations with a cap set at $100,000, said Jim
Nance, attorney for the victims.
</TEXT>
