<HEAD>Death Toll In Thai Floods, Mud Slides Reaches 142</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, ``A spokesman...'' to
UPDATE with U.S. relief aid. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``The worst...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week of monsoon rains sent logs and
mud crashing into villages and killed at least 142 people, officials
said today.
   Unofficial counts placed the dead at more than 200, with hundreds
missing and believed drowned or buried beneath mud slides that hit
several villages in southern Nakhon Sri Thammarat province.
   The Interior Ministry said at least 70,000 villagers in 12
southern provinces were left homeless, while extensive damage was
reported to roads, bridges, railways and agricultural land.
   Torrential rains in southeast Asia from Saturday to Wednesday
also were blamed for the deaths of dozens of people in Malaysia and
Indonesia. Flood waters washed out thousands of roads, cut off rail
service and destroyed crops in the hardest hit areas, authorities
said.
   Malaysia's state news agency Bernama reported an improvement in
the flood situation in Malaysia, with no new deaths. Earlier
Thursday, authorities said 27 people died from the storms, 14 in the
worst hit state, northeastern Kelantan.
   A spokesman of the Meteorological Department in Kuala Lumpur, the
Malaysian capital, said the weather, part of the annual Asian winter
monsoon season that lasts from November until March, was among the
three worst this decade.
   Monsoon rains lasting three to 10 days this month have lashed
southeast Asia, southern India and Sri Lanka.
   A spokesman for Thailand's Fourth Army, stationed in the south,
said hundreds of rescue workers today recovered 45 bodies from the
mud slides, bringing to 104 the number of dead in Nakhon Sri
Thammarat. Villagers in some areas were being evacuated by troops to
higher ground.
   The U.S. Embassy today said the U.S. Office of Foreign Disaster
Assistance will give $25,000 to relief efforts.
   The worst hit province recorded 17.5 inches of rain Tuesday, a
single-day record for rainfall since data collection began 38 years
ago, the Meteological Department said.
   The English-language newspaper The Nation reported that the
usually bustling tourist city of Hat Yai was reeling from three days
of flash floods, with many businesses closed and hundreds of
Malaysian and other tourists stranded in hotels ``like prisoners.''
   Food was reported scarce in hotels where water was being rationed
to guests.
   Official Radio Thailand said Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan
planned to fly to the disaster area 490 miles south of Bangkok.
   The army spokesman, contacted by telephone, said mud and logs
rolled off barren hillsides in the province's Phipoon District,
crushing people and slamming into homes.
   An inspector of the Forestry Department blamed the deaths on
``serious wounds on the soil and mountains'' inflicted by
uncontrolled logging and mining.
</TEXT>
