<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Communist Bloc, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Communist South Korea Making Economic Contact With Communist
World</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with agreement between Poland and
South Korea. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The Soviet Union...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staunchly anti-communist South Korea
further expanded its economic contact with communist countries today
by signing an economic cooperation agreement with Poland.
   The pact made Poland the third East European country to conclude
such agreement with South Korea. The others are Hungary and
Yugoslavia.
   South Korea has no diplomatic relations with communist nations
because of its bitter rivalry with communist North Korea. But it has
been seeking non-political contact through business avenues to boost
trade and reduce tension on the Korean peninsula.
   Today's pact was signed in Seoul by Tadeusz Zylkowski, president
of the Polish Chamber of Foreign Trade, and Lee Sun-kee, president
of the Korea Trade Promotion Corp. It calls for the two countries to
cooperate closely for joint venture and other projects.
   They will set up trade offices in each other's capital by the
first half of next year, cooperate for trade exhibitions and
exchange manpower and information on economic development, officials
of both sides said.
   Lee's visit next week to Moscow and Sofia, Bulgaria, is expected
to conclude accords to open trade offices in the Soviet Union and
Bulgaria early next year, Korean officials said.
   The Soviet Union reportedly has approved South Korea's plan to
open trade offices in both Moscow and Vladivostok, an east Asian
Soviet city that South Korea envisions as a window for investment in
the development of Siberia.
   After Hungary became the first communist country to open a trade
office in Seoul last June, Yugoslavia opened a trade office in the
South Korean capital in October.
   South Korea opened trade offices in Budapest, Hungary, last
December and in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, this year.
   South Korea and Hungary also were moving toward closer ties. The
two countries announced in September plans to establish
quasi-diplomatic missions in their respective capitals. Talks on a
bilateral investment guarantee agreement were also due to begin in
Seoul next Monday.
   Career diplomat Han Tak-chae was appointed head of South Korea's
permanent mission, with diplomatic status, in Budapest to oversee
trade, cultural and other non-political affairs.
   Han, commenting on improved relations with communist countries,
said those countries were ``changing their policies toward South
Korea and emphasizing practical and realistic aspects.''
   Trade agency officials said negotiations were also under way to
exchange trade offices with East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   Officials said Seoul already has set up a private business body
to promote trade and investment in China. One recent official report
said Seoul was near an agreement with China to open trade offices
next month in Beijing and Shandong Province, near Korea.
   Trade between South Korea and China was expected to rise to $2
billion this year, up from from $1.5 billion in 1987, trade
officials say. South Korean trade with other communist countries,
however, was still minimal, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
