<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Media     11-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Media,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Returns Credentials of British Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has returned the press credentials of
three British journalists after suspending them last month on
charges the journalists violated military censorship, the reporters
said today.
   The press cards of the three journalists were suspended Oct. 25,
two days after Reuters ran a story saying undercover army units had
orders to shoot Palestinians suspected of organizing violent
demonstrations.
   The army has denied there are any such underground units.
   Andrew Whitley, a correspondent for the London-based Financial
Times, reported on Oct. 11 that undercover units used Arab cars and
posed as journalists to detain suspected rioters.
   Neither story was submitted to the military censor. Under Israeli
law, journalists must submit reports relating to security matters to
the censors. The government has not clearly identified ``security
matters'' and leaves the submission of reports to the discretion of
correspondents.
   The Government Press Office reinstated the credentials of Paul
Taylor and Steve Weizman of the Reuters news agency without
explanation Tuesday, Taylor said. He said he was not told whether a
police investigation of the case had been dropped.
   Whitley said he got his press card back Nov. 6 and was told the
police investigation was closed.
   Yoram Ettinger, head of the Government Press Office, could not
immediately be reached for comment.
   Journalists whose credentials are suspended cannot interview
government and army officials and are banned from covering
government functions.
</TEXT>
