<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Mail Fire,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Suspected in Fires at Mail Sorting Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 firefighters battled for
several hours today to control two separate fires at Europe's
largest mail sorting office. Officials said arson was suspected.
   Two firefighters were hospitalized overnight for smoke inhalation
but the 500 employees who were in the building when the fires broke
out were safely evacuated, said a spokeswoman from the West Midlands
Fire Brigade.
   The spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
blaze was of ``doubtful origin'' and arson was suspected, since it
first broke out in two separate locations at the letter and parcel
sorting office.
   ``It couldn't possibly have happened accidentally,'' said West
Midlands Assistant Divisional Officer John Whitehead, adding ``there
has been a history of small unexplained fires there.''
   The spokeswoman said 25 fire crews from the Birmingham area were
needed to bring the fire under control by about 4 a.m., three hours
after it was discovered. Firefighters were still in the building at
8:30 a.m., she said.
   The spokeswoman said the fire ``severely damaged'' at least a
third of the ground floor of the four-story building.
   Royal Mail spokeswoman Sally Williams said several hundred
parcels were damaged by fire and water, and machines in the
mechanical parcel sorting area, which handles up to 100,000 items a
day, were destroyed.
   Mike Davis of the Birmingham office said sorting would be done by
hand and some mail would be diverted to other offices but operations
at Europe's largest sorting center would be at near-normal speed by
Monday.
</TEXT>
