<2ND_LINE>PM-East-West Trade,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Says East-West Trade Up, Thanks To Better Political Climate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East-West trade picked up markedly this year thanks
to the improved political climate and to economic reform in most
East European countries, a U.N. report said Thursday.
   But the report projects that the Soviet Union and its six East
European allies will register a slight overall deficit in 1988 after
a combined $2 billion surplus last year. While the volume of exports
increased faster than that of imports, the value of imports rose
more quickly, it said.
   The report was compiled by experts of the U.N. Economic
Commission for Europe. Overall figures for the value of the
East-West trade were not given.
   The better atmosphere and the economic reforms have been the
``catalyst for a flurry of contacts, negotiations and agreements,''
the document said. It specifically named large credit facilities
designed to support Western exports to the Soviet Union.
   It said East-West economic cooperation also gained momentum with
a June accord between the Soviet bloc's Council for Mutual Economic
Assistance, known as COMECON, and the European Economic Community,
or EEC. ``This accord .... sets the stage for more intense economic
interchange,'' it said.
   In volume, Soviet exports to the West rose 12 percent during the
first half of 1988 while imports rose 10 percent. But a 23 percent
increase in the value of imports accounted for what the report
called an ``unusually large trade deficit with the West,'' projected
to total $2.4 billion by Dec. 31. Last year, the Soviets ran up a
$800 million surplus.
   In contrast, Moscow's six allies _ Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East
Germany, Hungary, Poland and Romania _ were forecast to keep a
combined $2 billion trade surplus with the West, compared with $1.2
billion in 1987.
   In volume, exports of the six to the West increased 6 percent
while imports stagnated. In value, exports rose 14 percent while
imports were up 11 percent.
   Bulgaria was the most significant exception, according to the
report. Stagnating sales and a continued import boom led to a
Bulgarian trade deficit with the West of $900 million in the first
six months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
