<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhotoMix-up     11-25 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Photo Mix-up,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britons Encouraged to Visit Atlanta, Via Houston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways' in-flight magazine encourages
Britons to beat a path to Atlanta, but it's Houston's skyline that
beckons in the photograph, not the city of Scarlett O'Hara and Ted
Turner.
   An article in Highlife magazine's November edition extolls
Atlanta's virtues: ``It's climate is kindly, it's temperate and
attractive.''
   The Houston photo has publishers stumped.
   ``We wouldn't have asked for a picture of Houston,'' said Rebecca
Francis, an assistant at Headway Publications Ltd. of London, which
publishes about 100,000 copies of the magazine a month for
distribution on the planes.
   She told the Houston Chronicle the mix-up could be a printing
error, but officials would not know until the photos are returned in
``another four weeks.''
   ``That's the first I've heard of it,'' said Robert Harding,
library director of the Robert Harding Picture Library of London,
which is credited with the photo. ``We wouldn't do it intentionally,
that's for sure.''
   ``Oh, that's beautiful,'' British Airway's New York spokesman
John Lampl chuckled when he learned of the error. ``I certainly
don't want to confuse Houston and Atlanta. They are completely
different animals.''
   Ms. Francis said an American reader reported the error several
days ago, but only two complaints had come in. The magazine is
available on non-stop flights between Houston and London.
   In Atlanta, the photo mix-up was a source of amusement for a
Chamber of Commerce spokeswoman who did not want to be quoted by
name.
   ``You're kidding,'' she said when learning of the two-paragraph
article. She recalled that Atlanta and Houston have had somewhat
strained relations ever since the Georgia city beat out the oil city
for this year's Democratic National Convention.
   ``The Houston press was out to get us,'' she said. ``We still
compete for some of the same business.''
</TEXT>
