<HEAD>African National Congress Leaders Meet Churchmen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the African National Congress,
the main guerrilla group in South Africa, today held talks with
Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other South African churchmen on the
future of that country.
   The ANC described the talks as ``very important,'' and the World
Council of Churches called them ``significant.''
   No statement was released on specifics of the meeting.
   The ANC has met with South African church leaders in the past,
and Tutu, a Nobel Peace Prize-winner, has tried in vain to persuade
the group to abandon its policy of violent confrontation with the
state.
   The meeting took place on the last day of a five-day conference
of the church council that focused on the white-led Pretoria
government's destabilization of neighbor states, including Zimbabwe.
   It also came a day after Pretoria announced that Nelson Mandela,
jailed head of the ANC and South Africa's most important black
leader, would not be returned to his prison cell upon his recovery
from tuberculosis at a clinic.
   Mandela, 70, who began treatment for tuberculosis Aug. 1, was
sentenced in 1964 to a life term for sabotage and plotting to topple
the government.
