<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HolidayFiresRdp     11-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holiday Fires Rdp,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thanksgiving Fires Kill Eight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A portable heater was blamed for a fire that killed a
104-year-old woman and a kitchen stove used for heat started a fire
that killed four boys as holiday blazes claimed eight lives around
the country.
   In Lynn, Mass., a woman escorted her six children to the street
Thursday and then returned to her apartment, locked herself in and
apparently set a fire that killed her, fire officials said. The
victim, Evelyn Iliopoulus, had been released Wednesday from a
psychological counseling center, authorities said.
   Fire Chief Edward Higgins said several couches were set ablaze,
and the stove was turned on with flammable items placed on top of
it. The afternoon blaze forced the evacuation of 32 people and two
firefighters suffered minor injuries.
   Two 4-year-olds died in separate Thanksgiving Day fires in Texas,
and at Dunnellon, Fla., a propane heater in a camper exploded and
burned a family of four, police said.
   Fire officials in Alameda, Calif., said a heater started a fire
in a wall in the home of 104-year-old Fong Shee Wong. Her burned
body was found on the floor of the living room, where she slept,
they said.
   Wong's oldest son, Bryant, 64, said his parents came from China
in 1928 and his father owned a Berkeley restaurant until his death
in 1952. His mother had lived alone for the last 20 years, he said.
   ``She was quite a woman with plenty of gumption,'' he said.
   Four boys aged 11, 9, 9 and 8 died and another was seriously
injured when a fire sparked by a kitchen stove ravaged their home in
Camden, N.J., authorities said. It appeared that the stove had been
used to heat the house, they said.
   Officials said they could not determine all of the relationships
among the children and adults said to be living in the house. A
4-year-old boy was hospitalized in serious condition.
   Fire Inspector Paul Escher said Theresa Van Zant, mother of two
of the boys, was in the house at the time but escaped uninjured.
   ``She was screaming `Help, get the kids out,''' said Hector
Palacios, who lives across the street. ``I went out, and there were
flames from the kitchen. There was just smoke, thick, coming from
the front door. She tried to go up to save her kids, but she
couldn't make it up. I tried to go inside ... I went into the living
room, but it burned my eyes.''
   A heater apparently started a fire in the central Texas town of
Comanche that killed one boy and hospitalized his parents and two
younger sisters with severe burns, fire officials said.
   And in the east Texas community of Hemphill, authorities said a
4-year-old boy was killed in a house fire and his brother
hospitalized in the Shrine Burn Center in Galveston.
   At Dunnellon, Fla., the camper heater blast hospitalized John and
Julie Roof in critical condition and their two children were in fair
condition, said Shands Hospital spokeswoman Jennifer Fanzlow.
   ``He was attempting to light it, and it exploded,'' Ms. Fanzlow
said. ``Whether it was a malfunction of the heater or it was his
fault in lighting it, we don't know at this point.''
</TEXT>
