<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     11-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Council Bars Blacks From Public Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The municipal council in the
industrial town of Boksburg has voted to ban blacks from public
facilities that were open to all races for the past few years, a
town official said today.
   Town Clerk Johann Coetsee said the recently elected town
councilors voted 17 to 12 Thursday night to ban blacks from the
municipal lake, swimming pools, town hall and tennis courts.
   About 50 residents attended the meeting in Boksburg, 30 miles
east of Johannesburg. The town has a population of 87,000 whites,
110,000 blacks and 36,000 people of mixed race who live in separate
townships.
   The pro-apartheid Conservative Party gained control of the
Boksburg town council in the Oct. 26 municipal election. The
Conservatives won control of about 100 municipalities in the the
Transvaal and Orange Free State provinces.
   The party does not have control of parliament and cannot reverse
national policy, but it says it plans to institute strict apartheid
in the cities and towns it controls.
   In recent years, white authorities in most areas have been doing
away with segregation of public facilities.
   The Conservative Party has said it would not necessarily call for
reposting ``Whites Only'' signs, but might employ more subtle means
of carrying out its segregation policies.
   Some segregated facilities in South Africa now have the sign:
``Right of Admission Reserved.''
   In Boksburg, the councilors voted to put up ``Whites Only'' signs
at only one public facility, Boksburg Lake, a 37-acre former dam
surrounded by terraces, lawns, gardens and trees.
   Coetsee said that after a fence is erected around the lake, the
signs would be taken down, but the area would remain open only to
whites.
   He said the council majority decided to bar non-whites from using
the town hall because the townships have new community halls that
are ``better than the whites' hall.''
   The town's swimming pool had previously allowed non-whites to use
it only for organized competitions. But the council decided Thursday
that it would be only for whites, except in the case of a non-white
foreigner competing in an international competition in Boksburg.
   The council also rescinded a decision by the previous council
that allowed tennis clubs to have integrated membership if they so
desired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
