<HEAD>French President Arrives in Moscow for Visit, Space Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois Mitterrand arrived today
in Moscow on a two-day visit for talks with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and to witness the launch of a joint Soviet-French space
mission.
   The official Tass news agency said Mitterrand was greeted at the
airport by Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Vice
President Anatoly Lukynov.
   Mitterrand was to meet Gorbachev in the Kremlin, then travel
Saturday to the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Soviet Central Asia for the
launch of a team of Soviet and French cosmonauts for the Soviet's
orbiting Mir space station.
   The team will remain in space until Dec. 21 and is expected to
perform a wide-ranging series of experiments, including continuing
medical and biological tests started in 1982 by the first
Soviet-French space crew.
   Twenty-two years ago France became the first West European
country to sign an agreement with the Soviet Union to cooperate in
space studies.
   Nikolai Afanasyevsky, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, said
Wednesday the Soviets are hoping Mitterrand's visit will help
strengthen Soviet-French dialogue, which he said had ``noticeably
weakened'' in recent years.
