<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-US     11-25 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-US,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Approves Text of New Defense Pact With United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain's Cabinet today approved the text of a
new eight-year defense agreement with the United States that forces
the removal of 72 U.S. F-16 fighter bombers by 1992, a spokesman
said.
   Spokesman Guillermo Una told The Associated Press the Cabinet
approval means the accord will go soon for ratification before
parliament, where the governing Socialist party has a comfortable
majority.
   Spanish negotiator Maximo Cajal and U.S. Ambassador Reginald
Bartholomew signed the texts in Spanish and English on Thursday at
the Foreign Ministry, ending negotiations that began in July 1986.
   The two nations first signed a military cooperation treaty in
1953, during the height of the Cold War under the authoritarian
government of Gen. Francisco Franco.
   In the new agreement, Spain will not receive any U.S. military
aid in exchange for U.S. armed forces' use of two air bases, a major
naval station and nine communications posts.
   In January, both sides reached a tentative agreement for a new
accord in which the United States accepted Spain's principal demand
that the U.S. Air Force withdraw its 401st Tactical Wing of 72 F-16
fighter bombers from the joint U.S.-Spanish air base at Torrejon
just east of the Spanish capital.
   Italy has agreed to provide a new home base for the jets and the
3,600 U.S. troops and 600 civilians attached to the unit.
   The new agreement says no more than 8,000 U.S. troops and 1,000
U.S. civilians employed by the military can be based in Spain at one
time.
   The negotiations stemmed from a 1986 referendum in which Spanish
voters chose to remain in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization on
condition that the U.S. military presence be substantally reduced.
   Two other conditions approved in the NATO referendum were that
Spain prohibit the transport, storage or introduction of nuclear
weapons and that Spain's armed forces remain outside the integrated
NATO military command.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
