<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuriedBodies     11-25 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buried Bodies,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Body Identified in boardinghouse Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have identified a second body
among the the seven found buried in the yard of a boardinghouse,
this time the remains of a man named in the only murder charge
against the home's owner.
   Meanwhile, the national attention given to a 59-year-old Los
Angeles man who helped lead police to the boardinghouse owner
brought about a reunion with three children he hadn't seen in more
than 30 years.
   The body, identified by fingerprints, is Alvaro ``Bert'' Montoya,
a spokesman for the Sacramento County coroner's office who requested
anonymity said Thursday.
   The only other body identified so far is that of 55-year-old
Benjamin Fink, described by his family as a chronic alcoholic and
transient who moved into the home operated by Dorothea Montalvo
Puente earlier this year.
   Autopsies have been completed on the victims, but causes of death
have not been determined. Court documents indicate that one police
search of Puente's home turned up 14 bottles of pills and various
unknown substances.
   Among the items seized were a book titled ``150 Commonly
Prescribed Drugs,'' an 8-inch kitchen knife, a quilt with possible
blood stains, a coffee can with ``lye'' imprinted on the lid and a
book called ``The Smell of Evil.''
   Police believe Puente killed the boarders for their Social
Security checks.
   Social workers and neighbors who reported people missing led
police to question Puente, who was interviewed by police after the
first body was discovered. She was allowed to walk away by
authorities, who said they had insufficient grounds to hold her. She
fled the area, and was captured five days later at a downtown Los
Angeles hotel.
   Sacramento police, using a plane provided by a television station
news department, flew to Burbank, retrieved Puente and returned her
to custody in Sacramento.
   The department's actions in letting her go and then using a TV
station's plane to transport her have been criticized in newspaper
editorials and by Puente's court-appointed public defenders.
   Sacramento Mayor Anne Rudin said late Tuesday that she has asked
the state Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training to
examine the Sacramento department.
   Michael Di Miceli, a commission official, said Wednesday the
review would take 45 to 90 days.
   On Tuesday, police detectives met with Social Security officials
to obtain the records of 16 missing tenants of Puente's
boardinghouse. Police want the payment records of people reported
missing after living at the home, hoping to determine whether their
Social Security checks were improperly cashed.
   Detectives believe the bodies found in the yard may be among
those on the list of names.
   Charles Willgues Sr., who left his wife and three children in
Detroit for reasons the family won't discuss, met a woman he later
recognized as Puente earlier this month in a Los Angeles bar. He
called a television station, and she was soon taken into custody.
   Last week, a television reporter looking for Willgues visited his
previous apartment, and learned that the manager there was holding a
letter for him. The letter was from his daughter, Debbie Sculley.
Just weeks before, she had tracked him to his old address.
   Willgues was soon on the telephone to the Detroit-area city of
Taylor, where his children Charles Jr., 35, Sculley and Linda
Willgues live.
   ``He says, `Hello Chuck?' My jaw just about dropped,'' the son
said Tuesday. ``Then he said, `I don't know where to begin.' And I
said, `I don't either.'
   ``I was just at a loss for words,'' said the younger Willgues.
``I was crying on the phone.''
   After several calls discussing the past, the family now is hoping
to arrange a Christmas reunion.
</TEXT>
