<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SecretClient     11-25 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Secret Client,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Formal Charges Filed Against Restaurateur in Hit-and-Run Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The motorist who ended a 2{-year
controversy over lawyer-client privilege by confessing to the
hit-and-and-run death of a 28-year-old man has been charged with
leaving the scene of an accident involving injury.
   State Attorney's officials charged William D. Morser, a
restaurateur from nearby Delray Beach, on Tuesday with the
third-degree felony charge on which Morser had been arrested earlier.
   Mark Baltes was killed March 9, 1986, when he was struck by a car
on South Ocean Boulevard in Palm Beach.
   The case drew national attention when it was learned that the
driver of the hit-and-run vehicle had hired a lawyer the day after
the accident. That lawyer refused to disclose the name of his
client, citing the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality.
   Morser on Nov. 5 identified himself as the driver and gave a
confession under subpoena, meaning it cannot be used against him in
a criminal trial.
   Morser, 55, said he does not think he can be faulted for his
actions.
   He blamed Baltes for being in the road in the middle of the
night. Baltes, had a blood alcohol level of 0.26 percent, more than
2{ times the legal intoxication level in Florida.
   Morser said he didn't realize he had hit a person until he read a
newspaper the next day. After learning that a man had been killed,
he decided to seek a lawyer's advice.
   In the ensuing months, Morser's attorney, Barry Krischer, refused
to disclose his client's identification despite a lawsuit brought by
Baltes' parents. Last month a Palm Beach County judge ruled that
Krischer could not be compelled to disclose the identity.
   Investigators first suspected Morser two days before his
confession after inspecting his white Buick Riviera, which resembles
the car that struck Baltes. He is free on bond.
</TEXT>
