<HEAD>Three Shot After High School Football Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teen-agers leaving a high school football
game were shot and wounded following an argument, police reported.
   Thursday's shooting reflected the increased access to guns by
students, said Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke.
   ``For some of them, the handgun has replaced the fist as a means
of expressing their rage and frustration,'' he said.
   Four shots were fired from a .25-caliber pistol only 20 yards
from the main stadium gate, hitting one of those arguing and two
bystanders, police said. One victim was in serious condition with
chest wounds but the other two were in satisfactory condition with
minor leg wounds, authorities reported. No arrest had been made.
   At least eight incidents involving firearms have been reported in
city schools since classes began in September, and more than 30
students have been suspended for gun violations.
