<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerDispute     11-25 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Dispute,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Pulls Plug On Cancer Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have pulled the plug on an
experimental radio-wave device intended to heat malignant tumors
inside the body and make them stop growing.
   The Food and Drug Administration said in a letter that
researchers have failed to prove the device works on tumors deep in
the body or that it is safe for patients and technicians.
   Researchers responded that 10 years of research has shown that
the heat treatment, while not a cure, often relieves patients' pain
and extends lives, the Los Angeles Times said.
   ``There is no scientific basis whatever for what the FDA has
done,'' said Dr. F. Kristian Storm III, chairman of surgical
oncology at the University of Wisconsin, Madison.
   Storm, who helped design the device, has been testing it with the
assistance of 12 researchers at nine institutions, including the
University of California, Los Angeles.
   In a letter dated Oct. 6, Robert Sheridan, acting director of
FDA's Office of Device Evaluation, told Storm the government was
withdrawing approval of the so-called magnetrode hyperthermia system
concentric coil applicator.
   The letter said researchers have failed to monitor patients'
internal temperatures during treatments and that the device could
leak ``potentially significant levels'' of radiation.
   The Times quoted unidentified researchers as saying they have
told the FDA they would monitor the temperature of tumors and
internal organs during initial treatments but are unwilling to do so
on a repeated basis during follow-up treatments because the probes
are potentially hazardous to cancer victims.
   The manufacturer of the system, Henry Radio and Henry Medical
Electronics Inc. of Los Angeles, acknowledged there is potential for
radiation leaks, but insisted such leaks fall within established
safety limits and that all technicians take precautions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
