<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HomeSales     11-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Sales,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Sales Fall Despite Slight Decline In Mortgage Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes fell for a second
straight month in October even though mortgage rates declined
slightly during the month, a real estate trade group reported today.
   The National Association of Realtors said existing single-family
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63 million
units last month.
   The 1.1 percent October decline followed a similar 1.1 percent
September drop. Sales had been up 2.2 percent in August after
falling 4.5 percent in July.
   The pattern of declines in three of the past four months
indicated that sales have cooled, analysts said.
   ``The summer rush is over, and despite the window of opportunity
afforded by low mortgage interest rates in October, the surge of
home sales we saw earlier this year has run its course,'' said John
Tuccillo, the Realtors' chief economist.
   Tuccillo predicted that sales for all of 1988 would be very close
to the 3.5 million homes sold for all of 1987.
   The decline in sales was accompanied by a small drop in prices.
The median cost of an existing home sold in October was $88,100,
down $100 from the September level. However, the price was still 4.1
percent higher than a year ago, when the median home price was
$84,600.
   The weakness in October reflected a 2.9 percent drop in sales in
the West, which fell to an annual rate of 700,000 units. This offset
a 2.2 percent rise in home sales in the Midwest, where the annual
rate edged down to 960,000 units.
   Sales in the South were unchanged at 1.39 million units, but this
represented an increase of 8.6 percent from a year ago, reflecting
perhaps some improvement in depressed conditions in the oil belt.
   Sales in the Northeast were also unchanged at an annual rate of
650,000 units.
</TEXT>
