<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0534,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet's Family Tomb Bombed On His 73rd Birthday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile-Military, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with damage less extensive than
director thought, security at cemetery. Pickup 6th graf pvs,
``Leftist extremist...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blast today damaged the family tomb
of military President Augusto Pinochet on his 73rd birthday.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack, which
marred a day of ceremonies in homage to the right-wing leader.
   The bomb went off just behind the tomb shortly after 10 a.m. at
the city's General Cementery, about 20 blocks north of downtown
Santiago, cementery director Arturo Urrutia told The Associated
Press.
   The explosion shattered stained glass windows, religious icons
and flowerpots in and around the concrete-walled mausoleum.
Reporters who went to the site also found that several nearby crypts
also were damaged.
   Urrutia first said the explosion blew open the steel doors of the
mausoleum, but the damage turned out to be less extensive than he
thought.
   A second bomb was found and defused by police explosives experts,
according to security officials at the scene. They said the
mausoleum is guarded around the clock, and that the bombs apparently
were planted when a police guard briefly left his post to visit the
cementery's offices.
   Leftist extremist groups have been active in Chile since the
early 1980s, occasionally attacking military and political targets.
   Pinochet, who was born Nov. 25, 1915, seized power in a bloody
1973 coup that toppled an elected leftist government. In October, he
lost a referendum on extending his rule eight more years and is
obliged to call open elections, planned for December 1989, to pick a
successor.
   The president began his birthday celebrations in the central port
city of Valparaiso with a serenade from a military band in front of
his residence. He later went to the presidential palace, where
military and government officials paid him homage and a folk group
performed traditional dances.
</TEXT>
