<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ThanksgivingRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0464 11-25 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thanksgiving Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bounty Of Food, Good Will On Thanksgiving Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after the 5th to update with reference to
Soviets not allowed into home Thanksgiving dinners.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans shared a bounty of food and good will Thanksgiving Day,
offering plates heaped high to thousands of needy as descendants of
American Indians and Pilgrims recalled the spirit of peace that
prevailed at the first Thanksgiving.
   Football games and parades also captured the attention of
millions of spectators and television viewers on Thursday's holiday.
Parades featuring towering cartoon-character balloons, opulent
floats and miles of marching bands streamed through the streets of
New York, Philadelphia, Detroit and Houston to herald the start of
the holiday season.
   Of course, Americans sat down at family dinner tables to feast on
the traditional turkey, cranberry sauce, stuffing and gravy while
offering thanks.
   President-elect George Bush and his wife, Barbara, spent a quiet
Thanksgiving at their seaside vacation home in Maine; President
Reagan and his wife Nancy gathered with relatives and friends in
Santa Barbara, Calif.; and Vice President-elect Dan Quayle had a
quiet dinner with his family in Indiana.
   Soviet inspectors in this country monitoring compliance with a
U.S.-Soviet nuclear weapons treaty could not do the same because,
under a Defense Department security policy, they cannot accept
invitations to private homes.
   But six members of the Soviet team assigned to the Hercules Inc.
aerospace plant in Magna, Utah, attended services at the First
Presbyterian Church in Salt Lake City, then sat down to a
traditional Thanksgiving dinner at the church.
   Team spokesman Vladimir Zhukov said it was the group's first
Thanksgiving and he pronounced the holiday ``uniquely'' American.
   Rosemary A. Holt, president of Women Concerned About Nuclear War,
said the rules against home visits ``thwart the development of
better relations between our two countries and encourage the old
mentality that `we need to have an enemy.'''
   Thousands of needy people packed shelters and restaurants across
the country to dine on free hearty meals and enjoy the holiday's
good cheer.
   ``Thank God for places for this,'' said Henry Scott, a homeless
man dining at the Masonic Temple in Paterson, N.J. ``I'm making it
by the skin of my teeth. I'm trying not to resort to being
incarcerated.''
   In San Francisco, about 7,200 people, served by 600 volunteers,
feasted on a traditional holiday meal at the Glide Memorial United
Methodist Church, which has served Thanksgiving dinner to the needy
for 15 years.
   The Rev. Cecil Williams said the turnout was the largest ever and
had more women and children than past years. Women and children made
up about 35 percent of Thursday's turnout, compared with about 20
percent last year, Williams said.
   In Scott, Ark., residents gave thanks just to be alive following
a spate of deadly tornadoes last week that ripped across the state,
killing six people, three from Scott.
   Suzy Cotham's country store near the Lonoke-Pulaski county line
opened its doors Thursday to scores of residents whose homes and
businesses were swept away by the twisters.
   ``You don't realize how people are until something like this
happens, and then you find out they do have a heart, even though
they act tough and everything,'' said Mrs. Cotham.
   Homer Adams, 28, herded his three small sons to a table. ``We
would have been without Thanksgiving if not for all this,'' he said.
   Besides the spirit of giving, Thanksgiving also provoked a sense
of reconciliation between descendants of American Indians and
Pilgrims who gathered at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in New
York.
   ``What we are doing tonight is an act of deep respect and deep
affection between the people who came to this country and the people
who were there first,'' said the Rev. James Parks Morton.
   Chief Oren Lyons of the Onondaga tribe said he attended ``to join
in this celebration of reconciliation, to bring spirituality back
into Thanksgiving, and to bring people together in the way that it's
supposed to be.''
   About 12 tribes from 20 states were represented in the crowd of
4,000. The event ended when the participants joined hands in a
circle dance of friendship.
   On a lighter note, hundreds of high school bands struck up a
brisk tempo for parades across the country, with most of the major
events coming off without a hitch.
   In New York, Snoopy, Woodstock and the Pink Panther and other
giant helium-filled balloons flew alongside 24 floats, 14 marching
bands, hundreds of clowns and 400 cheerleaders at the 62nd annual
Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade.
   In Detroit, about 900,000 spectators turned out for a parade
featuring clowns, floats and marching bands. In Houston, parade
organizers said they were thankful for the good weather that brought
a record turnout.
   But in Philadelphia, a feisty 75-foot-tall Olive Oyl balloon
refused to stand up for the parade. With the help of about a dozen
handlers, she eventually rose for the occasion to join that city's
69th annual Thanksgiving Day parade, the nation's oldest.
   ``She looks like the rest of us this morning,'' said Dori Hall,
37, who helped raise the Popeye cartoon character. ``I was thinking
I didn't want to get up either.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
