<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Soviet Magazine,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Germany Defends Ban of Soviet Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's government Friday defended its
banning of a reformist Soviet magazine, charging the publication
contains articles that distort history.
   ``Distorted portrayals of the historical achievements of the
Soviet people, spread in East Germany, are unacceptable in view of
our friendship with the Soviet Union,'' said a commentary in the
East German Communist Party organ Neues Deutschland.
   The banned magazine Sputnik contains a selection of articles from
the Soviet press. Recent issues have included frank appraisals of
the Stalin era, along with letters and commentaries critical of
Kremlin politics.
   Its ban has provoked public protest. Witnesses reported East
German security officials arrested a man who held up a handmade
poster protesting the ban and demanding freedom of the press.
   Radio Moscow on Tuesday defended the magazine in a
German-language commentary heard in Berlin, saying the publication
``mirrors a plurality of opinion in the Soviet press.''
</TEXT>
