<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Protest     11-25 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Protest,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>400th Anti-Nuclear Protest in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atomic bomb survivors and other Hiroshima residents
Friday held their 400th protest against nuclear testing,
participants and city officials said.
   Protest leader Ichiro Moritaki said about 150 people demonstrated
in silence for an hour in Hiroshima's Peace Memorial Park,
protesting nuclear tests this past week by France and the Soviet
Union.
   The park is near the spot where a U.S. atomic bomb exploded in
1945, killing an estimated 140,000 people and destroying much of the
city.
   City officials said it was the 400th such protest since 1973,
when residents began demonstrations against every announced nuclear
test by any nation.
   To mark the 400th protest, the group adopted a statement calling
for nuclear disarmament and an end to nuclear testing, Moritaki
said. It will be sent to governments of Britain, China, France,
India, the Soviet Union and the United States.
   The United States dropped the bomb on Hiroshima in the closing
days of World War II. Three days later, about 70,000 more people
died in a second U.S. atomic attack on the city of Nagasaki, also in
southwestern Japan.
</TEXT>
