<HEAD>Round Table For Talks Dismantled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers have dismantled a specially built
round table that was to have been used for discussions between the
government and opposition, the government said Friday.
   ``The table could not be blocking a room where different meetings
and symposiums are usually held,'' said Zbigniew Augustynowicz, of
the government press office.
   He said the table could be reassembled quickly if the talks are
rescheduled.
   Last week, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Interior Minister
Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak failed to reach agreement on holding the
talks, but agreed to continue contacts with the goal of bringing
their positions closer together.
   A Communist Party source, who demanded anonymity, said this week
the talks were not expected to take place before February, after a
major party conference on ideology.
   Kiszczak and Walesa had agreed to the talks Aug. 31 during
Poland's worst labor unrest in seven years. They are supposed to
cover broad social questions, including Solidarity's future and
economic and political pluralism in Poland.
</TEXT>
