<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistClan     11-25 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Clan,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Polygamists' Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in the murder
trial of three members of a polygamist clan accused in the killing
of a law enforcement officer during a 13-day standoff at the clan's
farm.
   John Timothy Singer, 22, Addam Swapp, 27, and his brother,
Jonathan, 21, are charged in the Jan. 28 death of state corrections
Lt. Fred House.
   Some 200 potential jurors showed up at the North Summit
Elementary School to be interviewed by attorneys and 3rd District
Judge Michael Murphy. About 50 members of the original jury pool of
250 already have been disqualified because of illness or other
insurmountable problems, said Detective Sgt. Robert Berry of the
Summit County sheriff's office.
   Jury selection was moved to the school, where tight security was
enforced, because there was insufficient room to seat all the
potential jurors at the Summit County Courthouse, Berry said.
   House was shot as police moved in to end the standoff. He was
urging a police dog to attack the Swapp brothers when he was hit,
and prosecutors contend the wheelchair-bound Singer fired the fatal
shot. Investigators testified he told them he was firing at the
police dogs.
   The clan had holed up on the farm at Marion, in northeastern
Utah, after bombing a Mormon chapel, an act Addam Swapp said had
been ordered by God as a sign of impending collapse of the Mormon
Church and all government. He said it would trigger the resurrection
of John Singer, the father of John Timothy Singer and of Swapp's two
wives.
   The three defendants and Vickie Singer, 45, widow of John Singer,
were convicted in federal court on charges stemming from the bombing
and standoff. Addam Swapp was sentenced to 15 years in prison, Mrs.
Singer to five years and Jonathan Swapp and John Timothy Singer to
10 years.
   Jonathan Swapp was married Tuesday in a civil ceremony at the
Summit County Jail, his attorney, Earl Spafford, said Wednesday.
Swapp married Ann Eaton, 20, Salem, Utah, who first saw him on
television and then attended the federal court trial.
</TEXT>
