<HEAD>Crew Stops Flooding Aboard Sinking Spanish Trawler</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with sinking vessel stops flooding. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two helicopters and two ships rushed to assist a
Spanish trawler that sprang a leak off Britain today, but the 15 men
aboard the striken vessel managed to stop the flooding themselves,
officials said.
   The Punta Purras Tarri sent a mayday call this morning that its
engine room was flooding and it was in danger of sinking 250 miles
southwest of England.
   Two Royal Navy Sea King helicopters from the Royal Naval Air
Station Cludrose on the Lizard, in southwest England, were sent to
the rescue along with a Polish ship in the area, the British coast
guard said.
   The helicopters, operating near the outer range of their limits,
landed on the fleet support ship Argos until the trawler's skipper
declared the emergency over, said a coast guard spokesman, who by
custom was not identified.
   Another Royal Navy ship, the Avenger, was sent to the trawler's
aid with a special pump and the Polish ship was standing by until
another trawler arrived later in the day to escort the Punta Purras
Tarri back to the Spanish port of La Coruna, the spokesman said.
   The mayday call was picked up by Spanish-speaking operators at
Valentia radio station in the Irish Republic which broadcast an
all-ships alert.
</TEXT>
