<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--MercyKilling     11-25 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mercy Killing,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Gets Suspended Jail Term For Attempted Mercy Killing of Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DORDRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman found guilty of trying to
kill her comatose son by cutting his throat with a razor blade got a
one-year suspended prison term, a court spokesman said Friday.
   In court earlier this month, the woman admitted that in February
she tried to cut the neck artery of her 20-year-old son, Patrick,
who has been unconscious for 16 years since he fell through ice in a
pond.
   The mother was identified only as Philippine G., 44, in line with
Dutch judicial practice.
   The court recognized that the woman, who said Patrick's suffering
had become ``intolerable,'' acted out of compassion, the spokesman
said.
   Although euthanasia is banned, an estimated 5,000 cases occur
annually, according to the Netherlands' Royal Medical Association.
   Recently, Dutch courts have meted out only token sentences to
doctors under unofficial guidelines permitting euthanasia at the
explicit request of a patient if a terminal illness causes
``unbearable suffering.'' The Dutch government is preparing to
legalize this.
   But the Dordrecht court noted the woman lacked medical training
and her son did not ask to die.
</TEXT>
