<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Bush-Tate     11-25 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Tate,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Press Secretary Leaving After Transition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheila Tate, George Bush's campaign
and transition press secretary, said Friday she has taken herself
out of the competition for the same job in the Bush White House.
   ``I found myself in almost a permanent bad mood, thinking about
what did I want to do,'' Tate, 47, said in a telephone interview
from transition headquarters in Washington.
   ``I talked to members of my family, and I just had a reluctance
to give up the good personal life,'' she said. ``I worked in the
White House for four years. I do not want to go back.''
   Tate succeeded Peter Teeley as Bush's campaign press secretary
six months ago, giving up a public relations executive's job with
the Washington firm of Hill & Knowlton, to do so.
   There had been rampant speculation that Tate, who served as press
secretary to first lady Nancy Reagan during President Reagan's first
term, would be named by Bush as White House press secretary.
   No woman has ever held that position.
   Asked if she felt her decision to withdraw would have the effect
of ensuring that the job go to a man, she said, ``There are plenty
of qualified women ... so I don't take it upon myself that it is
less likely.''
   Bush had said that he wants to bring more women and minorities
into high-ranking government positions. Among the names mentioned as
possibilities for the press secretary's job are Tom DeFrank of
Newsweek magazine and Teeley.
   There also has been speculation that Bush was prepared to offer a
high-profile job to Bernard Shaw, a Cable News Network anchorman who
is black.
   Tate said that her husband, William, ``was willing to have me do
whatever I wished,'' but said that she had found the campaign and
transition press secretary's work very demanding. She said her son,
Hager, is a senior in high school and that she and her husband are
building a new home in McLean, Va.
   Tate said she informed Bush of her decision on Wednesday _ the
same day that the president-elect announced the selection of retired
Air Force Gen. Brent Scowcroft as his national security adviser.
   She said that he did not try to talk her out of it. ``He asked me
my thought processes. We talked for about 10 minutes.''
   She said they reminisced about ``the wars we'd been through. He
understood my concerns and we left it at that.''
   Tate is the second key Bush aide to announce departure plans.
Craig Fuller, who had been Bush's chief of staff for the past four
years, said last week that he would be leaving once his work as
co-director of the Bush transition office is complete in January.
   ``We're both old faces, and why not get some new faces?'' Tate
said.
   She said that Bush ``will find the best people for the jobs and I
know that a lot of them will be women and a lot of them will be
minorities.''
   She said that she and Fuller, and others who may not be remaining
for the Bush administration, ``share, above all else, a desire that
George Bush succeed.''
   Tate said she believes that Bush has a good attitude about the
role of the press in American life, and predicted that he will be
regularly available to reporters.
   ``He's made no commitments on (the number of) press
conferences,'' she said. ``But all you have to do is watch how he
has conducted himself (during th transition period) to see that he
recognizes the critical role of the press.''
   ``I don't think the press is going to have any complaints about
George Bush's accessibility,'' Tate said.
</TEXT>
