<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 11-25 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0571,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crashes Kills Five</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with plane's point of origin Las
Vegas, not Prescott, Ariz., picking up 5th graf pvs, ``It was ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CORTEZ, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small airplane crashed into a ravine in
this southwestern Colorado city, killing the four adults and one
child aboard, authorities said.
   In the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, six people survived when
their aircraft ran out of fuel and crashed.
   Cortez Police Chief Roy Lane said the Cessna 210, first reported
to have come from Prescott, Ariz., originated in Las Vegas, Nev. He
said the plane touched down as late as 3:30 p.m. Thursday in
Blanding, Utah.
   Priscilla Anderson, a spokeswoman for the National Transportation
Safety Board in Washington, D.C., said the plane was en route to
Durango.
   Lane said there was no indication from the crash that the
airplane was trying to land at the Cortez airport, which is about
four miles from the crash site.
   ``It was snowing real hard and there was fog (at the time),''
Lane said. ``Nobody actually saw the crash, several people heard
it.''
   The victims were identified as pilot William Robinson, 44; and
passengers Duane Robinson, 20; Paul Robinson, 23; Gloria Robinson,
22, and Sulinda Robinson, 5. All were from Las Vegas, Nev., said
Assistant Police Chief Russell Johnson, but he didn't know their
relationship.
   The Kass family from Okemos, Mich., waited six hours to be
rescued after their Piper Cherokee ran out of fuel and crashed in a
remote area in northern Michigan Wednesday.
   ``When the engine did stall, there was a feeling of helplessness.
I didn't think it would be a survivable crash,'' said David Kass,
30. Kass, wife Karol, 28, their two children, her brother and the
plane's pilot were flying to Hancock for a holiday feast with
relatives.
   Bruised and shaken, they sent up flares, built a bonfire and
shivered around it during their six-hour wait for help.
   Fog, wooded terrain, marshland and nearly impassable logging
roads delayed rescuers for six hours, said Marquette County
Sheriff's deputies. The plane crashed about 11 miles west of
Marquette County Airport.
   The plane was en route from Lansing to Houghton, but was diverted
to Marquette because of dense fog, Sheriff's Deputy Lawrence Sanders
said.
   Kass, his wife, and their 6-year-old daughter, Kristina, were
hospitalized while the others were treated and released.
</TEXT>
