<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cambodia     11-25 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cambodia,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Condemns Khmer Rouge Treatment of Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department condemned on Friday what
it described as the forced relocation by Khmer Rouge rebels of
innocent Cambodian civilians out of Thai-based refugee camps to
areas close to the Cambodian border.
   About 8,000 Cambodians were moved out of the Ta Luan camp,
controlled by the Khmer Rouge, in July and August and there have
been similar forced movements of additional Cambodians from other
camps more recently, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   Most of the remaining 2,000 or so refugees still at the Ta Luan
camp are aged or infirm, he said.
   ``We condemn this forced relocation of innocent civilians from
the relative safety of U.N.-assisted camps to more remote areas
subject to cross border shelling and lacking the necessary
facilities for the provision of essential services,'' Redman said.
   The United States has urged the Thai government to use its
influence to encourage more responsible, humane actions on the part
of the Khmer Rouge and it has done so, Redman added.
</TEXT>
