<DOCNO> AP881125-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionTrends     11-25 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Trends,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Abortions Held Steady During First Half of 1980s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of abortions in the United States each
year is holding steady, according to the latest figures Friday from
the Centers for Disease Control.
   The CDC said 1,328,570 legal abortions were performed in the
United States in 1985, the latest year for which statistics are
available; that's ``virtually no change'' from 1984, when 1,333,521
legal abortions were performed.
   In 1985, as in previous years, the typical woman obtaining an
abortion in the United States was young, white and single, with no
children.
   The 0.4 percent decline in 1985 is the second drop in abortions
reported by the CDC.
   Abortions rose from a reported 22,670 in 1969, when the CDC's
record-keeping began, until 1982, then dropped 3 percent in 1983.
The number rose 5 percent in 1984.
   ``Since 1980, the abortion numbers ... appear to be relatively
stable, with minor year-to-year fluctuations,'' the Atlanta-based
health agency said.
   Dr. Hani Atrash, a CDC researcher, cautioned that states are not
forced to report each abortion as they are required to do with
certain diseases, so the numbers may not be precise.
   Women under age 25 made up 61 percent of all women having
abortions in 1985, the CDC said. Sixty-seven percent were white, 81
percent were single and 57 percent had never given birth to a live
child.
   In 1972, when the CDC began tabulating detailed characteristics
of women having abortions, 65 percent were under 25, 77 percent were
white, 70 percent were single and 49 percent had never given birth
to a live child.
   The CDC cautioned that the number of states reporting such data
varies from year to year, and trends based on the information
``should be viewed with caution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-25 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want a romantic winter evening? Turn up the
lights.
   That's right, brighter.
   There's a hormonal link between light and wintertime blues that
include a seasonal loss of sexual desire, says Professor Russel J.
Reiter of the University of Texas Health Science Center.
   As the daylight hours grow shorter, so, too, does sexual desire
in nearly 5 million Americans affected by the hormonal changes,
Reiter said. But cravings for starchy foods, frequent mood swings,
depression and lethargy increase.
   Reiter said lower light levels force a tiny pine cone-shaped
pineal gland located under the brain to produce a hormone called
melatonin, which can plunge a particularly sensitive person into
depression and shut down his sexual responses.
   Similarly, the lengthening daylight of springtime has the
opposite effect on the melatonin cycle, shutting down the pineal
gland sooner and turning on sexual desire.
   Reiter said seasonal affective disorder is more common in
Northern states where winter days are much shorter than the normal
10-hour Texas days. He said women are four times more likely to be
affected than men.
   The common treatment is sitting in a brightly lit room in the
morning for up to two hours, Reiter said.
   ``The bottom line is that light is a drug that can have
significant impact,'' said Reiter. ``What I'm more interested in is
sex _ scientifically speaking, that is.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NAPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranchers who want to know if their llamas are
going to be mamas are keeping the pregnancy testing lab busy at a
California hospital.
   Queen of the Valley Hospital performs up to 600 llama pregnancy
tests a month for breeders as far away as Louisiana, Texas and
Canada, said Glenn Lee, head of outpatient laboratory services.
   The hospital, in Napa about 40 miles northeast of San Francisco,
estimates it now performs five times as many tests for llamas as it
does for humans.
   ``We're the llama pregnancy factory of the world,'' said Lee.
   Llamas, pretty-eyed, long-necked members of the camel family, are
popular as pets and pack animals. With baby llamas selling for
$10,000 or more, people who raise the creatures like to know as soon
as possible when their animals are expecting.
   The hospital began doing the tests in 1982, when a local
physician who raises llamas asked if the lab could run a test on one
of his animals. Word of the lab's services spread among breeders,
and what began as a favor soon became a business that offers llama
breeders the same-day testing and notification it gives to its human
patients.
   ``This has to be one of the more unusual outpatient services,
said Kirkwood Reid, the llama-raising doctor. ``But it's very
successful. The Queen is probably the country's No. 1 pregnancy
testing laboratory.''
</TEXT>
