<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pinochet     11-25 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pinochet,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Birthday Marred by Tomb Bombing, Pinochet Says Will `Go Away
Quietly'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet celebrated his 73rd
birthday Friday, although the festivities were marred by the bombing
of his family tomb, and he said he will ``go away quietly'' when his
presidency ends in 1990.
   The right-wing army commander who seized power in a 1973 coup was
feted throughout the day by military and government officials as
well as civilian supporters.
   In brief remarks to reporters, Pinochet reflected on the upcoming
end to his rule and said he will step down as scheduled in March
1990.
   ``I will go away quietly,'' he said, ``as did Venancius in Rome,
a general who after combat went to the countryside to till the
soil.''
   Pinochet lost an October referendum on extending his presidency
eight more years, and is obliged to call open elections, planned for
December 1989. He is to hand power over to the winner on March 11,
1990.
   At the city's General Cemetery, about 20 blocks north of
downtown, a bomb exploded beside the Pinochet family tomb during the
morning, authorities said. No injuries were reported and no one
claimed responsibility. The blast shattered stained-glass windows,
religious icons and flower vases in the concrete-walled mausoleum,
and also damaged other nearby crypts.
   A second bomb was found at the site and deactivated by police,
security agents said.
   Pinochet's birthday ceremonies began with a serenade by a
military band and congratulatory speeches by army officers at his
residence in an eastern suburb of the capital. Dozens of civilian
supporters also were gathered outside the house, cheering and
applauding.
   At midmorning, Pinochet went to the presidential palace, where
members of his Cabinet and other aides paid him homage and a group
of children performed folk dances.
   A group of communist activists opposed to his rule tried to enter
the palace to give him a bicycle as a birthday gift, but were
blocked by guards. An argument ensued and one of the activists,
Javier Saez, was detained by police.
   During the referendum campaign, Pinochet announced a plan to
provide workers with bicycles at reduced prices. The program was
lampooned by the opposition.
</TEXT>
