<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Prince 1stLd-Writethru a0591 11-25 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Prince, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0591,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oldest Surviving Son of Saudi Founder Dead at Age 80</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-3 to raise first full reference to king, make
clear prince is his son.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Mohammed, eldest brother of
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and a warrior who played an important part
in the conquests of his father, the late King Abdel-Aziz Ibn Saud,
died Friday at the age of 80.
   The Royal Court proclaimed the death to the nation and said the
prince would be buried Saturday.
   The conquests of the prince's father led to the overthrow of
Turkish domination from the preceding century and the unification of
most of the Arabian peninsula in 1932 into what is now Saudi Arabia.
   The Al-Saud dynasty does not pass on the rule by primogeniture,
but an inner circle of the family selects kings and crown princes
whenever needed.
   In Saudi Arabia, Mohammed was dubbed the ``maker of kings''
because he declined the crown in favor of King Faisal upon the
downfall of his half-brother, King Saud, in the early 1960s.
   He also refused the throne in favor of another half-brother, King
Khaled, after the assassination of Faisal in 1975.
   Mohammed, the eldest of the surviving sons of the founder of the
Saudi monarchy, was also called Abu Al-Sharrain, or father of two
evils, because of his fiery temper. He remained the most respected
personality in the house of Al-Saud and even the kings used to refer
to him to settle domestic disputes.
   In July 1977, Mohammed ordered the execution of his granddaughter
Princess Mishael and her lover, Khalid Muhallal, a nephew of the
then-Saudi ambassador to Lebanon.
   The execution was ordered by Mohammed for adultery, as Mishael
was married to a royal cousin. She was shot and he was beheaded. The
executions caused a stir in Western Europe and the United States and
were the basis for a widely watched British TV show, ``The Death of
a Princess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
