<DOCNO> AP881125-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1542EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElNino     11-25 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-El Nino,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Underwater Lava Flows May Cause Droughts, Typhoons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Nino, the warming of Pacific Ocean
waters blamed for droughts, typhoons and storms worldwide, may be
caused by undersea volcanic lava flows, says a study by the U.S.
Geological Survey.
   The lava from rifts in the ocean floor may bring about the
dramatic changes in sea temperature, air pressure, winds and
currents that characterize the phenomenon, according to the study
the current issue of EOS, the publication of the American
Geophysical Union.
   El Nino, from the Spanish for ``the child'' because the event was
noticed to occur around Christmas, caused staggering economic damage
on four continents in 1982-83. It occurred again in 1985-86 on a
lesser scale.
   Herbert R. Shaw and James G. More of the Geological Survey in
Menlo Park speculated that flows erupting through rifts in the
earth's crust transfer much of their intense heat to ocean currents
flowing around the equator.
   According to the theory, the warming of the water causes a drop
in air pressure at the ocean surface that in turn weakens or even
reverses the normal east-to-west trade winds.
   The overall result is a drastic alteration of normal weather
patterns and an abrupt halt to the upwelling of cold currents that
carry rich nutrients from the sea bottom to the surface along the
coast of South America.
   Scientists have been unable to predict when the weather
disruptions will return, but they seem to occur every three to seven
years with varying degrees of impact and can last up to two years.
   The 1982-83 El Nino wiped out fisheries in Peru and Ecuador,
touched off searing drought in Australia and southern Africa and
typhoons in Tahiti and caused unusually violent rainstorms in
California and abnormally wet winters in the Southeast.
   Both the 1982-83 and 1985-86 occurrences did major harm to
fishing off the West Coast.
   The Pacific Rim is one of the most active seismic regions in the
world. Recent underwater lava flows discovered near the Hawaiian
Islands cover nearly 9,000 square miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0109 </DOCNO>
