<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0600 11-25 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0600,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paratroopers Sentenced To Jail For Camp Rampage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Soldiers opened ...'' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with four more wounded. Pick up 4th pvs, ``At least ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one paratroopers have been sent to jail
for up to two weeks each for smashing cars and windows in a rampage
at a Palestinian refugee camp, the army said Friday.
   An Israeli officer was quoted as telling a military court in Gaza
City that four soldiers standing trial for the beating death of a
Palestinian from Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp were following orders.
   Soldiers opened fire on stone-throwing youngsters in two Gaza
Strip refugee camps, wounding a 14-year-old in Nuseirat and a
16-year-old in Bureij, Arab hospital officials reported. They said
both suffered head wounds and the older boy was in serious
condition. A 14-year-old Arab was wounded in the Deir el-Balah camp,
hospital officials said.
   In the West Bank, three Arabs were wounded, two in the city of
Nablus and one in the Tulkarm refugee camp, hospital officials said.
   At least 315 Palestinians have been killed and more than 7,000
wounded since an uprising against Israeli occupation began in the
West Bank and Gaza on Dec. 8, 1987. Eleven Israelis have been slain.
   The paratroopers sentenced to jail attacked the Kalandia refugee
camp north of Jerusalem after their bus was stoned Sunday night. At
least four cars and 20 houses were damaged.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, army chief of staff, said there was no
excuse for the rampage. He noted that the paratroopers had attended
an officer-training course and thus belonged to the military elite.
   ``The incident had nothing to do with a misunderstanding of
orders,'' Shomron said on Israel radio. ``The army insists that
orders be carried out exactly.''
   Standing orders allow soldiers to use force in catching rioters,
but prohibit them from beating people or damaging property once a
protest has been dispersed and rioters are in custody.
   An army spokesman said the paratroopers were given jail sentences
Thursday of one to two weeks and three sergeants received two-week
sentences, with a further two weeks suspended. The squadron leader
was given a two-week sentence Tuesday.
   Legislators from both left and right criticized the decision.
   Yuval Neeman of the right-wing Tehiya Party said the soldiers
should be pardoned and Israel should consider itself at war with
Palestinian activists.
   Ran Cohen of the left-wing Citizens Rights Movement said
politicians who block peace initiatives should be blamed, not
soldiers facing an impossible situation in the occupied lands. Cohen
is a paratroop reserve officer.
   The military trial of the four soldiers involves the death of
Hani el Shemi, 43, on Aug. 22 in Jabaliya.
   A report by the newspaper Hadashot quoted Lt. Rafil Tawil as
telling the court: ``The order to beat Arab rioters came straight
from the commander of the Gaza Strip, Brig. Gen. Zvi Poleg, and the
soldiers were carrying out the spirit of the order.''
   Haim Teferberg, a soldier and witness, said El Shemi was taken to
the military base in Jabaliya, accoring to a report in the newspaper
Haaretz.
   ``He was hunched over as he walked and blood was dropping from
his mouth,'' it quoted Teferberg as saying. ``I saw him up close.
They put him into the camp. His breathing was heavy. He kept saying,
`I want to die.'''
   ``When they put him on the floor I saw a soldier ... run quickly
toward him and kick him, as though in a karate move. After that he
no longer had a pulse.
   ``This is customary. Many soldiers beat up prisoners,'' he was
quoted as telling the court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
