<DOCNO> AP881125-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TreeFarms     11-25 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tree Farms,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yule Trees Sprout Among Palms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLANT CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yule trees are sprouting among the palms
in central Florida, where Christmas tree farms are a growing
business.
   The 9-year-old Florida Christmas Tree Growers Association has
grown from 23 to nearly 300 members in eight years, said Roger Webb,
associate professor in the University of Florida forestry department.
   Still, 750,000 Christmas trees are brought into the state from up
North, while only about 50,000 trees are grown and sold in Florida,
mostly in state's midsection, a fertile belt with bountiful
citrus-producing groves.
   ``We still play second-fiddle to the northern Christmas tree
industry. We still have lots of room to grow in Florida,'' Webb,
head of the Live Oak Reserve Center for research in Christmas trees,
said recently.
   Most of the farms _ which average five to seven acres _ are in
small towns near metropolitan areas.
   ``If you're going to have a Florida Christmas, you're going to
have to buy a Florida Christmas tree,'' said Fred Lloyd, who has
been growing Christmas trees for four years in Plant City, about 20
miles east of Tampa better known for its winter strawberry harvest.
   Lloyd and other farmers experiment with growing trees like the
Virginia pine in Florida. But there's also the scrappy native
Florida sand pine, the lush, aromatic red cedar and the Leyland
cypress.
   For $20 to $30, customers at Lloyd's farm can cut their own
8-foot red cedar and take it home.
   Like the Lloyds, many tree farmers are longtime farmers who added
Christmas trees to help shore up incomes. Others are retirees or
businessmen who grow trees in their spare time.
   Webb says growing trees requires diligence, hard work and usually
a minimum of four years before a farmer sees any return on his
investment.
   ``Out of 100 (interested) people, we might get five that end up
in Christmas tree production,'' he said. ``Nobody gets rich quick.
But people in the business _ once they have really gotten into the
business _ sell everything they have.''
   Large, well-established farms gross as much as $37,000 in the
three-week season beginning with the weekend after Thanksgiving,
Webb said.
   With regular trimming, the trees generally assume the conical
shape of the traditional tinsel bearers.
   But particularly in a state where the industry is in its infancy,
there are some that fall victim to the tree-trimmer in training.
   ``Last year, some of my trees looked like telephone poles,''
Lloyd said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
