<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sharansky     11-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharansky,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharansky Criticizes Israeli Intolerance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky on
Friday lashed out at what he called intolerance among Israelis of
differing beliefs, saying such attitudes endangered the nation's
existence.
   Sharansky, who arrived in Israel in 1986 after being imprisoned
for nine years in the Soviet Union, singled out the mistrust between
religious and secular Jews which escalated after four religious
parties won unprecedented political power in the Nov. 1 elections.
   ``It seems that we need a cataclysmic war to concede the
communality of our destiny,'' Sharansky wrote in an article
published in the English-language daily Jerusalem Post.
   To illustrate the point, he recalled that when he first arrived
in Israel, people speculated that his wife, Avital, would force him
to wear the skullcap worn by observant Jews. Mrs. Sharansky is
observant, while he is not.
   ``The gossip lost its humor for me when I began to realize that
it contained disbelief in our ability to live happily together
despite our different customs,'' wrote Sharansky, who during his
long imprisonment became a symbol for the struggle of Soviet Jewry.
   Sharansky said a stranger recently congratulated him for not
wearing a skullcap.
   ``I felt even my own bald pate was being conscripted into service
in a `kulturkampf' (cultural struggle). My `supporter' was not
interested in my soul-searching. He was only interested in knowing
if I was on his side or theirs,'' he wrote.
   Sharansky, 40, also cited the practice by Soviet authorities of
placing prisoners of radically different backgrounds in the same
cell to break their spirits.
   ``Our only recourse was to ... be as tolerant as possible of each
other and unite against the common enemy,'' Sharansky wrote.
   He said such unity was rare in Israel.
   ``We are so inured to self-hatred, so accustomed to our own
anti-Semitism, that when it raises its monstrous head, it hardly
raises a ripple,'' Sharansky wrote.
   He also expressed disillusionment with Israel's political system
after participating in free elections for the first time in his life.
   The election gave the right-wing Likud bloc 40 seats and the
rival Labor Party 39, with the rest going to small rightist, leftist
and religious parties. The result has been a flurry of political
bargaining as Likud tries to form a coalition government.
   Sharansky said all parties had shown their readiness to sell out
in exchange for a place in the new government.
   ``Principles were being auctioned off with dizzying dispatch. It
was not a pretty sight,'' wrote Sharansky, who despite overtures
from many political leaders has not joined a party.
   Sharansky suggested that electoral reform might alleviate some of
those problems, but added that ``ultimately, it will be our ...
ability to see ourselves in every face around us ... which will
truly bring us to the promised land.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
