<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     11-25 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Accord Mediator Removed From Political Settlement Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. diplomat who mediated the Afghan
accords will no longer try to arrange a political settlement in
Afghanistan because the Moslem guerrillas refuse to talk to him, a
U.N. official said Friday.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani noted this year's U.N.
resolution on Afghanistan asked Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar to promote formation of a broad-based government, a task
envoy Diego Cordovez was striving toward.
   The secretary-general is handling that duty, and Cordovez will be
limited to supervising the 50-man team of U.N. military observers
monitoring the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and checking
violations of the accords.
   The United Nations is trying to help establish a government of
national reconciliation in order to protect Afghan communist
officials after all the more than 100,000 Soviet troops are
withdrawn in February.
   Cordovez had been promoting a government in which President Najib
would step down in favor of a coalition led by the deposed Afghan
king and former officials in exile.
   The plan saw no role for the Islamic insurgents, who call
themselves the mujahedeen, or holy warriors.
   Earlier this month mujahedeen leaders announced they would not
deal with Cordovez, and they have vowed to fight on and oust Najib
and his government, whom they call ``traitors'' and ``Russian
agents.''
   Najib has refused to dissolve his government to make way for a
coalition, but has offered to incorporate opposition members into
his administration.
   Perez de Cuellar is expected to wait and see how upcoming
discussions between the mujahedeen and Soviets on the repartriation
of prisoners of war turn out before offering any new proposals, said
officials.
   Cordovez, a former U.N. undersecretary-general who resigned
several months ago to become Ecuador's foreign minister, mediated
the Afghan accords that were signed April 14 in Geneva.
   The accords call for Afghanistan and Pakistan not to interefere
in each others' internal affairs, and for the Soviet troops to be
out of Afghanistan by Feb. 15. Half the Red Army pulled out by Aug.
15.
   The Soviet Foreign has announced a suspension of further
withdrawals due to attacks by the mujahedeen and alleged Pakistani
violations of the accord, but has said it hopes to complete the
pullout on schedule.
   On Monday, U.N. officials announced a reorganization of senior
diplomatic and peacekeeping duties at the world body, under which
Perez de Cuellar assumed personal responsibility for all major
diplomatic activity.
</TEXT>
