<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DinnerForum     11-25 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dinner Forum,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Revives Century-Old Intellectual Tradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carpenters, farmers and a Pulitzer
Prize-winning poet have revived the century-old dinner forum that
once brought to this little town 115 miles from Boston such
intellectuals as Booker T. Washington.
   Some 150 residents came to Town Hall last weekend to eat pumpkin
pie and baked chicken and listen to former U.S. Poet Laureate
Richard Wilbur read a poem dedicated to the fire chief.
   It was the first such forum since Charles Eliot Norton, founder
of The Nation magazine, and other distinguished visitors dined with
local residents and held forth on such subjects as democracy and
education every August from 1879 to 1903.
   ``We are fortunate and grateful for the kind of history we've
had,'' organizer Susan Todd said. ``Education is a valued thing in
our community and we don't have to fight for that. We don't have to
fight to let new people in town have a role in our society. Our past
made that possible. That's why we did this dinner.''
   The original Ashfield dinners were held by summer residents
Norton and George William Curtis, an author and editor of Harper's
Weekly. They were attended by the likes of poet James Russell Lowell
and novelist William Dean Howells.
   ``For a few days each year it was the cultural center of
America,'' said Donald Robinson, professor of government at Smith
College.
   The dinner conversations were spirited, he said. When the United
States entered the Spanish-American War, Norton and other speakers
denounced what they considered U.S. imperialism in the Philippines,
Robinson said.
   When Norton retired and the dinners stopped, the Boston Herald
eulogized the gatherings as ``occasions of national importance.''
   Mrs. Todd, a third-grade teacher, began organizing Sunday's
revival dinner six years ago. Town Hall's steeple was mended by
volunteers, and townspeople donated their Sunday-best china and
silver.
   Teen-agers and college students cooked and served the meal to
local carpenters, electricians, farmers, selectmen and many others
sitting on benches used at the original dinners and refurbished for
the occasion.
   The price of the dinner was kept at a low $5 to encourage
townspeople to attend, and the cost was underwritten by a $500 gift
from a photographer.
   Wilbur, who lives in nearby Cummington, dedicated ``A
Fire-Truck'' to the Ashfield fire chief, who bent the rules to allow
candles on the tables.
   Mrs. Todd said she hopes to make the dinner a yearly event for
everyone in the western Massachusetts town of 1,500 and surrounding
communities, not just such local literary lights as Wilbur, novelist
Noah Gordon and her husband, Richard Todd, a Houghton Mifflin editor
and editorial director of New England Monthly magazine.
   ``It was very democratic,'' she said of the original dinners.
``Everybody came.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TribunePrinters     11-25 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tribune Printers,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribune Accepts Strike Settlement with Printers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Tribune said Friday it has agreed to a
settlement involving cash buyouts and lifetime annuities for union
members who walked out three years ago over work rules in the
newspaper's composing room.
   The Tribune accepted the settlement, worked out under the
guidance of former U.S. Labor Secretary W.J. Usery, on Thursday,
four days after Chicago Typographical Union members approved it in a
180-43 vote.
   The settlement, backed by an $8.56 million fund, was sent for
review to Morton Bahr, president of the Washington-based
Communications Workers of America, the parent body of the printers'
local, a newspaper spokesman said.
   When the strike began 40 months ago, 240 printers walked off the
job in a dispute over company moves to gain greater control over
hiring and assignments in the composing room.
   Under the agreement, 119 printers who have remained on strike
will have the option of a buyout or a lifetime annuity, as well as
company-paid medical insurance. Fifty printers who remained at the
newspaper since a 1986 unconditional offer to return can stay, or
can each accept a $30,000 cash buyout.
   The printers agreed to drop a lawsuit in federal court that
claimed the company violated a 1975 agreement in which members were
guaranteed lifetime employment in exchange for the introduction of
labor-saving technologies.
   The agreement does not affect sympathy strikes by mailers and
pressmen whose unions remain involved in lawsuits and proceedings
before the National Labor Relations Board.
</TEXT>
