<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NameSharing     11-25 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Name Sharing,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Stops Name Change On License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Joseph Sexton and Beth-Anne Thye
were married, they promised to love, honor and respect each other.
But the respect part of the vow, which they agreed to seal by
sharing surnames, has not been easy to fulfill.
   The University of Florida law students are challenging the state
Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles for not allowing him
to combine his surname with hers on his driver's license.
   ``Basically what my wife could do for free I would have to go out
and hire an attorney to do,'' he said, ``and that's what struck me
as wrong with the whole system.''
   A 1952 Florida Supreme Court decision allows a name change only
with a court order, which he estimated would cost $200.
   But officials stand behind the policy that allows women to change
their names when they marry, but requires men to have court orders.
   ``You must admit that it is a custom of the American way of
life,'' said Glenn Blocker, assistant director of the division of
driver's licenses. ``It's been with us for eons, centuries.''
   A second couple has challenged the policy as sex discrimination.
   Michael and Susie Boydston-White of Tallahassee sued Nov. 15 in
Leon County circuit court, claiming the policy is unconstitutional
because it allows women a courtesy not provided to men.
   The Thye Sextons, who initiated their challenge in July, have a
hearing Tuesday before the Division of Administrative Hearings.
   Before their Aug. 8, 1987, marriage, Sexton and Thye decided to
take each other's surname out of respect. When they returned to
Gainesville from their wedding, the couple went about getting legal
papers changed to their new name.
   Sexton said he had no trouble changing his Social Security card,
voter-registration card, bank identification, real-estate license
and school records.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
