<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Official Connected to U.S. Agent's Murder Released From
Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police commander sentenced to
four years in jail for allowing the alleged killer of a U.S. drug
enforcement agent to flee has been released after 36 months, a news
agency reported.
   Armando Pavon Reyes left a Guadalajara prison Thursday,
accompanied by his brothers, according to the Excelsior News Agency.
   Pavon Reyes was federal judicial police commander in Guadalajara,
322 miles west of Mexico City, when Drug Enforcement Administration
agent Enrique Camarena Salazar was abducted by gunmen within sight
of the U.S. Consulate there Feb. 7, 1985.
   He was convicted of taking a $300,000 bribe so reputed drug
kingpin Rafael Caro Quintero could escape aboard a private jet
despite U.S. officials' pleas for his detention.
   DEA agents at the airport said Caro Quintero gave Pavon Reyes a
farewell embrace while surrounded by a score of bodyguards. It was
the last seen of Caro Quintero until he was arrested April 4, 1985,
in Costa Rica.
   Pavon Reyes was fired shortly after reports surfaced about the
airport incident. When he surrendered to authorities, he said he was
innocent of the charge and claimed he did not even know Caro
Quintero.
   Camarena's badly beaten body was found March 5 buried in a
plastic bag on a ranch 60 miles southeast of Guadalajara, along with
the body of a Mexican pilot working with him who had been kidnapped
the same day elsewhere in Guadalajara.
   Pavon Reyes was among nearly 40 people arrested in the case in
April 1985.
   Caro Quintero was sentenced in September to 34 years in prison on
other charges in Mexico City. The sentence was handed down the same
day a U.S. federal jury in Los Angeles found former Mexican
policeman Raul Lopez Alvarez guilty of killing Camarena. Lopez had
been a state judicial policeman on the homicide squad in Guadalajara.
</TEXT>
