<HEAD>Hirohito Weakening, Slept Most of Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, weakening progressively after
being bedridden for more than two months with internal bleeding,
slept most of Friday and did not speak to visitors, palace officials
said.
   The 87-year-old emperor's anemia remained severe despite blood
transfusions Wednesday and Thursday, said a palace official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said Hirohito only moves his hands and feet and hardly speaks.
Two doctors and three nurses attend him always.
   The emperor has received nearly 44{ pints of blood _ more than
five times the normal amount in his body _ since his condition
worsened Sept. 19.
   Palace officials have refused to comment on reports that the
emperor has cancer.
