<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hungary     11-25 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Say Political Reform Will Not Get Short Shrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government won't neglect political
reforms despite the heavily economic background of new premier
Miklos Nemeth and economic reform theorist Reszo Nyers, officials
said Friday.
   Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz, who relinquished his
additional post as premier Thursday in favor of the 40-year-old
Nemeth, said the new team would be better able to manage the reform
program of austerity combined with economic and political change.
   Nyers, 65, was appointed to the newly created post of minister of
state for economics.
   He and minister of state Imre Pozsgay are two of the most adamant
proponents of reform in Hungary's communist leadership. Pozsgay
reported to parliament Thursday on planned political reforms,
indicating he will take charge of this area.
   At a news conference Friday, he denied political reforms have
taken a back seat to necessary economic changes.
   He said the draft of a new constitution which may allow for a
multiparty system, could be ready in six months. But it cannot be
adopted until 1990 to allow for broad social debate, he said.
   In an interview with the government daily newspaper Magyar
Hirlap, Nemeth said recent lessening of tension between the
superpowers created ``favorable conditions'' for Hungary's reforms.
   ``This is a rare, fortunate moment in history when both our
allies ... and the other side ... are taking an interest in the
success of the Hungarian reform policy,'' Nemeth told the daily.
   ``In this changing Europe we live in, we have to emerge as a
country which promotes the overcoming of the continent's divide
without any local tensions,'' he said.
   Under Grosz, Hungary's leadership has been grappling with
unpopular reforms to revive the stagnating economy and curb a $17
billion debt.
   Nemeth, like Grosz, would like to see the development of what the
leadership calls a ``socialist market economy.''
   Nyers, considered the pioneer of economic reforms in the 1960s,
was returned to the country's top leadership last May after being
ousted from the ruling Politburo in 1974.
   Grosz told Western and Hungarian journalists in an impromptu
interview Friday that he supports both men wholeheartedly.
   He described Nemeth, who spent a year at Harvard University in
the mid-1970s, as ``a gifted young man and outstanding economist.''
   Asked why the second post was created and why Nyers lost his bid
challenging Nemeth for the premiership, Grosz said the two would
complement each other in a way impossible in the reverse
constellation.
   ``You cannot imagine the amount of drudgery the premier faces
around the clock,'' Grosz said. ``There is little time to deal with
theory.''
   He described Nyers as a ``farsighted'' scholar, who for 20 years
has dealt with theory rather than day-to-day work.
   Grosz, 56, said he hoped Nemeth would bring in ``young people
capable of taking on burdens,'' preferably those in their 30s.
</TEXT>
