<2ND_LINE>AM-Onassis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0598,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christina Onassis Funeral in Cathedral Her Father Helped Build</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 13th pvs `Her father established...' to correct
spelling of Liechtenstein.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEA SMYRNI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and relatives sobbed
uncontrollably Friday at the funeral of Christina Onassis in the
cathedral her father, Aristotle, helped to build.
   A cross of pink roses in the name of her 3-year-old daughter,
Athena, adorned the casket. The young girl did not attend the
45-minute Greek Orthodox liturgy for the shipping heiress, who died
Nov. 19 in Buenos Aires at age 37.
   Fifteen priests and bishops officiated at St. Fotini cathedral,
which was packed with about 500 friends and relatives.
   Athena, the child of Ms. Onassis and former husband Thierry
Roussel, was said to be staying with relatives somewhere in
Switzerland, unaware of her mother's death. The body arrived on a
chartered airliner Thursday via Switzerland.
   An Argentine coroner said in a preliminary report that Ms.
Onassis died of a pulmonary edema, or buildup of fluid in the lungs
at the home of her friends Alberto and Marina de Doderos.
   Argentine authorities have not dismissed the possibility of a
drug overdose because pills, which have not been identified, were
found in her bedroom.
   Roussel, who was Ms. Onassis' fourth husband, stood alone behind
the flower- covered casket flanked by her close friends and
relatives. They were married in March 1984 but she began divorce
proceedings eight months later.
   Priests with gray beards and golden robes chanted ``Eternal Be
Your Memory'' as they circled the closed mahogany casket trimmed
with silver. An all-male choir accompanied the chanting priests from
behind screens.
   Shipowners, government ministers and former business associates
of her father were present in the crowded cathedral.
   About 3,000 mourners stood outside in a light rain. Hundreds of
people lined balconies of nearby apartment houses.
   ``Life to you!'' the crowd shouted as white-gloved pallbears
carried the casket from the cathedral behind the cross of pink roses
and a large wreath of chrysanthemums and roses from both Roussel and
Athena.
   All the pallbearers were recipients of scholarships for graduate
study abroad from the Alexander Onassis Public Benefit Foundation,
of which Ms. Onassis was president.
   Her father established the foundation, based in Liechtenstein,
after her brother, Alexander, was killed in an air crash at the
Athens airport in 1973. Half of the $1 billion legacy Aristotle
Onassis left went to the foundation and Ms. Onassis inherited the
rest.
   Ioannis Georgakis, a business adviser to the Onassis family, said
the body was flown to an airport on Greece's northwest coast after
the service and taken by launch to Skorpios, an Ionian Sea island
Aristotle Onassis bought in 1963.
   He said the burial service on the island Saturday would be
attended only by relatives and close friends. Ms. Onassis is to
buried beside her father, who died in 1975, and her brother in the
family mausoleum adjacent to a tiny chapel in the center of Skorpios.
   The chapel was the site of her father's wedding in 1968 to
Jacqueline Kennedy.
</TEXT>
