<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0609,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Exchange to Continue on Saturday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to recast; ADDS two grafs at bottom with Iranian
comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Cross said Friday it is hopeful a 10-day
air shuttle can repatriate more than 1,500 disabled Iraqi and
Iranian prisoners as planned, although the exchange started with
fewer prisoners than expected.
   On Thursday, the first day of the exchange, each side sent back
fewer than half the number of prisoners envisaged under an accord
they signed earlier this month with the International Committee of
the Red Cross.
   Red Cross officials said they were working with both sides to
resolve the problems in the first major exchange of prisoners since
a cease-fire Aug. 20 ended fighting in the 8-year-old war between
the Persian Gulf neighbors.
   The International Committee spoke of a ``setback,'' but spokesman
Juerg Bischof said it is hopeful the goal of returning all sick or
wounded prisoners by the end of the year can be achieved.
   He said Red Cross delegates in Baghdad and Tehran were in touch
with the responsible officials and other contacts were made through
diplomatic channels in an effort to reconcile ``differences of
interpretation.''
   Bischof said plans to continue the exchange Saturday remained in
effect, and ``we hope that this time the numbers of returnees will
be as planned.''
   Under the accord, 115 Iraqis and 41 Iranians are to be
repatriated daily in air shuttles between the capitals, except on
Friday, the Moslem holiday.
   On Thursday, only 52 Iraqis and 19 Iranians were flown home
aboard a DC-9 jet chartered by the Red Cross.
   Iran said 36 of those chosen for the first flight sought or
already had been granted political asylum, and 27 had recovered from
illness and no longer met the criteria for repatriation.
   Iraq accused Iran of reneging on the accord and responded by
reducing the number of Iranians sent home.
   Bischof would not comment on the Iraqi charges.
   He said the accord was based on a list of 1,569 disabled POWS the
Red Cross compiled some years ago.
   ``This old list was the only concrete basis,'' he said. ``At
least it was something to work with, as no other sick and wounded
prisoners have been registered yet by the ICRC. Only if the whole
list has been covered will we be able to say how many no longer met
the criteria for repatriation.''
   All prisoners are examined by a three-member commission _ two
Swiss Red Cross physicians and a local doctor. Subsequently, each
prisoner is asked by a Red Cross delegate, without witnesses, to
make sure he agrees to repatriation.
   Under the accord, both sides agree that Red Cross registration of
all other disabled prisoners can begin Dec. 5.
   ``We have no reason to assume that this date will be changed,''
Bischof said.
   More than 100,000 prisoners of war are believed held by both
sides.
   In Iran, meanwhile, Speaker of Parliament Hashemi Rafsanjani
vowed that Iran would never start a war and warned that his country
must be wary of new attacks by Iraq, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported Friday.
   Rafsanjani, in remarks to a gathering of paramilitary troops in
Tehran on Thursday, said Iraq's commitment to peace was
questionable, the agency reported.
</TEXT>
