<HEAD>Berry Takes Plea; Pays $250 Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock legend Chuck Berry, accused of punching a
woman in the mouth, pleaded guilty to a reduced charge and paid a
$250 fine, officials said Friday.
   Berry, 62, of St. Louis, had been charged with misdemeanor
assault. Marilyn O. Boteler accused him of hitting her at a hotel in
1987, loosening several of her teeth and causing a cut that required
five stitches.
   The nature of the dispute was not disclosed.
   Berry pleaded guilty Tuesday to harassment. He could have
received up to a year in jail and a $1,000 fine if convicted on the
assault charge.
   Ms. Boteler has filed a multimillion-dollar suit against the
singer, composer and guitarist, whose hits include ``Johnny B.
Goode'' and ``Roll Over Beethoven.''
