<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RailroadScandal     11-25 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Railroad Scandal,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scandal Derails Italy's Train Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Italy's state-run railways resigned
Friday during a corruption scandal that prompted a criminal
investigation into the purchase of disposable sheets for sleeping
berths in trains.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said all 14 other board directors of
the system also submitted their resignations.
   Rail chief Ludovico Ligato, who has denied wrongdoing, cited the
criminal investigation as one reason he decided to resign.
   A judicial investigation centers on a $120 million, five-year
contract for supplying disposable sheets. Domestic media dubbed it
the ``Golden Sheets Scandal.''
   Transportation Minister Giorgio Santuz accepted Ligato's
resignation and said he will nominate a special administrator to run
the railroads until a permanent replacement is appointed.
   Eleven people from both the railroads and private industry have
been charged with fraud and corruption in the case.
   Ligato has not been charged but recently received an official
notice from the Rome prosecutor's office he was under investigation
for possible fraud.
   Ligato, 59, was named president of the rail system in 1985. He is
a former member of parliament with the Christian Democrats, Italy's
largest party.
   The case involves a contract awarded in May 1987 to a company
owned by Elio Graziano, who was charged last year with improperly
obtaining funds under a program to rebuild earthquake-damaged areas
near Naples. Graziano was also charged in this case, but authorities
cannot find him.
   Their investigation began after a rival firm complained that all
competing companies were notified too late to submit bids.
   Newspapers say authorities are trying to determine if bribes were
paid for the contract and if other companies were bought off not to
enter bids.
</TEXT>
