<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-25 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Moves Into The Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm over the southern Plains, snow in the northern midsection
and a downpour in southern California added up to an inclement
Friday for much of the nation west of the Mississippi.
   Showers and thunderstorms occurred in Arkansas and parts of
eastern and northern Texas.
   To the north of the low pressure area associated with that storm,
snow fell in western Kansas and Nebraska and in eastern Colorado. An
inch of snow fell at Pueblo, Colo., in the six hour period ending at
1 p.m. EST.
   Winter storm watches were posted for Friday night and Saturday in
eastern South Dakota, extreme southeastern North Dakota and parts of
western and north- central Minnesota.
   Up to 8 inches of snow was expected to pile up by late Friday in
the Arizona mountains. Snow overnight also was forecast in the
mountains and higher elevations of Utah, and light snow fell in
parts of the Pacific Northwest and the Intermountain region west of
the central Rockies.
   Rain soaked parts of southern California and turned to snow in
higher elevations.
   San Diego had nearly three-quarters of an inch of rain in the six
hours up to 1 p.m. EST, flooding streets.
   Wind speeds exceeded 50 mph in the Tehachapi Valley in southern
California. In West Texas, wind gusts were clocked at up to 69 mph
at the Guadalupe Pass on Friday morning, with prospects for gusts up
to 80 mph.
   Temperatures early Friday afternoon were in the teens and 20s in
parts of the northern and central Rockies. Central and eastern
Texas, southern parts of the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf
Coast region and much of Florida had 70s, with 80s in southernmost
Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Jackson, Wyo., to 87 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The
nation's low Friday morning was 11 degrees below zero at Jackson,
Wyo.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
across much of the Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes, the
Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley and the central Gulf Coast. Snow
was predicted for northeast Nebraska, South Dakota, western
Minnesota, the northern and central Rockies and higher elevations of
the central and southern Plateau. Rain was forecast along the
Pacific Northwest coast.
   High temperatures were expected to be 20s in North Dakota and the
northern Rockies, 30s and 40s from the northern Pacific Coast across
the northern and central Intermountain region, the central Rockies,
the central Plains and South Dakota into the upper Mississippi
Valley, with 40s in northern Maine. Highs were forecast to be in the
70s and 80s from south-central and eastern Texas across the Gulf
Coast states and Florida to eastern parts of the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast. The desert Southwest should have 70s, and most of
the remainder of the nation 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
