<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IllegalDominicans     11-25 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illegal Dominicans,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 116 Dominicans Who Sneak Into Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARIO De LEON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Friday they arrested 116
refugees from the Dominican Republic who made the dangerous 90-mile
crossing of the Mona Passage in flimsy boats.
   They said 84 men and 32 women were in the group.
   Thousands of Dominicans enter Puerto Rico illegally each year by
crossing the strip of water that separates their impoverished
Caribbean island from the wealthier U.S. commonwealth of Puerto Rico.
   Authorities said 109 of the refugees were caught Friday and seven
had been apprehended Thursday. Police in helicopters patrolled the
shoreline between Aguadilla, on the western tip of the island, and
nearby Rincon in search of others who may have fled.
   Police said the arrested refugees, aged 15 to 42, were given to
immigration officials for deportation. Authorities said it was the
largest group of illegal Dominicans ever caught in Puerto Rico in
one day.
   The Dominicans pay organizers $500-$3,000 each for a trip on a
``yola,'' the name given the frail boats of aluminum or wood.
   In August, the Dominican navy said one organizer of a trip to
Puerto Rico threw two men overboard, drowning one, when the boat was
detected. In late July, at least seven people drowned and 11
disappeared after their boat capsized.
   Inflation as high as 60 percent and rising unemployment drive an
increasing number of Dominicans to risk the trip in hopes of jobs
and better living conditions in Puerto Rico.
   Because Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens with U.S. passports,
entry to the United States is easier for Dominicans from there.
   Hundreds of Dominicans apply daily for U.S. visas at the U.S.
consulate in the Dominican capital, Santo Domingo. Embassy officials
say they believe about 1 million Dominicans live in the United
States and more than half may be illegal residents.
</TEXT>
