<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Libya     11-25 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Libya,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Says It Will Follow Poison-Weapon Prohibitions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Libyan official told Italian authorities Friday his
country adheres to international rules that prohibit the use of
chemical weapons but not their production, the Foreign Ministry said.
   The United States has said Libya is on the verge of producing
chemical weapons.
   Maj. Abdulsalam Jalloud, considered No. 2 man to Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi, was asked about poison gas production during a
meeting in Rome with Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti, a ministry
statement said.
   Jalloud said Libya adheres to the 1925 Geneva convention, which
bans the use of chemical weapons but not their production and
storage.
   In September, the U.S. State Department said it had evidence
Libya was able to make chemical weapons and was on the verge of
full-scale production.
   Libya has denied the accusation and claimed a new factory,
described in reports as a site for chemical weapons manufacture, is
a pharmaceutical plant.
   Jalloud is the highest-ranking Libyan official to visit Rome
since Libya fired a missile at the tiny Sicilian island of Lampedusa
in April 1986, hours after the U.S. bombing raid on two Libyan
coastal cities. Libya is a former Italian colony.
</TEXT>
