<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition Staff, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0592,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Son, Sununu Work For Free On Transition Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inserts new grafs 7-8, But in, to ADD Sununu offer to Teeter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush's eldest son,
George, and John Sununu, the designated White House chief of staff,
are among those working for free at the transition office, according
to a list released Friday.
   The transition office provided names of the 109 paid staff as
well as some volunteers. All told, 150 people are volunteering. Nine
people have been brought over from the vice president's office to
staff the headquarters.
   The transition's co-directors, Craig Fuller and Robert Teeter,
previously made public the top people in the transition office. The
new list supplements that, and says whether a person is receiving
compensation.
   Some transition staffers have already received appointments to
work in the Bush administration.
   For instance, Ed Rogers and Andrew Card, members of the paid
transition staff who were on the Bush campaign, will work for
Sununu, the retiring New Hampshire governor, in January.
   Fuller, who lost to Sununu in the jockeying to become chief of
staff, said he will return to private business after Jan. 20.
Teeter, a political consultant from Detroit, Mich., has not said
what he will do.
   But in an interview taped Friday for broadcast on CNN's vans and
Novak program on Saturday, Sununu said he had asked Teeter to serve
as deputy chief of staff.
   ``He's considering it and I would hope that he says yes,'' Sununu
said of Teeter, who served as Bush's pollster during the campaign.
   George W. Bush Jr., Bush's 42-year-old son, is serving as a
senior adviser to the transition on a volunteer basis, as is Lee
Atwater, the Bush campaign manager named as chairman of the
Republican National Committee.
   James A. Baker III, a Bush confidant in line to become the
secretary of state, is a paid senior adviser on the transition team.
So is his longtime aide, Margaret Tutwiler.
   Also on the paid staff is press secretary Sheila Tate, who
disclosed in an interview Friday she has taken herself out of the
running for that job at the White House.
   Fred Zeder, a close friend of Bush and one of his campaign
fund-raisers, is another paid senior adviser.
   Among those on the policy development staff is Doug Wead, who
served as Bush's liaison to evangelical groups during the campaign.
   Two of the seven people working in the transition for Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle are volunteers, the office said. They are
Dan Evans, an Indianapolis attorney, and Fred Fielding, a Washington
lawyer. Evans is Quayle's good friend; Fielding is the former White
House counsel in the Reagan administration.
   Congress appropriated more than $3 million for the transition
operation.
</TEXT>
