<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico     11-25 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Runner-Up Calls Incoming Government Illegitimate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, runner-up in Mexico's
disputed presidential race, said Friday that any foreign president
who attends his opponent's inauguration would be supporting an
``illegitimate government.''
   Cardenas spoke at a news conference to introduce the book,
``X-Ray of a Fraud,'' which lists him as co-author.
   ``This book investigates how and why the official results of the
(July 6) election differed from the true vote,'' he said.
   The book says a close analysis of election returns revealed
numerical, logical and statistical inconsistencies which prove that
vote totals were altered fraudulently.
   President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, takes office on Dec. 1.
He offered on Thursday to begin a dialogue with the opposition
National Democratic Front, a coalition of leftist and centrist
parties headed by Cardenas.
   ``There can be a thousand kinds of dialogue,'' Cardenas said
Friday. ``But we will maintain our position that the first objective
must be to discuss ways of restoring legitimacy to the government.''
   He was asked if Cuba's Fidel Castro and Nicaragua's Daniel Ortega
would be giving Salinas the blessing of the international left by
attending the inauguration.
   Cardenas replied, ``We assume they, like any other president, are
coming in accordance with the purposes of their own governments.
   ``It's up to them whether they want to lend support to an
illegitimate government or if they don't want to lend support to an
illegitimate government.''
   He noted that Mexico invited foreign heads of state to the
inaugural for the first time, and said, ``For me, it means that the
government of Mexico is searching with a certain desperation for
foreign support because they don't have enough internal support.''
   In official returns, Salinas received 9,641,329 votes, or 50.36
percent, to Cardenas' 5,956,988, or 31.12 percent. Manuel Clouthier
of the rightist National Action Party got 3,267,159 votes, or 17.07
percent. Minor parties split the rest.
   ``X-Ray of a Fraud'' said a reconstruction of the ``actual vote''
gave the Democratic Front 41 percent, the PRI 36 percent and
National Action 23 per cent.
   The PRI says that while some irregularities did occur during the
election, they did not materially affect the results. It also says
opposition candidates manipulated the vote in some areas themselves.
   ``X-Ray of a Fraud'' tries to track the footprints of fraud,
opposition representatives said in a statement.
   As an example, the book notes that party vote totals in a ward
have a one-in-10 chance of ending in zero, but PRI totals in wards
where the party won by large margins ended in zero far more often.
   ``The statistical odds of that happening by accident are the same
as if you flipped a coin 191 times and they all came up heads,''
said the statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
