<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     11-25 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Leader To Attend Paris Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan will
participate in the next round of peace talks in Paris among warring
Cambodian factions, the guerrilla radio said Friday.
   According to the radio, Khieu Samphan sent a letter dated Nov. 17
to Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the Cambodian resistance leader, saying:
``I am ready to join with all parties in our CGDK (Coalition
Government of Democratic Kampuchea) in the next meeting in Paris at
any time you think suitable.''
   The three-party coalition is fighting the decade-old Vietnamese
occupation of Cambodia. A transcript of the clandestine broadcast
was obtained Friday by The Associated Press.
   In the letter, Khieu Samphan said he will ask Khmer Rouge envoy
Ok Sakun to attend meetings of a working committee established
earlier this month, the radio said. The committee, based in the
former Cambodian Embassy in Paris, is studying political solutions
for Cambodia.
   A three-way meeting of Sihanouk; Son Sann, who leads one of the
three resistance groups, and Premier Hun Sen of Cambodia did not
reach agreement on Cambodia's future at the Nov. 7-8 talks in France
but agreed to meet again early in 1989.
   Sihanouk, who governed Cambodia from 1941-1970, accused Hun Sen
of putting Vietnamese and Soviet interests ahead of Cambodian
concerns.
   The communist Khmer Rouge, the largest rebel fighting force, was
invited to the November meeting but the others rejected Ok Sakun as
its representative.
   The Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia in 1975-79 with a reign of terror
in which more than 2 million people died by execution, famine and
rioting.
</TEXT>
