<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BankScandal     11-25 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Scandal,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Businessman Arrested After Banker Flees Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested multimillionaire
businessman Argyris Saliarelis on Friday on charges that he helped
George Koskotas, the central figure in a major Greek banking
scandal, flee to the United States.
   A federal magistrate in Boston ordered Koskotas held without bail
Friday. FBI agents arrested the 34-year-old fugitive when he arrived
in Massachusetts late Wednesday by private Lear jet.
   Saliarelis, who deals in precious stones and shipping, was taken
into custody in Athens and accused of providing the jet. He said his
two pilots used the aircraft without his knowledge while he was on a
business trip in Africa.
   If convicted, Saliarelis could receive a 10-year prison term.
   Koskotas first fled to Brazil and then to the United States as a
scandal rocked Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist government and
forced two ministers to resign. It prompted a call Friday for new
elections.
   Opposition conservatives claimed that Koskotas was allowed to
escape so he would not implicate top government officials in illegal
financial deals. Magazines and leading newspapers accused
Papandreou's son, Education Minister George Papandreou, of being
involved.
   Koskotas was chairman of the Bank of Crete. A preliminary
government report said he siphoned off $135 million in bank money
into his own accounts and used $200 million more for unsecured loans
and gifts to soccer clubs, athletes, business associates,
journalists and friends.
   The report said Koskotas used bank funds to build up a publishing
empire, including five magazines and three national daily papers.
Later, he bought a controlling interest in an Athens soccer club.
   He was suspended as bank chairman Oct. 20 and charged with fraud
and embezzlement. Koskotas disappeared on Nov.6 while under police
surveillance.
   His lawyer said Koskotas was in Brazil with his wife, a
naturalized U.S. citizen, and their five children but decided to
leave because he believed that Greek assailants tracked him down and
planned to kill him and his family.
   Meanwhile, George Papadimitriou, a former minister of transport
and communications, demanded that the government schedule immediate
elections. He served in the government with Papandreou's Panhellenic
Socialist Movement party.
   In his statement, Papadimitriou said the ``stinking Koskotas
scandal has captivated the ordinary citizens, who ask for a cleaning
up of the situation, while the recent government reshuffle proved a
total absence of sensitivity by certain persons.''
   Papandreou made a minor reshuffle last week but kept all
ministers accused in the scandal.
   General elections are scheduled for June when the government's
four-year mandate expires. Elections can be called earlier if the
governing party chooses.
   Recent polls indicated the scandal has damaged the government's
image for failing to act quickly to investigate.
</TEXT>
