<HEAD>Czechoslovakia's Dubcek Ends Visit To Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLOGNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the ousted Czechoslovak
leader whose 1968 reforms were crushed by Soviet troops, left Friday
for Vienna, Austria, the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
   Dubcek is traveling outside his homeland for the first time in 18
years. He came to Italy on Nov. 11 to receive an honorary degree at
the University of Bologna.
   He left Bologna on Friday aboard a private chartered aircraft,
bound for Vienna, but he indicated earlier he wanted to spend his
67th birthday on Sunday with his family in Czechoslovakia, ANSA
reported.
   Dubcek feared that the government might not let him return after
granting him the travel visa, but it said he will be allowed back.
   As Communist Party leader, Dubcek tried to liberalize
Czechoslovakia's political and economic systems through the
so-called ``Prague Spring'' reforms of 1968. Soviet-led East bloc
troops repressed the movement that same year and Dubcek was
subsequently ousted.
   Dubcek visited Bologna, Rome, Venice and Ravenna and met with
Italian political leaders and Pope John Paul II.
