<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Clan,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Screening Begins For Nearly 200 Potential Jurors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers used a questionnaire Friday to
begin screening 177 potential jurors in the trial of three members
of a polygamist clan who are accused of murdering a state officer.
   State District Judge Michael Murphy told potential jurors who
assembled in a school auditorium that he wanted the case to be in
the hands of the jury by Dec. 20. He warned against contact with
news media and reporters that could influence the potential jurors.
   Addam Swapp, 27, his brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21, and John
Timothy Singer, 22, are charged with second-degree murder in the
Jan. 28 shooting death of state Corrections Lt. Fred House.
   House was directing police dogs in an attempt to capture Addam
Swapp during a 13-day standoff at the clan's farm in Marion. The
standoff was triggered by the Jan. 16 bombing of a nearby Mormon
chapel.
   During the standoff, Addam Swapp said the bombing had been
ordered by God as a sign of impending collapse of the Mormon Church
and all government. He said it would trigger the resurrection of
John Singer, the father of John Timothy Singer and of Swapp's two
wives.
   The 25-page, 276-question questionnaire asked potential jurors
whether they were active members of the Mormon Church, and whether
they, their relatives or acquaintances associate with any organized
polygamous group.
   ``I don't want a jury who may be accused of compromising their
decision because of their community or church ties,'' said Earl
Spafford, one of the defense attorneys who planned to cull the
survey for jurors who should be dismissed.
   The three defendants and Vickie Singer, 45, widow of John Singer,
were convicted in federal court on charges stemming from the bombing
and standoff.
</TEXT>
