<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RideCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0617 11-25 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ride Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0617,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ride's Paint-Covered Crack Cause of Carnival Accident,
Investigators Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The ride' to CORRECT name of company to
Eyerly.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack that would have been nearly
impossible to detect by normal inspection methods used on traveling
carnival rides appears to have led to the collapse of a ride in
which a teen-ager was killed, state officials say.
   An inspection of the ``Monster'' ride Thursday at the Broward
County Fair found that one of its six metal arms had collapsed at
the spot of a tiny crack that went unnoticed in previous inspections
because it was painted over, said Wally Rich, director of the
state's Bureau of Fairs and Expositions.
   Rust under the paint indicated the crack had been there for some
time, he said Friday.
   The broken section was sent for detailed study by a metallurgist
at Florida Atlantic University.
   ``This ride has been inspected in four states in the past two
months by four inspectors, and in that time, no one found that crack
_ neither the inspectors, nor the staff operating the ride,'' Rich
said.
   Wednesday's collapse at the fair killed a 17-year-old high school
senior and injured seven other fairgoers. One remained in a hospital
Friday.
   The ride was built in 1975 by Eyerly Aircraft Co., of Salem,
Ore., Rich said. He said the company went out of business ``about
three years ago,'' but that a new company formed by the owner of
Eyerly still supplies replacement parts for its rides.
   Each arm of the ride supports four baskets that hold up to three
people each and whirls them up and down.
   Rich said the ride at the Broward fair had been subjected to a
thorough inspection in Anderson, S.C., on Sept. 14. Inspection each
day at the Broward fair also showed no signs of negligence or
improper inspection, Rich said.
   Rich said his department hoped to get a final report from the
university on the cause of the accident in two weeks.
   ``We haven't found any area of negligence,'' Rich said. ``There's
nothing we can really put our finger on. We're not technical
experts.''
   Rich said his department's six inspectors would be hard put to
give frequent, exhaustive tests to the state's 1,161 licensed
carnival rides.
   ``It would be almost impossible for us to carry out a program of
that magnitude,'' Rich told reporters at the fairground.
   Product Safety Investigator Jeff Simon of the federal Consumer
Product Safety Commission said he had been assigned to the case but
declined to discuss his own investigation.
   Fair official Kieth Hessey said expressed concern for the
families of the victims, but said the fair would remain open through
Sunday, completing its scheduled run.
   On Friday, fair operators put up a Ferris wheel on the spot where
the Monster had stood.
</TEXT>
