<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 2041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran     11-25 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Agrees To Rights Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Friday that it would allow the
first visit to the country by U.N. human rights investigators next
month, a move seen aimed at countering reports that it has launched
a wave of executions.
   The General Assembly is scheduled to vote next week on a
resolution that strongly criticizes Iran for blocking a probe of
alleged human rights abuses.
   The U.N.'s special monitor on human rights in Iran, Reynaldo
Galindo Pohl, issued a preliminary report in early November that
condemned Iran for executing large numbers of opposition members
after accepting a cease-fire with Iraq.
   Galindo and his staff from the Special Commission on Human Rights
have never been allowed to visit Iran and rely on reports in Iranian
and Western media and testimony from defectors and opposition
members.
   Iranian U.N. Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said his
country would prefer a resolution with milder language, one that
would call for Galindo to ``receive full cooperation of the
government of the Islamic Republic of Iran in all respects before
the end of 1988, for the purpose of carrying out his mandate.''
   On Wednesday, Ambassador Michael Costello of Australia, one of
the sponsors of the resolution, called upon Iran to ``give a clear,
unconditional and public indication of its readiness to allow a
visit (by human rights investigators) within a specified period.
...''
   Mahallati replied Friday, ``I have delivered today, in no
uncertain terms, what the sponsors in the draft resolution ... have
called for.''
   He said Iran's cooperation with Galindo would refute claims of
execution and torture that were made by the People's Mujahedeen of
Iran, an opposition group.
   Mahallati contended that Iran had been preoccupied by its war
with Iraq, and only now has been able to spare time to respond to
international criticism.
   He said Iran's administration of justice has been ``the most
lenient'' of any country that has gone through a revolution and
subsequent war, and that ``the members of opposition groups, however
violent, are entitled to due process of law. ...''
   The Iranian envoy said Galindo's previous report relied on ``the
People's Mujahedeen Organization, a terrorist organization, (and) is
filled with the bogus allegations leveled against the Islamic
Republic of Iran with clear malice, purely political and propaganda
objectives.''
   Galindo's interim report cited mass executions in Iran from July
through September that included 1,140 political prisoners, as well
as other common criminals.
   The executions followed a July 25-28 raid into Iran by the
National Liberation Army, the armed wing of the People's Mujahedeen,
and Iran's acceptance in mid-July of a cease-fire with Iraq. The
truce took effect Aug. 20.
</TEXT>
