<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Rights     11-25 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Rights,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,000 Protest in Rare, Authorized Rally for Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 Chileans chanted slogans, sang
protest songs and waved banners on Friday at the first human rights
demonstration allowed in 15 years of rule under military President
Augusto Pinochet.
   The protesters in this capital city passed out pamphlets and
displayed banners declaring ``Enough of Impunity'' and ``They
Torture In Chile; We Demand Justice.'' They chanted, ``Trial and
punishment now!''
   About 30 women wore photographs pinned to their bosom, of sons or
husbands who disappeared after arrest.
   Groups of human rights victims and their relatives organized the
event. They are demanding that when Chile returns to civilian rule,
authorities prosecute military and police officers accused of human
rights atrocities.
   Elections are planned for December 1989 to pick a successor to
Pinochet, the right-wing general who last month lost a referendum on
extending his presidency eight more years.
   Many local Roman Catholic leaders and opposition political
leaders have said they do not favor prosecution of the military.
They argue it could endanger the transition to democracy in Chile,
where the defense forces are apt to remain powerful.
   Pinochet seized power in a 1973 coup that toppled the elected
leftist government of President Salvador Allende, a Marxist.
   Human rights groups say about 700 people later disappeared and
thousands were arrested and tortured in a military-led wave of
anti-leftist repression.
   Municipal officials granted permission for Friday's
demonstration. While authorities had allowed some political and
labor rallies in recent months, they had never before authorized a
protest by human rights groups.
</TEXT>
