<HEAD>Engine Shutdown Forces San Francisco-Bound Eastern Plane to Turn
Around</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines jetliner bound for San Francisco
returned to Miami International Airport shortly after takeoff Friday
when one of the L-1011's three engines shut down, a control tower
supervisor said.
   The pilot radioed that he was coming back because of an engine
failure, said Rory Reed, control tower supervisor.
   About 25 minutes into the flight, the pilot reported an oil light
on and that engine No. 3 had shut down as a result, said Eastern
spokeswoman Virginia Sanchez.
   ``This occasionally happens and usually just requires a change of
(an oil) filter,'' said Ms. Sanchez. ``If there's no (other) problem
... you can turn that around fairly quickly.''
   The 78 passengers and six-member crew aboard non-stop Flight 501
waited while the plane underwent maintenance, she said.
