<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Politics     11-25 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Politics,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Pro-Aquino Party Takes Full Control of Lower House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate president accused a new
political party backing President Corazon Aquino of ``dictatorship''
on Friday after it cemented control of the lower house by stripping
non-members of committee chairmanships.
   The legislative revamp by the majority Struggle of the Democratic
Filipino Party on Thurday had been expected since the party was
launched in September. It represented the latest step in a
realignment of forces that helped topple President Ferdinand Marcos
in February 1986 and catapult Mrs. Aquino to power.
   ``This is one-party dictatorship,'' Sen. Jovito Salonga said in a
radio interview Friday. ``They have committed an act of injustice in
the House (of Representatives).''
   Committee chairmanships in the House were previously apportioned
to members of a six-party, pro-Aquino coalition regardless of
individual party affiliation.
   The new party, its ranks swelled by defections from other
parties, controls at least 145 of the 202 House seats. In the
reshuffle, it stripped other parties of nine chairmanships and took
control of the House's 45 committees.
   House Speaker Ramon Mitra and Rep. Jose Cojuangco, Mrs. Aquino's
politically powerful brother, said in creating the new party that
they wanted to bring all Aquino supporters under one umbrella to
boost her programs.
   Mrs. Aquino herself refuses to join any political party.
   ``The LDP now assumes full responsibility for the success or
failure of the legislative program of the government,'' Mitra said
using the party's Tagalog language initials.
   Salonga said he would not retaliate by calling for a similar
refashioning of the 23-member Senate, where the Democratic Filipino
Party holds only six seats.
</TEXT>
