<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0642,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Proposes Mutual Efforts on Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with State Department comment;
picks up 4th graf pvs: Three Iranians...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Friday renewed an offer to work
for the release of nine American hostages in Lebanon if the United
States would make the same efforts on behalf of Iranian hostages
there.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani made the offer in a Friday
prayer sermon broadcast on official Tehran radio. Other Iranian
officials have made the same suggestion in the past.
   ``If you are interested in having your people held hostage in
Lebanon released, then tell the Phalangists to release our people
who have been in their hands for years, and of whom we do not have
any news,'' Rafsanjani was quoted as saying in the broadcast, which
was monitored in Nicosia.
   In Washington, the State Department on Friday reaffirmed its
policy against making any deals for release of American hostages in
Lebanon. Spokesman Charles Redman said that all hostages, American
and Iranian alike, should be released immediately.
   Three Iranians _ Ahmad Motevaselian, Hussein Musavi and Kazem
Akhavan _ were kidnapped by right-wing Christian Phalangist gunmen
in northern Lebanon in 1982. Their Lebanese driver, who had an
Iranian passport, also disappeared. The four are widely believed to
be dead.
   Rafsanjani alleged in his sermon that the United States backed
the Christian Phalangists in Lebanon and thus could not claim it had
no influence among them, the radio said.
   If the United States helps free the Iranians, Rafsanjani said,
``we will also suggest to our well-wishers and friends in Lebanon to
release any hostages they may have.''
   Fourteen foreign hostages, including nine Americans, are being
held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists. In addition,
a Swiss Red Cross official was kidnapped in the southern port of
Sidon on Nov. 17, but no one has claimed responsibility.
   The longest-held foreign hostage is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Rafsanjani also condemned former U.S. President Jimmy Carter for
trying to link resumption of U.S.-Iranian ties to the hostage issue.
   In a letter made public by the Iranians last week, Carter asked
Iran to release the hostages, saying it would overcome a main
obstacle to the renewal of ties between Washington and Tehran.
   ``We are neither hostage-takers or interested in resuming ties
with the U.S.,'' Rafsanjani said.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, responding to Carter's letter last
week, said ``the relationship between Iran and the U.S. is like the
relationship between a wolf and a lamb, and between these there can
never be reconciliation.''
   A spokeswoman for Carter in Atlanta said the letter was
``responding to an initiative from Iran.''
   Rafsanjani said Carter had sent him a similar letter and he was
preparing a reply.
   ``America is looking for a way to establish contact with the
Islamic Republic, and the malice of its leaders has driven it to
this (sending the letter),'' the radio quoted Rafsanjani as saying.
   ``The American leaders do not have enough courage to say, `We
have made a mistake, we mistreated the Islamic Republic, and we had
a bad attitude towards the Islamic revolution, and we want to make
up,'' Rafsanjani said.
   ``If you want to establish ties with the Islamic Republic, then
you must give up your vile schemes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
