<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices Edge Down in Japan Due to Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with late
figures. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices edged down on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
in its half-day session Saturday, mainly due to profit-taking in
early trading, dealers said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 66.62-point winner the
previous day, lost 43.06 points, or 0.15 percent, to end the week's
trading at 29,363.59. Losing 128.21 points shortly after the market
opened, the index did not change its overall downward trend although
it recovered slightly toward the end of trading.
   Securities dealers attributed the decline to heavy profit-taking
in early trading by institutional investors after continuous gains
for the last few weeks.
   Since the beginning of November, the Nikkei index has risen
1,424.11 points, or 5.1 percent, setting new historical highs almost
daily.
   A Nomura Securities' analyst said market players, who regained
some confidence of foreign exchange stability as the dollar did not
go below the 120-yen level Friday, started buying late in the
session.
   ``Market players increasingly bought steels toward the end of the
session, which helped the index recover a little,'' said the
analyst, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 550 million
shares.
   The foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
