<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 2216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-TitanTrip 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Titan Trip, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0661,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA, European Space Agency To Probe Titan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with NASA comment. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
Titan is ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe and the United States plan to send a space
probe to Titan, the solar system's biggest moon and the only one
with an atmosphere much like primordial Earth's, the European Space
Agency announced Friday.
   The joint mission to Saturn's immense, gas-shrouded satellite
would begin in 1996 and include a lunar probe that may be able to
test soil from the mysterious moon.
   The mission, to be called the Cassini-Titan probe, was chosen
from a series of proposed joint projects during meetings Thursday
and Friday of the European Space Agency's Science Program Committee.
   NASA, however, still is seeking official approval for the $550
million project. It is expected to ask Congress for some funding
during the 1990 fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, NASA spokesman
Charles Redmond said in Washington.
   Redmond said he expects the Europeans would contribute about $100
million to $150 million. They proposed paying for at least one major
instrument system, helping to pay for some others and providing
propulsion components.
   The project is named after 17th-century Italian astronomer
Giovanni Domenico Cassini.
   Titan is the only moon in the solar system known to have a thick,
organic-rich nitrogen atmosphere. The surface temperature is about
minus 354 degrees.
   Scientists believe that the chemical processes in Titan's
atmosphere may resemble those at work on the primitive Earth before
the origin of life.
   Cassini-Titan is to be launched in April 1996 by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration and should arrive in the Saturn
system in October 2002, the European Space Agency said in a
statement.
   Saturn and its system of rings and satellites were briefly
encountered in 1980-81 during the United States' Voyager 1 and 2
missions.
   The Cassini-Titan mission will place around Saturn a NASA-built
orbiter that will send an European-built probe into Titan's
atmosphere. The probe is to slow down to subsonic speeds when it
gets within 110 miles of the moon.
   The probe is named Huygens, after the Dutch astronomer and
physicist Christian Huygens, who discovered Titan in 1656.
   A parachute system will be deployed to allow a slow descent to
the surface of Titan, which some scientists say is covered by ethane
and methane lakes or oceans. The low-velocity impact may be soft
enough to allow analysis of a surface sample before the probe dies,
the European Space Agency said.
   During the descent of Huygens, the orbiter will be used as a
radio relay station to transmit the probe's data to Earth. After
Huygen's mission, the Cassini orbiter is to circle Saturn for four
years at an altitude of only 620 miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 2322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Drugs     11-25 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Drugs,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Conference Opens to Adopt Pact on Illegal Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. conference opened Friday to adopt
an international convention against illicit drug trafficking and
drug abuse.
   ``The convention will provide a new powerful weapon to combat
drug abuse and illicit trafficking,'' Axel Wuestenhage, deputy
director of the U.N. Information Office in Vienna, told The
Associated Press.
   ``What's very important is that they (the new rules) include
rights to forfeit assets of illicit drug traffickers and rights of
extradition given to all signatory countries for the first time,''
he said.
   The conference is scheduled to last until Dec. 20. The convention
to be adopted complements two existing international legal
instruments _ the Convention on Narcotic Drugs of 1961 signed by 121
countries and the Convention on Psychotropic Substances of 1971, to
which 88 countries have so far acceded.
   The new convention is meant to meet the challenge posed by an
upsurge in illicit drug trafficking and associated organized
criminal activity. Both are viewed as undermining legitimate
economies and threatening the stability, security and sovereignty of
U.N. member states.
   The innovations will reportedly deal with such issues as
forfeiture and confiscation of the proceeds and assets derived from
illicit trafficking, extradition, mutual legal assistance and
cooperation and training of law enforcement officials.
   Special chapters will provide for measures for international
cooperation and help for drug-transit states, monitoring of
substances frequently used in illicit manufacture of drugs,
eradicaton of illegal plant cultivation and suppression of outlawed
traffic by sea, in free-trade zones and free ports, conference
officials said.
   Francesco Ramos Galino, director of the United Nation Division of
Narcotics Drugs, said some countries that previously refused to
divulge information on secret bank accounts now are willing to do so.
   Wuestenhage said the measures have been under discussion since
1984, He said once the convention is adopted, it would be open for
signature by U.N. member states.
   To become legally binding, the convention will have to be
ratified by parliaments or other national bodies in signatory
countries.
   Delegates from about 100 countrties have sent representatives.
Bolivia's Foreign Minister Guillermo Gutierrez is president of the
conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
