<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PenPalMarriage     11-25 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pen Pal Marriage,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pen Pal Relationship to Result in Wedding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A relationship born when a Navy seaman
stationed in the Persian Gulf opened a holiday greetings letter from
a Dayton woman by chance is scheduled to bloom into marriage this
weekend.
   Michael Rodriquez, 22, of Savannah, Ga., and Ruth Brame, 25, are
to exchange vows Saturday nearly a year after they became pen pals.
   The relationship began last January after Ms. Brame read a column
in the Dayton Daily News in which writer Dale Huffman suggested
readers send greetings to servicemen in the Persian Gulf who would
not be home for the holidays.
   Ms. Brame, a single, working mother, sent a card, a letter and a
picture of her 2-year-old son Earl.
   Rodriquez, who was stationed aboard the USS Elrod, said Ms.
Brame's letter was given to him by the ship's postal clerk on a day
Rodriquez received no regular mail.
   ``That was a gift from God,'' he said.
   Rodriquez said he wrote back to Ms. Brame, which resulted in a
response from her. More letters and packages followed.
   ``I fell in love with her before I even met her,'' he said.
   The two finally met face-to-face April 6 at the home of Ms.
Brames' parents in suburban Trotwood.
   ``When I first saw her, I drove up to her house (and) there was a
six-foot neon sign that said `Tom Rodriquez, Welcome to Trotwood,
Ohio. We Love You,''' he said. ``I didn't know whether to drive
around the block or pull into the driveway,'' he said, laughing.
   Ms. Brame said the two basically fell in love through the mail.
   ``All I can say about it is the Lord does work,'' said Ms. Brame.
``The attraction was there, and everything went from there.''
   Rodriquez, who is no longer in the Navy, said that after the
church wedding the couple plan to move to Savannah, where he will
try his hand at the restaurant business.
</TEXT>
