<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laboratory experiments announced today show
that a plant toxin combined with a synthetic protein is able to
attack and kill cells infected with the AIDS virus while leaving
healthy cells untouched.
   In a study published today in the journal Science, a group of
researchers report that a manmade molecule called recombinant CD4
can be used to deliver a killer toxin to cells infected with AIDS in
test-tube experiments.
   However, they cautioned that the new laboratory development _
like other incremental advances in AIDS research _ was far from
being ready for clinical application and, at best, might offer a
potential new treatment approach rather than a cure.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farmers Home Administration is mailing out
today the last of 83,480 delinquency notices to farmers who owe more
than $8 billion in past-due government loans.
   Agency officials began sending out the notices by certified mail
on Nov. 15 telling FmHA borrowers they have 45 days to complete and
return the nine forms. Basically, the notices tell farmers about the
options they have for settling their debt, including restructuring
and write-offs.
   Congress ordered FmHA in the Agricultural Credit Act of 1987 to
revise its lending practices, including ways to handle long-overdue
debt owed by thousands of farmers. Parts of the law were put into
effect earlier in the year but debt write-down, or forgiveness,
kicked in this month. The purpose of the notices is to give
delinquent borrowers an opportunity to let FmHA know how they want
to handle their debt under the new law's provisions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet, his
15-year-old rule nearing an end, is swiftly moving his army back to
the barracks and away from the political battlefield where he
suffered a major defeat in October.
   Political observers and specialists say recent government and
military appointments by Pinochet are aimed at restoring the army's
professionalism and reaffirming his leadership over the service,
which has served as the backbone of his power since a 1973 coup.
   ``He is trying to preserve the army after the electoral defeat he
led it into,'' said Ricardo Lagos, a socialist and prominent
opposition leader. In an Oct. 5 referendum, Chilean voters rejected
a proposal by Gen. Pinochet and other military commanders that he
remain in power until 1997. As a result, he was obliged to call open
elections, planned for late next year, and must hand over power in
March 1990.
</TEXT>
