<1ST_LINE>a a PM-MedicalWasteland-Texas ADV28   11-25 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medical Wasteland-Texas, ADV 28,0705</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Nov. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Texas Leads Nation in Hospital Closings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Medical Wasteland-Rural, b0134</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Name Bill Cosby in 14th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This fall, Hutchinson County became the
52nd Texas county without a hospital when the town of Borger lost
Golden Plains Community Hospital, a 33-bed center brought down by
financial problems and a steadily declining number of patients.
   The decision to close was made by its outside owners, the
Atlanta-based Gateway Medical Systems Inc., and doctors and county
officials are trying to find a buyer.
   But in the meantime, residents of the rural Panhandle county must
drive at least 28 miles if they need anything fancier than stitches
or a cast for a broken bone.
   ``The doctors will meet patients in their offices to treat minor
emergencies,'' said Dr. Eduardo Coligardo, who was chief of staff at
Golden Plains. ``If it's a major emergency, we refer them to a major
hospital, usually in Amarillo (an hour away).''
   Just 100 miles to the southeast is the town of Memphis, a fifth
the size of Borger but recently the victor in a fight to keep Hall
County Hospital open and operating after predictions it would shut
in two months. Local people raised $366,000 in six weeks to buy new
equipment and recruit another doctor.
   Small community hospitals have become all but extinct in the
western and southwestern sections of Texas, home to about 400,000
people. In 1986 and 1987, Texas led the nation in hospital closings.
Twenty-four of the 32 hospitals that were shut were in rural areas.
   So far this year, 19 Texas hospitals have closed, 10 of them in
small towns and rural areas, according to the Texas Hospital
Association.
   Charles Bailey, THA vice president of legal affairs, said the
state's vastness is one simple reason for the high failure rate
among hospitals _ tiny rural hospitals can't afford to keep up with
the technology and expertise offered by the big medical centers in
the cities. Demand for rural hospital beds has dropped, below 20
percent in some cases, Bailey said, as urban hospitals advertise to
attract outlying patients.
   But more important is the ailing Texas economy.
   ``With businesses having trouble and some employees being laid
off and losing thir insurance, uncompensated care has increased in
the state, which puts strain on hospitals financially,'' he said.
   The worsening Texas economy has added to the indigent population;
hospitals provide more than $1.2 billion in uncompensated care each
year.
   While thousands of rural Texans are learning to live without the
protection of a nearby hospital, people in Hall County decided to
take a stand.
   In mid-September, an analysis team from an urban hospital
predicted the county hospital was failing and would fold by
Thanksgiving. It took just six weeks for residents to prove them
wrong.
   ``We realized we had to do something for ourselves, or we
wouldn't have a hospital,'' said Bill Cosby, a retired accountant.
   During the six-week fund drive, children emptied piggybanks,
citizens raffled off pickup trucks and sides of beef, and the
Memphis police chief used his radio to appeal to passing truckers
for donations.
   Almost two-thirds of the money raised was earmarked for new
equipment that would draw patients. Other funds went to recruitment
costs and salary for a new doctor to supplement the efforts of two
elderly physicians who serve the county's 5,000 residents, whose
average age is 57.
   The strong community support that characterized the fund-raising
effort should be enough to ensure the hospital's future survival,
but most communities aren't as lucky, said Dave Clark, regional
health care services coordinator for the Panhandle Health Care
Coalition.
   Hospitals will continue to close, although some may be able to
convert to clinics or emergency care centers.
   ``Some of these towns will just have to face the fact that they
won't have a hospital,'' he said. ``Their hospital may just be a
facility where a patient can be stabilized before taking the patient
on to a city hospital.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Nov. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-HazardousBrazil Adv02   11-25 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hazardous Brazil, Adv 02,0736</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Dec. 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brazil is Most Hazardous Place to Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the beachfront Copacabana neighborhood
in Rio de Janeiro, drivers run red lights on an average of 50 times
an hour.
   Since becoming mayor of Sao Paulo in 1985, former President Janio
Quadros has personally given out more than 20,000 tickets for
traffic violations.
   Across this nation of 144 million people and 13 million motor
vehicles, 25,000 people are killed and 350,000 injured a year in
traffic accidents.
   So far as anyone here knows, that makes Brazil the world's most
hazardous place to drive _ or cross a street.
   About 47,000 people are killed annually in traffic in the United
States, but it has 177 million vehicles in a population of 242.2
million.
   Faced with highway carnage, Brazilian officials have started to
take serious steps to punish reckless drivers, including proposals
for increased jail sentences and stiff fines that in some cases can
exceed what a person earns in monthly wages.
   Reasons given for the carnage on Brazilian roadways include:
   _An inborn passion for moving fast.
   _Weak and ineffective traffic laws and enforcement.
   _National economic problems, such as 1,000 percent-plus annual
inflation that forces people to run around day and night to make
ends meet.
   ``We have a Vietnam in traffic every year,'' said Justice
Minister Paulo Brossard, in announcing a ``National Traffic Safety
Program'' proposing tougher treatment of bad drivers.
   ``It is civil war,'' said Jose Fernando Eichenberg, the No. 2
official in the ministry and a critic of weak traffic laws.
   Under the new program, traffic fines have gone up by as much as
300 percent. In some places a ticket for speeding or running a red
light costs the equivalent of $88, while parking in a prohibited
zone can go as high as $140. Brazil's montly minimum wage is about
$60.
   ``People are concerned with what hurts their pocketbooks,'' said
Cyro Vidal, the traffic director of Sao Paulo, Brazil's biggest city
and traffic-accident leader. ``It used to be cheaper to take a
ticket than pay for parking.''
   But Vidal added in an interview that Sao Paulo's 4 million annual
traffic fines _ equal to the number of cars in the city _ really
haven't reduced violations or accidents.
   Mayor Quadros routinely jumps out of his official car to hand out
tickets for traffic violations. For really gross infractions, he
calls a tow truck to haul away the violator's car. The mayor also
has placed the remains of smashed and twisted cars on special
platforms throughout the city, pinning signs to the wreckage that
read, ``Haste 1, Life 0.''
   But the wrecks continue anyway.
   Gov. Orestes Quercia of Sao Paulo state has outlawed the sale of
liquor at cafes and truck stops along state highways. But the news
media have reported that the law, the first of its kind in Brazil,
is being widely ignored.
   The head of the Traffic Department in Rio de Janeiro, Jose Alves
de Brito, said that in his city at least ``repression does not
achieve objectives.''
   ``Rio drivers are not civilized,'' he said, citing such
violations as chronic drunken driving, speeding, lack of respect for
traffic lights and signs, parking on sidewalks and even high-speed
zigzagging in tunnels.
   Brito said that because of Brazil's dismal economic situation,
with record inflation and the falling buying power of the cruzado,
the nation's currency, ``people need to earn more to maintain their
economic status and so must be on the go all day.''
   ``Accidents are a reflection of those problems,'' he said.
   Traffic authorities have some hopes for a plan to modify Brazil's
penal code to change traffic violations from simple misdemeanors to
felonious crimes. The plan proposes up to six months in jail for
reckless driving, a year in cases involving serious injuries and 18
months for a fatal accident.
   It also provides for mandatory driver education in high schools
and colleges and monthly upward readjustment of the amount of
traffic fines. The latter is aimed at violators who wait until the
end of the month to pay the fines and thus take advantage of the
daily devaluation of the cruzado.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Dec. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Yellowstone'sGhosts ADV30   11-25 1202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yellowstone's Ghosts, ADV 30,1234</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Nov. 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Summer's Blazes Expose Yellowstone's Secrets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old-timers with long memories
knew it was there. Archivists gave it a special place in the history
books. But millions of people passed by the wreckage without a clue
it was there.
   Then, in the summer of 1988, a woodcutter dropped a cigarette and
started a 450,000-acre forest fire that laid bare the bones of a
World War II-vintage B-17 bomber, 45 years after it went down on a
frigid spring night carrying 10 young airmen to their deaths.
   Besides blackening hundreds of thousands of acres in America's
first national park and triggering an uproar over firefighting
policy on public lands, the intense blazes in Yellowstone also
revealed some of its old secrets.
   ``The fires exposed a lot of old road cuts, torn up culverts and
bridges, and abandoned dump sites,'' said Tim Hudson, Yellowstone's
maintenance chief and a sanitary engineer. ``We vaguely knew about
all that stuff, but over the years trees had grown up around it and
it became hard to get to, too expensive to remove, or people forgot
about it.
   ``Our rehabilitation efforts following the fires have also given
us an opportunity to do some monumental cleanup of old junk because
we have the helicopters here to help us do it.''
   Besides rebuilding burned-out bridges, repairing bulldozed and
hand-cut firelines and fixing trails and public facilities, park
crews also raced the winter to remove all debris from the crash of
the B-17, tail No. 42-30260.
   Ground teams carefully collected the shattered, rusted pieces of
.50-caliber machine guns, splinters of practice bombs once filled
with sand and dozens of bullets.
   Much of the aluminum and steel already twisted by the crash was
charred from the North Fork fire. The weathered metal was loaded
into helicopter slings and hauled four miles north to a sorting area
inside the park near West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The main wreckage and the 20-foot crater created by the massive
bomber when it plowed into the ground around midnight May 23, 1943,
had been covered over by initial rescue crews, so Hudson's cleanup
team left it undisturbed.
   ``The stuff we pulled out totals about 25,000 pounds,'' said
Hudson. ``We flew all the bullets out first, then dumped and burned
their powder. The biggest piece we recovered was a wing tip. We also
found the vertical and horizontal stabilizer on the tail section a
mile from the main crash site.''
   Even the archivists had missed that one on their maps and charts
because, in the past half century, the forests of Yellowstone had
grown up around the site to create a living green shroud.
   Hardly any wreckage was recognizable. Park records indicate that
a few years after the crash a Yellowstone ranger salvaged enough
aluminum to make a snow plane, forerunner of the snowmobile. The
area also showed signs of earlier scavenging and looting. Nothing
recovered this fall was deemed usable, so the park service, with
Department of Defense approval, will sell it as scrap to the highest
bidder.
   Poking through the forest fire's ashes, park employees also found
small reminders of the airmen who died.
   ``We found part of a leather jacket, a shoe, some pieces of belts
and rings off of parachute harnesses,'' said Dick Bahr,
Yellowstone's air operations supervisor. ``There was no identifying
markings on any of the personal gear so we sent it to a mortuary to
be incinerated.''
   It was precious little to commemorate the burial ground of an
airplane once hailed as ``The Queen of the Skies'' and singled out
by the Smithsonian Air and Space Museum as the most powerful weapon
in the war against Hitler's Germany.
   In 1983, park service historical archivist Andy Beck collected
every scrap of information he could find about aircraft No. 42-30260
and compiled it in a plastic ringbinder now kept at Yellowstone
headquarters.
   The plane, with 11 men on board, was flying from Marysville,
Calif., to its home base at Lewiston, Mont. According to an Army Air
Corps investigation, the pilot climbed to 15,000 feet above Reno,
Nev., and soon hit rough air. He was flying by instruments.
   Next to the line citing ``Nature of Accident'' was this notation:
``Airplane encountered icing conditions. No definite knowledge of
what happened.''
   Retired Yellowstone Park Ranger Tom Ela never knew the cause but
he remembers the crash well.
   ``My wife, Betty, and I'd been to a birthday party and had just
gotten home when we heard the plane go over. I went to the window
because I knew it wasn't sounding right. We could hear it go into a
scream as it went down.''
   Ela rushed to a nearby observation plateau and saw the sky alight
with flame. The plane, carrying live ammunition, burned on impact.
   There was confusion about the number of men aboard, so Ela was
among searchers looking for survivors. On the third day, when he
clibed a tree and hollered ``Hallooooo'' for the hundredth time, an
answering call came back.
   ``He said his name was McDonald, he was very, very cold, and he
asked `Where am I?' because he had no idea,'' recalled Ela, who now
lives in Santa Fe, N.M.
   ``When I told him he was in Yellowstone National Park he couldn't
believe it. He told me he'd been sleeping right by the hatch with
his parachute on. Apparently he'd had a tight squeak before on a
flight and he was the only one in the crew who had his 'chute on.
   ``When he heard in his headphones `THIS IS IT! THIS IS IT! GET
OUT!' he just rolled out the hatch and pulled the cord. He saw the
plane crash below him and knew he'd made it but didn't know if
anybody else did. That was bothering him a lot.''
   McDonald told Ela that later, as he'd wandered alone in the woods
for two days, he'd wondered if he'd had a nightmare and bailed out
by mistake as his plane flew on to its home base.
   The Army Air Corps listed Lt. William McDonald, bombardier, as
the only survivor. After leading McDonald out of the woods, Ela
helped pack out on horseback the dead men and the plane's top secret
equipment.
   The official investigation concludes that 2,000 square feet of
Yellowstone were damaged, the aircraft was totally destroyed, and
the pilot (no signature available, deceased) absolved the park
service of any blame.
   Hudson, Bahr, and other park employees agreed that working on the
B-17 cleanup had been an interesting chapter in the story of the
Yellowstone fires. Next summer they hope to tackle an even bigger
rehabilitation project.
   ``There's a B-47 bomber still out there in an area that didn't
burn,'' said Hudson. ``It crashed in 1963, killing four Air Force
crewmen, without any fire or explosion. We estimate its wreckage at
85,000 pounds. If we can get the big helicopters back in here next
summer that ought to keep us busy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Nov. 30</NOTE>
