<2ND_LINE>AM-Settlement Family, ADV 02,0643</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Dec. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Guns are Part of Life for Israeli Settlers in West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OFRA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before leaving for work, Aliza
Herbst packed sandwiches for her five children and drank a cup of
coffee with her husband.
   Then she slipped a pistol into her purse.
   ``Irrational violence has made us fearful,'' explained Mrs.
Herbst, 36, an immigrant from San Antonio. ``But we're the kind of
people who will put our bodies and lives on the line for what we
believe in.''
   Nearly a year of Palestinian rebellion has prompted many Jewish
settlers in the occupied West Bank to make pistols or automatic
rifles a part of their daily lives.
   Mrs. Herbst and her husband, Gershon, moved to this tight-knit
West Bank community 13 years ago because they wanted to put down
roots in a place where crime was virtually non-existent and
neighbors shared basic religious values.
   But Ofra, like the 118 other Jewish settlements in the West Bank,
has been thrust into the midst of the Palestinian uprising in which
settlers have become targets of roadside ambushes and rock-throwing
protests.
   The American-born couple still describes the settlement, with its
lawns and rows of identical orange-roofed houses, as a community in
which ``kids can wander free and you don't have to lock your front
door.''
   But the the violence surrounding Ofra's 760 residents echoes at
the Herbst family's dinner table and in its living room.
   On one recent Jewish Sabbath, the youngest children played on the
bare tile floors in the family home before joining their parents in
prayers, songs and Friday night dinner.
   After the meal, 10-year-old Yehuda brought a tattered Palestinian
flag into the kitchen.
   ``I will give it to them, then kill them,'' he boasted to a young
friend while clutching the red, white, green and black banner.
   His parents cast disapproving looks across the table, explaining
later that teaching the children to deal with anger is one of the
challenges of raising a family in the midst of the uprising.
   ``I don't want my kids going around being hateful,'' said Herbst,
a native of Brooklyn, N.Y. ``We always take time to talk to them
about the situation. They know people get hurt and they have to
express their fears.''
   Traveling beyond the settlement's perimeter has become risky.
   Herbst, a partner in a farm cooperative, carries an M-16 assault
rifle on trips to his fruit orchard which is near Jerusalem, 15
miles south of Ofra.
   ``It's not an over-reaction to shoot. I'd rather deal with the
judicial system than the hospital system,'' Herbst explained as he
drove along unlighted West Bank roads on a Saturday night with the
rifle at his side.
   According to Law in the Service of Man, an Arab-run human rights
group, Jewish settlers have killed 12 of the 315 Palestinians who
have died since last December as a result of the violence. Five
Israeli civilians have been killed in the occupied lands.
   One victim of Palestinian attacks was Meshulam Moscowitz, a
neighbor of the Herbsts' who is still recovering from a head wound
suffered in a stone-throwing Arab ambush eight months ago. Doctors
implanted a plastic plate to repair his damaged skull.
   Now Moscowitz wears a bicycle helmet and carries an automatic
rifle when he travels beyond the line of olive trees that separates
Ofra from the neighboring Arab village of Ein Yabrud.
   ``I don't want it to happen again,'' said the New York-born
Moscowitz, who taught self-defense courses to the settlement's
children before the attack. ``But I'm not going to leave now and
show them that throwing stones works.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Dec. 2</NOTE>
