<1ST_LINE>a a AM-YellowstoneRehabilitation ADV30   11-25 1185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Rehabilitation, ADV 30,1210</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Nov. 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Halted by Snow, Park Work Crews Assess Fire Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finally, with the Christmas
season hard upon a wintry land, the fires have gone out in
Yellowstone National Park.
   It has been half a year since lightning hit a tree near Rose
Creek on May 24 and ignited the first of 20 wildfires in the 2.2
million-acre park.
   That blaze died on its own. But others, christened Hellroaring
and Storm Creek, Clover and Mist and Huck, roared up from smoldering
embers to engulf nearly half of the first national park in walls of
flame that eventually stretched 20 miles wide and 40 miles long on
two fronts.
   The firestorms of Yellowstone were awesome and frightening.
Despite the efforts of 25,000 firefighters, only the natural forces
of snow and rain were a match for the fires' fury.
   By mid-November, the firefighters were gone and the remnants of
flame no longer demanded constant attention. As inches, then feet of
snow fell on the park tucked into the corner where Wyoming, Idaho,
and Montana meet, park officials officially declared the
conflagration over Nov. 18.
   After six months of trying to fight fires, patch together
disrupted services and keep the park gates open, Yellowstone
officials at last had a chance to assess damage and prepare for the
future.
   They have already asked Congress for $21.3 million toward fire
recovery, including elaborate exhibits, books, traveling information
teams and extensive research. Of that money, $10 million would be
used to repair actual fire damage.
   ``We lost 100 power poles and 18 miles of line, which amounted to
about 40,000 pounds of copper wire,'' said Tim Hudson, Yellowstone's
maintenance chief. ``At one time we were running 13 generators and
using 5,000 gallons of diesel fuel a day just to keep this park
operating. We didn't get full power restored until October.
   ``About 200 miles of roadside terrain needs to be rehabilitated
by taking down all the burned trees _ the snags _ which threaten to
fall on the highway. Lord knows how many need to be pulled down
along the hiking and ski trails. Then we have to cut the stumps down
to ground level and grind up their tops, spread wood chips out, and
cover them with soil so they'll decompose.''
   ``We had 32 miles of bulldozer line, but we got that fixed. About
1,000 miles of hand-cut fire lines still have to be repaired. On one
trail alone we've got to replace seven pedestrian bridges. We've got
to clean up and aerate the soil at more than 150 helicopter landing
sites. All the back-country campsites used by fire crews also have
to be rehabbed.''
   Hudson is a straightforward manager whose vanity is a handlebar
mustache that makes him look like the villain who tied Pauline to
the railroad tracks. He was an unheralded hero of Yellowstone's
summer of smoke as he organized his beleagered maintenance crews to
rush from one disaster to another.
   They set up miles of sprinkler pipe at Old Faithful and Canyon
Village, saved 26 backcountry cabins with a jury-rigged system of
hoses strung from tiny creeks, and frantically wrapped an enormous
steel water tank in fiberglass insulation that burned off but saved
the tank.
   Generally, Hudson's staff held the entire park's infrastructure
together with ingenuity, improvisation and, as Hudson put it, ``a
lot of luck.''
   ``At some point I knew it would end. I just never thought it
would go on so long,'' said Hudson, who took six days off in the
five months of the worst strain. ``I also knew that when it did
ultimately end, we'd be stuck with the leftover mess.''
   Of the request for funds now with Congress, Hudson asked for
$90,000 to rehabilitate bulldozer lines, $1.5 million for electrical
services, $1 million to groom highway corridors, another $1 million
to upgrade 600 miles of hiking trails and $15,000 to rebuild a
burned-out bathroom.
   Decades of forgotten debris camouflaged by growing trees was
exposed by the fires, so rehabilitation crews also targeted for
cleanup piles of tin cans, old culverts, abandoned campsites and
even the wreckage of a B-17 bomber that crashed in 1943.
   Immediately after the worst of the fires were contained, park
officials offered free firewood along the roadside to anybody who
wanted it. Hudson estimated several thousand cords of charred fuel
went to the public. He also negotiated a contract with a Livingston,
Mont., lumber company to pay the park $25 for every 1,000 cubic feet
of snag trees it hauled away. That project is expected to last well
into next summer.
   Never without his walkie-talkie, Hudson prowled Yellowstone's
roads supervising crews trying to clean up the ``leftover mess''
until snow closed most of the highways. It's his responsibility to
get the park in shape for next summer's tourist season.
   Lore Williams is one of Hudson's assistants. As Yellowstone's
landscape architect, Ms. Williams, 33, was criticized at the height
of the blazes for resisting the use of bulldozers and heavy
equipment to build fire breaks inside the park.
   ``I felt the heat both literally and figuratively,'' Ms. Williams
said wryly, acknowledging her role in helping direct a firefighting
strategy that is to be reviewed by Congress amid outcries about
mismanagement.
   ``From the beginning we assigned resource people to work on every
fire to brief crews on how to cut hand line in a serpentine way so
it wouldn't be so hard to rehabilitate it,'' said Ms. Williams, a
park employee for four years. ``When they put that bulldozer line
in, it was overrun six hours later. We knew it wouldn't hold.
   ``It took an operater 325 hours on a rubber-tired excavator, plus
20-man crews using hand tools for several weeks, to fix it. Now I'm
worried that poachers will use the new 'dozer roads in the back
country. ''
   Ms. Williams is frustrated by the amount of human-caused damage
left behind by the thousands of firefighters who camped for months
in Yellowstone.
   ``Our top priority was hauling out trash and food that could
attract bears,'' she said. ``We worked our tails off to get the
bulldozer firebreak rehabbed before winter, but we've got a long way
to go on the hand line. A 20-person crew can only rehabilitate two
miles of hand line a day.''
   Ms. Williams supervised eight crews this fall and hopes to have a
similar number back on the job next spring if there's enough money.
Each crew includes seven sawyers certified to use chain saws, two
fallers approved to bring down trees, one emergeny medical
technician, and at least two squad bosses.
   ``It's filthy, unglamorous work in the cold, wind and ash,'' said
Ms. Williams, who spent part of every day supervising from a
helicopter, ``but we are trying to work with the natural scene. We
are trying to heal the scars.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Nov. 30</NOTE>
