<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0534</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. urged owners of
its 27 million shares against siding with dissidents bent on
dismantling the last major U.S. television manufacturer.
   In a letter Wednesday, Zenith Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman
acknowledged that the Chicago-area company ``has had some rough
times in the past several years'' but said it was absurd to think
Brookhurst Partners could do better.
   Zenith shareholders have until Dec. 4 to return signed consent
forms to Brookhurst Partners, indicating their support for
Brookhurst's plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats have questioned the
fairness of a Federal Communications Commission proposal to replace
profit regulation of telephone companies with caps on prices.
   A report by the Democratic staff of the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications subcommittee said Wednesday the FCC's proposal
fails to assure that rates for regulated phone service will be
``just and reasonable.'' The FCC has proposed to change the way it
regulates American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and the regional Bell
phone companies by lifting limits on the profits they can earn and
instead set a ceiling on rates.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 460 money market mutual
funds rose $1.07 billion in the latest week to a record $280.40
billion, the Investment Company Institute says.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday followed a
revised $4.64 billion increase in the funds' assets the previous
week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade group.
   The previous high for the funds' assets was $280.02 billion in
the week ended Feb. 24.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Farm Bureau Federation says it
fears federal agents are eagerly waiting to corral farmers who hire
undocumented aliens when immigration sanctions against employers
take effect Dec. 1.
   But a spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service
said Wednesday those worries are unfounded and that the agency will
be evenhanded in enforcing the employer sanctions against farmers.
   Nevertheless, a labor specialist at the U.S. Department of
Agriculture acknowledged that some farmers are afraid of an INS
crackdown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-awaited new grain deal with the Soviet
Union may be near, Agriculture Department spokesmen say.
   The department's information office said Wednesday that no
announcement would be forthcoming but that ``something may be in the
works'' at some point in the next few days, possibly next Monday.
   Negotiators led by Alan F. Holmer, deputy U.S. trade
representative, have been attempting to reach agreement with Soviet
representatives for months. The old pact expired Sept. 30. It called
for minimum annual purchases of U.S. corn and wheat.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a moderate advance Wednesday in quiet
pre-Thanksgiving Day trading. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials climbed 14.58 to 2,092.28 for its best single-day
showing in nearly three weeks.
   The dollar closed lower against all key foreign currencies.
   Bond prices finished narrowly mixed.
   Copper futures prices rocketed higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange, and grain and soybean futures, sugar, crude oil, precious
metals, livestock, meat and stock-index futures all advanced.
</TEXT>
