<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly higher against most major
currencies in thin morning trading today with the market waiting for
a cue from New York after the Thanksgiving holiday.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Traders said the dollar moved higher following an estimated $200
million of buying by Japan's central Bank of Japan in East Asian
markets earlier today.
   The dollar ran into some resistance early in Europe at around
1.7180 West German marks, but most traders said they were waiting
for the opening of the U.S. market after the holiday Thursday.
   ``The market wants to see where New York would take the dollar,''
said one trader at a European bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where markets close before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 121.15 yen, unchanged from Thursday.
Later in London it traded higher at 121.25 yen.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. One pound
cost $1.8353, cheaper for buyers than Thursday's late $1.8375.
   Other midmorning dollar rates, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7180 West German marks, up from 1.7135; 1.4390
Swiss francs, up from 1.4375; 5.8715 French francs, up from 5.8585;
1.9375 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9340; 1,276.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,273.75; 1.1905 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1960.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $420.20 a troy ounce and
at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $422.60. Both prices were higher than
Thursday's late bid price of $420.
   Gold was trading in Zurich at a bid price of $422.80, up from
Thursday's late price of $420.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $3.39 to close at a bid price of $424.55
today.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid $6.14 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
