<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0741EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-25 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Unchanged, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After trading lower throughout the day, the dollar
recovered slightly to close unchanged against the Japanese yen in
the Tokyo foreign exchange market today. Share prices were
moderately higher.
   The dollar closed at 121.15 yen, unchanged from Thursday's close,
after opening lower at 120.88 yen. It was the first time since Jan.
4 that the dollar opened below the 121-yen level.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 66.62
points, or 0.23 percent, to close at 29,406.65. The market's main
index lost 90.09 points Thursday after rising for eight consecutive
trading days.
   After declining in London overnight, the dollar traded in the
relatively wide range of 120.67 yen to 121.20 yen before settling at
121.15 yen.
   Central bank intervention, along with bullish comments by Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, first helped to slow and eventually to
stop the dollar's fall. Dealers estimated the bank's dollar
purchases today at 300 to 400 million yen.
   Dealers said Japan's central bank actively intervened before
Tokyo trading began, buying dollars in the Sydney market.
   ``The Bank of Japan is changing its intervention style'' by
entering the market early, said Kaneo Ogino, a dealer at Goldman
Sachs in Tokyo. ``They've been asking prices and are going to buy.''
   Ogino said the central bank also appeared to be active in the
Singapore market after the Tokyo market had closed. Bank of Japan
officials refuse to comment on their market activities.
   Sentiment toward the dollar remained bearish, traders said. But
speculation that a new Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
production agreement could be reached in the next few days could
help prop up the dollar during European trading, said Stephen
Codrington, head of equity sales at Jardine Fleming (Securities)
Ltd. here.
   On Thursday, Iranian oil minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh announced
that he agreed in principle to a new OPEC agreement, which raises
the cartel's production ceiling to 18.5 million barrels a day.
   In the stock market, prices were firmer until midafternoon, when
investors sold utilities on speculation over the OPEC announcement,
Codrington said.
   But the market recovered to close higher after a late rally.
   ``There was some window dressing by investment trusts, and today
was the last day of trading for November accounts, so some dealers
were squaring positions,'' he added.
   Analysts said the financial markets were relatively quiet due to
the Thanksgiving holidays, and that brokers were reluctant to make
major changes in their positions. Japanese markets were closed on
Labor Thanksgiving Day Wednesday, and U.S. financial institutions
closed for Thursday's Thanksgiving holiday.
   Japan's finance minister told reporters today that Japan is ready
to intervene in the currency market to stem exchange rate volatility.
   He also said that fluctuations in the currency exchange markets
had not created a need for a meeting of the Group of Seven major
industrial nations. The comment followed calls for a G-7 meeting
after president-elect George Bush's inauguration from West German
Finance Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg and his French counterpart,
Pierre Beregovoy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
