<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Salt,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salt Rationed in Many Parts of China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panic buying has forced 19 provinces and cities to
impose rationing on salt, the manager of the China National Salt Co.
was quoted today as saying.
   The official China Daily quoted Zhang Tiecheng as saying
rationing of table salt went into effect this month and will not end
until the shortage has eased.
   Zhang said the company stopped wholesale salt supplies to
enterprises and individuals, limiting supplies to retail outlets in
an effort to stop hoarding and panic buying.
   The daily quoted another salt company official as saying table
salt supplies had been stable for more than 30 years but that salt
output will reach a record 20 million tons this year, up 3 million
tons from last year.
   He was quoted as saying the shortage resulted from a rapid
increase in salt consumption by the chemical industry and panic
buying in 26 cities and regions.
</TEXT>
