<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0858EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HollyFarms-Tyson     11-25 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Tennessee Anti-Takeover Laws Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that
Tennessee's anti-takeover laws are unconstitutional and cannot be
used to stop Tyson Foods Inc.'s bid to buy out Holly Farms Corp.
   ``These acts violate the commerce clause of the U.S. Constitution
to the extent they apply to target corporations organized under the
laws of states other than Tennessee,'' U.S. District Judge Thomas A.
Wiseman wrote in a memorandum.
   Wiseman on Wednesday enjoined the state from enforcing the laws
to prevent a takeover of Holly Farms.
   Tyson of Springdale, Ark., the nation's largest poultry producer,
last month made a $52-per-share takeover offer for the Memphis-based
food producer. It has extended the offer until mid-December.
   Holly Farms has rejected Tyson's bids and struck up a deal to
merge with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., through a stock swap.
ConAgra is the fifth-largest poultry processor in the nation.
   Wednesday's ruling came just days after Tyson sued Holly Farms
and ConAgra in chancery court in Wilmington, Del., where the three
companies were chartered.
   The suit, filed Monday, seeks to invalidate the proposed Holly
Farms-ConAgra merger as well as an option the Holly Farms board
granted to ConAgra allowing the Nebraska producer to purchase Holly
Farms' top poultry assets in the event the merger fails.
   Wiseman said Tennessee's laws violate the commerce clause because
they regulate interstate commerce, risk inconsistent regulation and
place an excessive burden on interstate commerce in relation to
local benefits.
   The state laws passed March 11 include the Investor Protection
Act, which regulates takeover offers for corporations that are
incorporated or have principal offices in Tennessee and substantial
assets in the state.
   The other three laws require an investor to wait five years or
more after acquiring 10 percent of a company's stock to make a
takeover offer, strip voting rights from a potential buyer and
regulate corporations not incorporated in Tennessee.
   State Attorney General Charles Burson said he had not yet decided
whether to appeal Wiseman's decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 0919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Economy     11-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Economy,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit More Than Doubles, Prompting Interest Rate Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit more than
doubled to 2.93 billion pounds, or about $5.4 billion, in October as
exports fell sharply and imports surged, the government announced
Friday.
   The Bank of England pushed up interest rates a full percentage
point to 13 percent half an hour after the trade report was released
at 11:30 a.m. The rate increase, the first since a full-point hike
on Aug. 25, steadied a plummeting pound, but sent stock prices
plunging.
   The increase underscores the government's determination to ``take
no risks'' with inflation, said a Treasury official, who wasn't
identified in accordance with British practice. The benchmark rate
has been pushed up 5.5 points since June.
   Britain's major commercial banks quickly responded to the central
banks' signal, with Barclays Bank PLC, National Westminster Bank
PLC, and Lloyds Banks PLC increasing their benchmark rate.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said on British
Broadcasting Corp. television that the worsening October figures
should be viewed together with good figures in the previous month,
adding ``interest rates do take time to take their full effect.''
   Lawson has said repeatedly that interest rates would have to rise
further if the nation's economy continued to move at too fast a rate.
   The British pound dropped from about $1.8335 to $1.8220 on the
trade news but it bounced back to $1.8370 on the rate increase.
   But developments sent the Financial Times Stock Exchange
100-share index tumbling 41.1 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,791.9 at
about 1 p.m., its worst level for the day. Moments before the trade
report, the index was down just 1.1 points.
   The seasonally adjusted deficit in October, which the government
blamed partly on erratic items and distortions caused by a September
mail strike, compared with a revised deficit of 1.09 billion pounds,
or $2 billion, in September and of 954 million pounds, or $1.8
billion, in October 1987.
   Exports fell 10 percent in October while imports gained 12
percent, the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   With October's trade in invisible items _ which covers services,
overseas investment earnings and official transfer payments _
estimated to be in surplus by 500 million pounds, or $920 million,
Britain's current account showed a record deficit of 2.43 billion
pounds ($4.5 billion) in October, compared with a revised deficit of
594 million pounds ($1.09 billion) in September and a deficit of 491
million pounds ($903 million) in October 1987.
   The department said the September postal dispute affected the
recording of exports, but not imports. As much as 300 million pounds
of exports ($552 million) that were allocated to September should
have been allocated to October, it said.
   The department also said that October's imports included around
400 million pounds ($736 million) in erratic items, such as precious
stones and aircraft.
   Since the beginning of 1988, Britain's merchandise trade balance
has been in deficit by 17 billion pounds ($31 billion), compared
with a deficit of 7.8 billion pounds ($14 billion) in the same
period a year earlier.
   The current account has been in deficit by 12.4 billion pounds
($23 billion) so far this year, compared with a deficit of 1.1
billion pounds ($2 billion) a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0199 </DOCNO>
