<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0347</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled in light post-Thanksgiving
Day trading today, depressed by expectations of higher oil prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 20.09 to 2,072.19
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 228 up, 688 down and
370 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 17.30 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The session after Thanksgiving is usually one of the quietest
days on the year on Wall Street, as many market participants take a
long holiday weekend.
   This time, however, those traders who were present were faced
with the news of a tentative agreement by members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on production quotas
aimed at shoring up oil prices.
   The prospect of increased energy costs weighed down the credit
markets. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, fell nearly $10 for each
$1,000 in face value this morning.
   The stock market followed suit, with the notable exception of
energy stocks.
   In the energy sector, Atlantic Richfield rose 1[ to 79[; Exxon ]
to 42]; Chevron } to 45; Amoco 1 to 72|, and Phillips Petroleum ] to
19~.
   Losers among the blue-chip industrials included International
Business Machines, down 1] at 116|; General Electric, down { at 43~;
General Motors, down ] at 81~, and American Telephone & Telegraph,
down ] at 28~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.04 to 150.37. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .14 at 290.23.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 14.58 to
2,092.28.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 882 up, 517 down and 514 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 112.01 million shares, against 127
million in the previous session.
