<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0548</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It's beginning to look a lot like a tight inventory Christmas,
everywhere you go.
   Today's opening of the nation's annual shopping marathon finds
retailers cautiously optimistic about improving their seasonal
sales, but conservative enough to stock sparingly.
   Lean inventories are unusual at this time of year when stores are
gearing up for the post-Thanksgiving rush that accounts for a large
slice of their yearly sales. But inventory control has become an
industry standard in 1988, as merchants puzzle through the second
year of a long slump.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration says it has
successfully reached the goal of cutting its final budget by $35
billion without raising taxes.
   Joseph R. Wright, director of the Office of Management and
Budget, said Wednesday the draft budget reduces an anticipated $135
billion deficit for the 1990 fiscal year to $100 billion through a
combination of sales of government assets, increased user fees and
cuts in certain domestic programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says orders to U.S. factories
for durable goods rose in October but would have fallen if a rise in
military equipment orders were excluded.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that total orders,
including the biggest gain in military goods since June, rose 2.4
percent last month to a seasonally adjusted $122.1 billion.
   Excluding defense, the government said orders fell 0.2 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. car and light truck sales rose by a lower
than expected 3.5 percent in mid-November compared with the same
period last year.
   The seven automakers said Wednesday they sold 259,725 vehicles
during the Nov. 11-20 period this year, compared with 282,177 during
the same time last year. But sales were up 3.5 percent on a daily
sales basis because there were only eight selling days this year and
nine last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest meatpacker has agreed to
resdesign jobs in its 15 plants in a landmark move that could lead
to better working conditions throughout America's most hazardous
major industry.
   IBP Inc. said Wednesday it is committed to the three-year program
as part of an accord with the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration and the United Food and Commercial Workers union,
settling $5.7 million in proposed fines by the government.
   The terms call for IBP, formerly known as Iowa Beef Processors,
to pay a reduced fine of $975,000 while establishing a model job
redesign program at its 2,800-worker flagship plant in Dakota City,
Neb., to address repetitive trauma disorders such as tendinitis and
carpal tunnel syndrome.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Bennett LeBow has intensified efforts to
buy Prime Computer Inc., telling its management he has no hidden
agenda in the $970 million hostile takeover attempt by his much
smaller computer business, MAI Basic Four Inc.
   ``Contrary to speculation from certain quarters about MAI Basic
Four's intentions, the only motive for MAI Basic Four's tender offer
for Prime shares is to acquire Prime,'' LeBow wrote Wednesday to
Prime president Anthony Craig.
   Some analysts have suggested that LeBow may have tryiong to stir
some interest in MAI Basic by going after Prime.
</TEXT>
