<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Fiat     11-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fiat,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ghidella Resigns As Managing Director Of Fiat Auto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vittorio Ghidella, credited with being the
brain behind Fiat SpA's turnaround this decade, will resign as
managing director of Fiat Auto, the manufacturing unit of Italy's
largest private-sector conglomerate, it was announced Friday.
   The company said Ghidella, 57, will quit his post before year's
end. Cesare Romiti, managing director of Fiat SpA, will be nominated
at the next board meeting for Ghidella's position, it said.
   Ghidella is also the chairman of the luxury car subsidiaries
Lancia-Alfa Romeo and Ferrari.
   Ghidella's resignation follows speculation on the Milan stock
market that he may join General Motors Corp., the giant U.S.
automaker.
   The announcement of Ghidella's departure hurt Fiat stocks'
performance. Fiat shares fell 90 lire to 9,800 lire on the Milan
exchange on Friday.
   Ghidella had been appointed managing director of Fiat Auto in
1979, when the company was plagued by a severe deficit and by labor
unrest.
   He masterminded, along with Romiti, a reorganization of the auto
division, which included staff layoffs and robotization, and
achieved a major turnaround earlier this decade.
   Fiat said Ghidella's decision to leave was made ``after careful
examination of the strategic choices which Fiat must take to
confront the challenges of 1990s.''
   ``Having failed to find agreement on some essential aspects, it
was decided to bring to an end a long and profitable collaboration
for both parties,'' it said.
</TEXT>
