<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TribunePrinters     11-25 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tribune Printers,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribune Accepts Strike Settlement with Printers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Management of the Chicago Tribune has accepted a
settlement to end a 3-year strike by the newspaper's unionized
printers, officials said today.
   The printers, members of Local 16 of the Chicago Typographical
Union, approved the pact and an $8.56 million settlement fund Sunday
on a 180-43 vote.
   A company spokesman said lawyers accepted and signed the
settlement on behalf of the newspaper Thursday and forwarded it to
Morton Bahr, president of the Washington-based Communications
Workers of America, the parent body of the printers union.
   The agreement was crafted under the guidance of former U.S. Labor
Secretary W.J. Usery.
   Under the agreement, the 119 printers who have remained on strike
will have the option of a buyout or a lifetime annuity, as well as
receiving company-paid medical insurance.
   When the strike began 40 months ago, 240 printers walked off the
job.
   Under the agreement, the 50 printers who remain at the newspaper
after a 1986 unconditional offer to return can stay, or can each
accept a $30,000 cash buyout.
   The agreement does not affect strikes by mailers and pressmen at
the newspaper. Those unions and the company are involved in a series
of strike-related lawsuits and proceedings before the National Labor
Relations Board.
   The printers' strike largely resulted from the company's desire
to gain greater control over hiring and assignments in the composing
room. The unions representing mailers and pressmen went out in
sympathy with the printers, but Teamster drivers of delivery trucks
stayed on the job and distribution of the newspaper continued.
   Under the agreement, the printers also agreed to drop a lawsuit
pending in federal court. The lawsuit alleged that the company
violated a 1975 agreement in which members were guaranteed lifetime
employment in exchange for the introduction of new, labor-saving
technologies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
