<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated in light post-Thanksgiving
Day trading today, faced with expectations of higher oil prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 17.78 to 2,074.50
by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 5 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 321 up, 776 down and
456 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.58 million shares at
midmorning.
   The session after Thanksgiving is usually one of the quietest
days on the year on Wall Street, as many market participants take a
long holiday weekend.
   This time, however, those traders who were present responded to
the news of a tentative agreement by members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries on production quotas aimed at shoring
up oil prices.
   The prospect of increased energy costs weighed down the credit
markets. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, fell nearly $10 for each
$1,000 in face value this morning.
   The stock market followed suit, with the notable exception of
energy stocks.
   In the energy sector, Atlantic Richfield rose 1\ to 79\; Exxon \
to 42\; Chevron } to 45; Amoco 1[ to 72}, and Amerada-Hess ~ to 30[.
   Losers among the blue-chip industrials included International
Business Machines, down 1{ at 116{; General Electric, down | at 43};
Ford Motor, down } at 50], and American Telephone & Telegraph, down
{ at 28}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.84 to 150.57. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .42 at 290.51.
