<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
moderately higher in light trading today on the Chicago Board of
Trade, reflecting higher prices for soybeans and soybean meal in
Europe on Thursday.
   Up to 80,000 metric tons of soybean meal and as many as 40,000
metric tons of soybeans were traded at higher levels in Rotterdam,
the Netherlands, and ``that sparked interest here this morning
because it showed interest over there,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Forecasts for a dry weekend in the South American soybean belt
added to the bullish tone in the soy markets, he said.
   Futures prices of wheat and corn were up slightly on continuing
expectations that the Soviet Union and the United States will sign a
long-term grain sales agreement early next week.
   The grain markets are optimistic about a new grain pact with the
Soviets. ``If it doesn't happen, it'll be a disappointment,''
Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.20\ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 2
cents higher across the board with December at $2.14\ a bushel;
soybeans were 3} cents to 6{ cents higher with January at $7.61} a
bushel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Cattle futures were slightly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent to .37 cent higher with December at
73.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .35 cent higher
with January at 82.70 cents a pound; hogs were .57 cent lower to .40
cent higher with December at 39.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent lower to .70 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
