<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Polaroid-Shamrock     11-25 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Polaroid-Shamrock,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Blocks Polaroid Takeover Pending Disclosures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court stalled the $2.6
billion hostile takeover of Polaroid Corp. by Shamrock Holdings
Inc., ordering the investment group to make corrective disclosures
about its offer, Shamrock said.
   Shamrock, headed by Roy Disney, a nephew of the late Walt Disney,
planned to make the required disclosures promptly and seek to have
the court order lifted so it can pursue its offer to acquire the
instant-film company, Shamrock spokesman Tom Reed said Friday.
   The ruling was issued late Wednesday by the 3rd Circuit Court of
Appeals. The court instructed the U.S. District Court in Delaware to
enjoin the Shamrock offer until corrective disclosures were made.
   The court sought clarification of the applicability of federal
margin regulations to the offer, Reed said, calling the order to
provide more information a technicality.
   The ruling followed a Polaroid appeal of an earlier order to
provide the names and addresses of workers who participate in an
employee stock plan, Reed said.
   That legal wrangle is separate from a suit by Polaroid seeking an
order blocking Burbank-based Shamrock's $42-a-share tender offer to
buy the company from shareholders.
   ``That's the big case that will decide this thing,'' Reed said.
``This other thing about technical disclosures is just a little
sideshow.''
   Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware, where state laws make
hostile takeover bids more difficult to complete than in some other
states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Argentina-Crops Bjt   11-25 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Crops, Bjt,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentine Wheat Farmers Unable To Cash in on U.S. Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late rains dried up plans by
Argentine wheat farmers to cash in on last summer's drought in the
United States, further enhancing the switch to soybeans in this
agricultural exporter.
   ``Not just me, every farmer anticipated sowing more cereal
crops,'' said Alejandro Delfino, whose 1,976-acre farm lies in Santa
Fe province northwest of Buenos Aires.
   But the country's fertile pampas were hit by their own mild
drought during a three-month period through early October, when the
rains returned.
   The National Grain Board estimates 11.4 million acres of wheat
were planted, a decline of 494,000 acres from last year, which was
the smallest planting in a decade.
   ``Farmers intended to plant as much as 6 million hectares (14.8
million acres),'' said Hector Niell, the board's president, who
estimated that yields would drop by 20 percent an acre or more.
   The Ministry of Agriculture projects that wheat production will
amount to about 8.4 million tons, a drop of about a million tons
from this year's crop.
   The planting of other crops is taking place normally, however,
and 1989 looks to be another banner year for farmers, who reaped a
$1 billion bonanza when prices for soybeans soared due to the
drought in the United States.
   Prices have remained high, and Argentina's crop exports in 1989
should fetch $5.5 billion, or about $1 billion more than this year,
Niell said.
   An additional 2.5 million acres are being planted in soybeans,
affirming that as the main export crop in a country that for decades
depended most heavily on wheat. Farmers planted 10.4 million acres
of soybeans in 1988.
   Argentina is the world's No. 2 exporter of corn, No. 3 producer
of soybeans and No. 4 producer of wheat. Soybeans replaced wheat as
the country's top export in 1987.
   Total production _ wheat, soybeans, corn, sorghum, soybean oil,
pellets and other crops _ is projected at 38 million to 40 million
tons, up from 36 million tons in 1988, Niell said.
   About 12 tons are consumed domestically, and the rest is offered
for sale abroad, said Guillermo Toranzas, an economist for Rural
Society, a powerful farm group.
   Peak production _ 44 million tons _ was achieved in the 1984-85
season.
   ``Argentina easily could produce 60 million tons a year,'' bu
does not because of agricultural subsidies by the United States and
European Economic Community that protect their lucrative markets,
Niell said.
   But farm groups also complain about domestic barriers to
production.
   The most aggravating is a dual exchange system by which farmers
who want to import machinery are obliged to purchase U.S. dollars at
the commercial rate of 14 australs to 1, but are reimbursed by the
Central Bank for dollars they earn from export sales at the rate of
12-1.
   The system was imposed by the government in August to raise
revenue and foreign exchange. Farmers consider it an export tax.
   Also, farmers say Argentina's infrastructure deficiencies _
inadequate roads, out-of-date trains, lack of bank credits _ limits
production, as do government policies that favor industry at the
expense of agriculture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881125-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-TheWeekAhead     11-25 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-The Week Ahead,0457</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the major business events and economic events scheduled
