<1ST_LINE>u f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv26-27   11-25 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 26-27,0614</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 26-27</NOTE>
<HEAD>L.A. Skips Traditional Credit Markets for First-of-its-Kind Loan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles County had a yen for new dollars, so
it went across the Pacific to get some _ in a roundabout way.
   Deciding to forgo the public bond market, the county agreed to
borrow $100 million from Nippon Life Insurance Co. and Long Term
Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., with the loan to be repaid over 10 years
at a below-market interest rate.
   While simple on the surface, getting to that point took two years
of ground-breaking bargaining.
   The pact is thought to be the first of its kind between a local
U.S. government body and foreign businesses. It involves a special
currency-swap arrangement, said Anthony C. Hughes, a vice president
at First Boston Corp., Los Angeles County's financial adviser.
   Under the agreement, he said, the county will receive $100
million worth of yen that will be converted into dollars at a fixed
rate. The loan will be repaid in dollars, then converted back to yen.
   Hughes said the currency rate will be fixed at the date of the
deal's closing, expected before year's end, and that will provide a
hedge against any risks from fluctuating currency exchange rates.
   A fixed interest rate also will guard against volatility in the
credit markets, which set the pace for rates. Interest repaid by the
county will be equal to the rate of the 10-year U.S. Treasury note
at the closing, plus 0.58 percentage point. At today's rates, that
is lower than the 10 percent charged for the prime lending rate of
major American banks.
   Hughes said that while the deal appears to be more favorable to
the county, it also will help boost Japan's image in the area.
``There is significant interest on the part of Japan to do business
in L.A. and with L.A.-based companies,'' he said.
   Hughes said the $100 million would be invested in high-grade
bonds, with the profits used to help reduce the unfunded liability
in the employees' retirement system.
   ``We have been shopping for opportunities in the taxable market,
and this is the first and best opportunity we have found,'' said
Richard B. Dixon, the county's chief administrative officer.
   The county had been seeking alternatives to the domestic market
after Congress eliminated local government's ability to issue
tax-exempt pension bonds under the 1986 Tax Reform Act.
   While some analysts predicted the county's arrangement with
Nippon and Long Term Credit Bank might prompt other municipalities
to seek similar arrangements to get a more competitive interest
rate, those close to the Los Angeles County agreement were not so
sure, partly due to the complexity of their deal.
   ``We've had a lot of calls, mostly from municipalities that are
curious,'' said Sharon Yonashiro, director of public finance for the
county treasurer's office. ``(But) I'm not sure how broad this is
going to apply.''
   She also noted that most Japanese companies prefer to deal with
large loans.
   ``Other than very large borrowers, the U.S. taxable (bond) market
would generally be more attractive,'' she said.
   Neal Attermann, municipal reserach director of the investment
firm Kidder, Peabody & Co. Inc., agreed.
   He predicted such a deal could become a viable alternative if
California's controversial insurance rate rollback was upheld by the
courts and insurance companies ultimately left the state.
   ``California itself might have to become an insurer and go
abroad'' for funds, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 26-27</NOTE>
</DOC>
