<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pound Finishes Higher, Dollar and Gold Also Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British pound grabbed the attention of the
European currency market Friday, taking an early plunge but ending
higher after news of a record British trade gap triggered a full
point rise in interest rates.
   The dollar ended slightly higher in a thin market, pushed up
primarily by a few big orders. Gold prices also rose.
   News that Britain's current account deficit widened to a record
2.43 billion pounds, or $4.5 billion, in October surprised the
financial markets, The figures sent the pound plunging to around
$1.8220 but dealers said selling was thin because most market
players expected the Bank of England to respond by triggering a hike
in base interest rates to 13 percent from 12 percent, which it did.
   High interest rates make pound-denominated investments more
attractive.
   The dollar received an early boost in Tokyo trading by persistent
intervention by the Bank of Japan, dealers said. The dollar also was
pushed higher by the pound's initial weakness following the trade
figures, plus a few big orders in the market, they said.
   In London, the pound gained to $1.8435 dollars from Thursday's
late $1.8375.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.7154 West German marks, up from 1.7135; 1.4365 Swiss francs, down
from 1.4375; 5.8615 French francs, up from 5.8585; 1.9368 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.9340; 1,275.50 Italian lire, up from 1,273.75;
and 1.1918 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1960.
   In Tokyo, where markets close before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 121.15 yen, unchanged from Thursday.
Later, in London, it also was quoted at 121.15 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $424.00 a troy ounce,
compared with Thursday's late bid of $420. In Zurich, gold rose to
$424 an ounce from $420.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed up $3.39 to $424.55 an ounce
Friday.
   Silver bullion prices gained ground on the London market, closing
at $6.18 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
