<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Tumble on Poor Trade News, Interest Rate Hike</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News of the worst British trade deficit on record
and a consequent 1 percent rise in a key interest rate sent the
stock market into a tailspin Friday, as share prices finished
sharply lower.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed down
38.3 points, or 2.1 percent, at 1,794.7, an improvement over the
session low of 50.5 points down.
   Its best level for the day came at the opening, when the index
was up 3.4 points.
   ``The bears are definitely out in force,'' a dealer said. Noting
that confidence in the market had been recovering lately, he said,
``But now everyone's been completely blown out of the water.''
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 31.1 points at
1,462.6 at the close.
   Volume was an active 713.1 million shares, up sharply from the
524.6 million shares traded Thursday.
   Wall Street was down 19.73 points at 2,072.72 as the London
session drew to a close, adding another pessimistic note to trading,
dealers said.
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit in October more than doubled
to 2.93 billion pounds, or around $5.4 billion, the Department of
Trade and Industry reported.
   Soon after the report was released in late morning, the Bank of
England, by increasing its own money-market lending rate, signaled a
1 percentage point rise in the commercial banks' base lending rate
to 13 percent. That was the key rate's highest level in more than
31@2 years.
   The Financial Times 500-share index fell 23.48 points to close at
1,017.14.
</TEXT>
