<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Carnival-Holland     11-25 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carnival-Holland,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carnival to Buy Holland America's Seattle Operations for $625
Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holland America Line's Seattle-based travel and
tourism companies will be purchased by Carnival Cruise Lines Inc. of
Miami for approximately $625 million, the two companies announced
Friday.
   Officials of Carnival, one of the world's largest cruise lines,
described it as a significant consolidation in their business. The
announcement came one month after Carnival lost in its attempt to
take over another cruise operation, Royal Admiral Cruises Ltd.
   Micky Arison, president of Carnival and the son of its
billionaire majority owner Ted Arison, and Nico van der Vorm,
chairman of Holland America Line N.V., said in a joint announcement
that their companies had signed a letter of intent for Carnival to
buy Holland America's cruise operations, Westours tour operations,
Westmark Hotels and Windstar Sail Cruises.
   Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher said it would likely be an
all-cash transaction although details haven't been completed.
   The proposed sale is subject to signing of defintive agreements,
approval by both companies' boards of directors, and approval by
shareholders of Holland America. The sale is expected to close
before Jan. 15.
   Holland America operates four ships in the Caribbean and Alaska,
representing about 4,500 berths. Westmark has a chain of 18 hotels
in Alaska and western Canada, while Westours is the largest
wholesale tour operator in those areas.
   Windstar Sail Cruises operates three passenger sailing ships in
the South Pacific, Mediterranean and Caribbean.
   Van der Vorm will join Carnival's board of directors. The Holland
America companies will continue operating under their current names
and management with no merging of operations or change in products
planned, Arison said.
   Carnival operates seven cruise ships in the Bahamas, Caribbean
and Mexico, each equipped with a casino and usually fully booked.
The cruise line also operates a casino in the Bahamas and is builty
an 872-room luxury resort there.
   The cruise line is 80 percent owned by Ted Arison, 64, an Israeli
shipowner's son who is one of the world's wealthiest men. He has
been ranked No. 17 on the Forbes List of richest Americans with an
estimated fortune of $1.6 billion.
   Arison also has holdings in New York's Ensign Bank, an Atlanta
real estate firm and an interest in the Miami Heat basketball
franchise.
   He founded Carnival in 1972 with parnter Meshulam Riklis and
bought out his interests two years later. Arison took Carnival
public in 1986 and its shares are traded on the American Stock
Exchange.
   The price rose 12{ cents late Friday to $14.25.
</TEXT>
