<1ST_LINE>d f AM-PrizeWool     11-25 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prize Wool,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Firm First Non-Briton To Buy Prize Wool Bale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American suit maker became the first
non-British tailoring firm to win the annual bidding for a prize
bale of premium Australian merino wool.
   J. Schoeneman Inc., a Baltimore company that makes men's clothes,
bid the equivalent of $4,800 to buy the ``Golden Bale'' auctioned by
Joseph Lumb & Sons in Huddersfield, England.
   Lumb, which established the Golden Bale Award to encourage the
production of high-quality merino wool in Australia, said previous
prize bales had been bought by a few exclusive tailors from London's
Savile Row.
   The prize bale, which was produced by Trevor Picker of Bigga, New
South Wales, brought a price 12 to 15 times greater than the average
bale of premium Austalian wool, Lumb said.
</TEXT>
