<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1545EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BoeingYear Bjt   11-25 1045</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Year, Bjt,1080</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing's Bottom Line Overshadows Bad News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1 of Nov. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Boeing-Big Orders and BC-Boeing-Next</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This might be considered a crummy year for Boeing
Co. if it weren't selling commercial jets at the rate of $85 million
a day.
   There's been no dearth of bad news in 1988 for the giant
planemaker:
   Longtime customers complained about quality. Employees working
with new materials complained of mysterious ailments. The Navy was
upset with a contract. There are lingering problems with commuter
planes.
   A much-promoted new jumbo jet was delayed. So was a major ``Star
Wars'' project. So was a new helicopter. So was the president's new
jet.
   Most dramatically, a harrowing accident in which the top sheared
off a Boeing 737 over Hawaii underscored concerns about how long
airlines can continue to fly old jets.
   All of that aside, the company smashed industry records for
number and value of aircraft ordered in a single year.
   With this fourth straight year of record orders, Boeing has
guaranteed work for its two jetliner factories well into the
mid-1990s. Its Boeing Commercial Airplanes division is increasing
production across the board, only the third such time it's done so.
   Boeing has introduced two new passenger jets this year, plans a
third for May, and is thinking about a fourth and possibly a fifth.
   On the military and aerospace sides, several projects could start
moving from development into production in the next few years,
meaning they'll start bringing in money.
   ``They can have all eight cylinders percolating at the same time
here in a few years,'' said Paul Nisbet, aerospace industry analyst
for Prudential Bache Securities in New York.
   So far this year, Boeing has announced orders for 595 commercial
planes, worth $28 billion, up from 366 planes worth $19.9 billion
last year. Boeing has about two-thirds of the world commercial jet
market, with rivals Airbus Industrie and McDonnell Douglas Corp.
sharing the remainder.
   The record could go higher. Several major carriers, including
United Airlines and TWA, reportedly are considering major purchases.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Boeing earned $440 million, or
$2.88 a share, on sales of $12.09 billion, up from $339 millon, or
$2.18 a share, on sales of $10.87 billion in the same 1987 period.
   Boeing has an order backlog of more than 1,000 jets, and has been
setting delivery dates as late as 1995.
   To accommodate that growth, Boeing is boosting production of 767
widebodies and 747 jumbo jets next year, mid-sized 757 jetliners in
mid-1989 and the smaller 737s in mid-1990.
   ``An absolutely massive exercise,'' says Philip Condit, Boeing
Commercial Airplanes executive vice president for production and
engineering.
   In late summer, Boeing announced that electrical problems had
forced delays in delivery of the new 747-400 jumbo jet, the world's
largest commercial plane, to the first 20 customers. Deliveries are
expeted to be on track by second-quarter 1989.
   Boeing began 1988 with the unprecedented introduction of two new
aircraft on the same day: the 747-400 and the 737-400, an updated
and stretched version of the workhorse twinjet. Both are popular
sellers.
   But soon came word that some major Boeing customers, including
Japan Air Lines, British Airways, All Nippon Airways and American
Airlines, were upset at the quality of some planes they were getting.
   More production problems were reported in early summer, when
workers at a Boeing fabrication plant began reporting ailments
ranging from nosebleeds to headaches and memory loss. They
attributed the illnesses to chemicals used to make lightweight
aircraft parts.
   Air samples at the plant showed nothing untoward, but the
complaints have persisted. Two medical panels have been formed to
study the problem, and Boeing has cut back on the chemicals' use.
   On April 28, the top of an Aloha Airlines 737 ripped off at
24,000 feet, sweeping a flight attendant to her death before the
plane could land safely. The 19-year-old plane, with nearly 90,000
flights, was one of the most-used in the 737 fleet and the accident
prompted a round of investigations and discussions about aging
aircraft.
   Boeing says its planes have an indefinite life, if they are
properly maintained, and intensified its studies of older aircraft.
   The four airlines whose workmanship complaints were publicized
all have since made sizeable orders with Boeing. Aloha also bought
replacement 737s.
   Boeing offers eight aircraft models with anywhere from 108 to 660
seats. The planes are grouped into three ``families,'' 747s, 757-67s
and 737s, that share many systems, and don't require a pilot to
recertify to fly another model within a family.
   Boeing's newest plane, the 108-seat 737-500, rolls out next May.
And Condit said ``we're looking very hard'' at a larger 767.
   An existing 767-300 holds about 250 passengers, and Condit said
the new plane, designated 767-X, is envisioned at 300 or 350 seats,
or both.
   As Boeing speeds jet construction, it's struggling to keep its
money-losing de Havilland commuter plane line on schedule. Boeing
officials haven't hidden their disappointment since buying de
Havilland from Canada in 1986.
   In defense and space work, 1988 also has been uneven. This fall,
Boeing rolled out its first Avenger launch system for Stinger
missiles, and the space shuttle Discovery carried a Boeing-built
rocket booster in September.
   But there have been delays on several major projects, including
Navy A-6E attack aircraft, the V-22 Osprey tilt-rotor helicopter and
the Airborne Optical Adjunct, a Strategic Defense Initiative project.
   Problems with wiring in two 747s being built as new Air Force
Ones pushed back the delivery of the first presidential jet 13
months to next November.
   Judith Comeau, analyst at Goldman, Sachs & Co. in New York, said
Boeing's earnings from military and aerospace work will fall to $48
million this year from $179 million in 1987.
   How long can the good times roll? Depends on the economy, says
Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton. What it comes
down to, he says, is that if people have money to fly, airlines have
money to buy planes.
   Still, Condit remembers that both times Boeing increased
production on all its lines, in 1967-68 and 1978-79, it promptly was
pounded by a recession.
   ``Everybody's been watching that one,'' he said. ``Everybody's
been looking over their shoulder and saying, `OK, when?'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
