<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat, Soybeans Post Solid Gains In Broad Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of wheat and soybeans posted solid
gains Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a broad rally.
   Analysts said the rally was fueled by brisk soybean trade on
European markets and expectations for a new U.S.-Soviet grain
agreement.
   The wheat market had its strongest day since Oct. 3. Wheat
futures surged in response to a French press report that U.S. and
Soviet negotiators would open a final round of talks Monday in
Moscow on renewing a 5-year grain pact that expired on Sept. 30. A
2-year extension is expected.
   Analysts said up to 80,000 metric tons of soybean meal and as
many as 40,000 metric tons of soybeans exchanged hands at higher
prices in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, during the week, an indication
that export demand for U.S. soybeans may also rise.
   Recurring talk of dry conditions in the South American soybean
belt, where planting is well underway, also lent support to the
soybean market. But analyst Cathy Leow of Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York said such concerns were premature.
   ``There are some areas of dryness but at this point in the crop
year you can't get too excited about it,'' she said.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 1} cents to 7{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.25{ a bushel; corn
was 1} cents to 2} cents higher with December at $2.65 a bushel;
oats were 2} cents to 5 cents higher with December at $2.15 a
bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents to 12} cents higher with January at
$7.66{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
