<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1645EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OPEC-Texas     11-25 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC-Texas,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say OPEC Accord Would Help State Revenues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-OPEC Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative OPEC accord aimed at boosting crude
prices by cutting back output would have little immediate impact on
Texas oil producers, industry experts said Friday.
   But it could help bolster natural gas prices and brighten the
budget outlook for the 1989 Legislature, they said.
   Iraq's oil minister predicted the tentative deal would send crude
oil prices soaring to $18 a barrel within a few months, although
analysts said they doubted prices would rise that high.
   ``Obviously, from the standpoint of Texas, the higher the price
of oil, the better our economy can perform,'' said Ray Perryman,
director of the Baylor University Forecasting Service.
   ``Over the short term, our economy has been driven by other
things, such as manufacturing, but over the long term it would have
a much more substantial effect,'' Perryman said.
   The tentative deal worked out by the ministers of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was announced late
Thursday. It would reduce the amount of oil OPEC has been producing
by an estimated 4 million barrels a day.
   But given the history of in-fighting among cartel members and
cheating on individual quotas, many analysts predicted the agreement
would not last long enough to push prices up to $18 from the
$14-a-barrel range.
   Nevertheless, such a steep climb would not prompt drastic changes
among Texas oil producers, but could stimulate exploration and
production among natural gas companies next spring when gas prices
would otherwise fall after a peak season, experts said.
   ``The impact would obviously be positive, but I don't think the
impact would be as much as some people might think,'' said Charles
M. Strain, director of energy research for Lovett Mitchell Webb &
Garrison in Houston.
   ``Based on our conversations with major oil companies, and even
smaller producers, they are not reacting to short-term swings in
price anymore,'' Strain said. ``They are not going to change their
expenditure plans dramatically when prices go down to $13 for a
month or two, or go up to $20 for a month or two.''
   Perryman also expects some hesitation among producers who have
watched OPEC ignore past production quotas. However, he predicted an
agreement could draw immediate reaction in the halls of the Texas
Capitol.
   ``Probably the most interesting short-term effect is the impact
on state revenues. It could literally change the entire character of
the next legislative session if they go in with oil at $18 a barrel
instead of $13,'' Perryman said.
   ``If they go in with oil at $18 the way things are structured
right now on the revenue base, the legislators would probably be
looking at a small surplus, and that would enable them to focus on
other issues,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
