<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-25 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pound Finishes Higher In Volatile Trading; Dollar Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar crept slightly higher against several
key currencies in quiet dealings Friday, but the British pound took
center stage in volatile trading linked to the latest report on
Britain's trade deficit.
   The metals markets were closed for the Thanksgiving Day holiday
in the United States, but gold prices strengthened overseas.
   James Chorek, a technical analyst with MMS International in
Chicago, said the dollar received an early boost from persistent
intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   The dollar also was helped later in the trading session by
speculation that the Federal Reserve might push up short-term
interest rates by raising the discount rate, or the interest charged
on loans to member banks.
   Higher interest rates tend to support a currency, and that was
the case with the pound Friday. It ended higher in domestic and
European trading after news of a record British $4.5 billion trade
gap triggered a full point rise in interest rates.
   The trade report had sent the pound plunging to around $1.8220 in
Europe, but dealers said it rebounded after the Bank of England
pushed up base interest rates to 13 percent from 12 percent.
   In London, the pound rose to $1.8435 from Thursday's late
$1.8375. Later, in New York, sterling fetched $1.84235, up from
$1.8365.
   In Tokyo, where markets close before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar ended at 121.15 Japanese yen, unchanged from
Thursday. It also was quoted at 121.15 yen in London.
   But in New York it rose to 121.175 yen from 120.95 Friday, when
it reached a 40-year low.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.7170 West German marks, up from 1.7155; 1.43725 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4360; 1.19025 Canadian dollars, down from 1.19625;
5.8705 French francs, up from 5.8645; and 1,275.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,276.375.
   The dollar did not trade in New York Thursday in observance of
Thanksgiving Day.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday: 1.7154
West German marks, up from 1.7135; 1.4365 Swiss francs, down from
1.4375; 5.8615 French francs, up from 5.8585; 1.9368 Dutch guilders,
up from 1.9340; 1,275.50 Italian lire, up from 1,273.75; and 1.1918
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1960.
   The Commodity Exchange in New York, where gold and silver are
traded, was closed Friday.
   But in London, gold rose to a late bid price of $424.00 a troy
ounce, compared with Thursday's late bid of $420. In Zurich,
Switzerland, gold rose to $424 an ounce from $420.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed up $3.39 to $424.55 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices gained ground on the London market, closing
at $6.18 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
