<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1724EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-25 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Surge On Hopes For Soviet Grain Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices posted their strongest gains in nearly two
months Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid signs that the
United States and the Soviet Union were nearing agreement on a new
multi-year grain deal.
   On other markets, soybeans and other grains also advanced; cotton
futures surged; cattle futures were higher; pork futures were mixed;
and stock-index futures retreated.
   The major U.S. markets for oil, metal, coffee, cocoa and sugar
futures were closed Friday for Thanksgiving.
   Heavy speculation surfaced Wednesday that U.S. and Soviet
negotiators were about to sign a grain pact, and those expectations
were enhanced on Friday by a French Press Agency report that a final
round of talks would begin Monday in Moscow.
   Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Alan Holmer confirmed after the
grain markets closed that the talks would resume next week in the
Soviet Union.
   The pact being discussed was rumored to be a 2-year extension of
the 5-year agreement that expired Sept. 30, guaranteeing annual
Soviet purchases of 9 million metric tons of U.S. grain _ 4 million
of wheat, 4 million of corn and 1 million of the buyer's choice.
   Wheat futures prices leaped 3 cents to 7{ cents higher on the
news _ the sharpest one-day rally since Oct. 3 _ with the contract
for delivery in December settling at $4.25{ a bushel.
   ``We're confident the long-term agreement will be signed early
next week, by Monday or Wednesday or so,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
grain trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``If not, it could be a problem,'' he said. ``And even if it is
signed, it could be a case of that old saying, `Buy the rumor, sell
the fact.'''
   Soybean futures hit new highs for the week in response to brisk
trade in soybeans and soybean meal on European markets on Thursday
and Friday, an indication that export demand for U.S. soybeans may
rise.
   Recurring talk of dry conditions in the South American soybean
belt, where planting is well underway, also supported the soybean
market. But analyst Cathy Leow of Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
in New York said such concerns were premature.
   ``There are some areas of dryness but at this point in the crop
year you can't get too excited about it,'' she said.
   Soybeans settled 4 cents to 12 cents higher with January at
$7.65} a bushel; corn was 1} cents to 3\ cents higher with December
at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 5 cents higher with
December at $2.15 a bushel.
   Cotton futures surged on the New York Cotton Exchange on
indications of increased demand, analysts said.
   The soon-to-expire contract for December delivery opened 2.4
cents higher, an extremely sharp gain, in reaction to a pending
17,200-bale decline in the exchange's certificated warehouse stocks.
The owners have declared their intention to decertificate the cotton
because they have found buyers for it.
   ``I have hardly ever seen a big figure like that pending
decertification,'' said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``That brings the
certificated stock down to 33,500 bales. That's a small stock.''
   In addition, Simon said, U.S. cotton is beginning to find more
overseas buyers despite its high price on the world market. A USDA
report issued after the close of trading said cotton exports for the
week ending Nov. 17 were about 45 percent above both the prior week
and the four-week average.
   Simon said the reliability of U.S. cotton suppliers apparently
was the reason for recent sales to South Korea, Indonesia and the
Philippines.
   Cotton settled .67 cent to 1.90 cents higher with December at
55.70 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures gained modestly on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
on strong spot markets and expectations for higher spot markets next
week. Pork futures finished mixed amid expectations of lower spot
hog prices on Monday, analysts said. Trading activity was light.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent to .48 cent higher with December at
73.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .28 cent higher
with January at 82.67 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .23
cent higher with December at 39.85 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .35 cent lower to .17 cent higher with February at
42.45 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated substantially on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 1.9 points lower at 267.35. Each
point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
