<1ST_LINE>u f BC-MoneySupply     11-25 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Money Supply,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>M3 Up, M2 and M1 Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The broadest measure of the nation's money supply
rose in the week ended Nov. 14 but two narrower measurements fell,
the Federal Reserve Board reported Friday.
   The Fed said its all-encompassing measure of money known as M3
rose to a seasonally adjusted $3.881 trillion, up from $3.878
trillion the previous week. A narrower measure known as M2 averaged
a seasonally adjusted $3.044 trillion, down from $3.045 trillion the
prior week.
   The narrowest measure, known as M1, fell by $2.4 billion to a
seasonally adjusted average of $779.3 billion, vs. a revised figure
of $781.7 billion the prior week.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the dollar's value, commodity prices and the difference
between short- and long-term interest rates, rather than focusing
heavily on money supply figures. It also has suggested that of the
three figures, M2 and M3 are more significant.
   The Fed said in mid 1988 that it reaffirmed its target for annual
growth in M2 and M3 at between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is
slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent.
The Fed has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose by $160 million
in the week ended Nov. 16, vs. a decline of $59 million the previous
week.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $294 million a day in
the week ended Wednesday, down from $540 million a day the previous
week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $285.1 billion in the two-week period ended Nov. 16, up from
$283.5 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
