<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     11-25 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Called Off in Pillsbury-Grand Met Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court hearing that had been set for Monday
in the Delaware lawsuit against Pillsbury Co. has been called off
because the food and restaurant company has postponed the record
date of its planned spinoff of Burger King.
   Hostile suitor Grand Metropolitan PLC is suing Pillsbury to block
the spinoff and invalidate Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' defense,
designed to make a takeover prohibitively expensive.
   The British liquor, gambling and specialty products conglomerate
says the two defense tactics are preventing Pillsbury shareholders
from cashing in on Grand Met's $5.23 billion tender offer,
equivalent to $60 a share.
   A hearing had been scheduled for Monday in Delaware Chancery
Court on the Burger King spinoff, but a clerk for Chancellor William
Allen said Friday it was called off.
   Joseph Rosenthal, a lawyer for dissident Pillsbury shareholders,
said the need for a hearing on Monday was eliminated when Pillsbury
postponed the record date of the planned spinoff from Dec. 2 to Dec.
19.
   Rosenthal said Friday the spinoff issue probably will be
addressed at a court hearing Dec. 12 before Chancellor Allen.
   Early this week, Pillsbury delayed its plans to spin off Burger
King into a separate company after Burger King franchisees voiced
opposition to the spinoff, saying it would add too much debt to the
slumping fast-food chain that accounts for a large portion of
Pillsbury's profits.
   Under the plan, Pillsbury shareholders would be issued stock in
the newly separated Burger King, which would borrow money and issue
a special dividend to shareholders.
   Grand Met has said a separate Burger King would present a huge
tax liability to Grand Met if its takeover bid is successful.
</TEXT>
