<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     11-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Up, Home Sales Down, Markets Weak, Christmas Buying Appears
Strong</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   News of rising oil prices hurt the stock and bond markets but
trading was light and most Americans paid no attention anyway,
preoccupied instead with that annual post-Thanksgiving pilgrimage,
Christmas shopping.
   Oil traders bid up the price by more than $1 a barrel Friday to
the $14.40 level on international markets because of the expectation
that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would ratify
a tentative production accord to limit output and help reduce a
chronic supply glut.
   While OPEC ministers meeting in Vienna, Austria, appeared
determined to enforce production discipline, industry analysts
expressed skepticism, given the cartel's history of failing to honor
its own pacts because of member cheating.
   Some analysts said they didn't believe the price rise would have
much of an impact on prices of gasoline or other petroleum products
because it would be short-lived.
   Still, the magnitude of the oil increase rattled the bond market,
a key barometer of the economy, inflation and interest rates. Prices
of 30-year Treasury bonds dropped sharply and their yields, which go
in the opposite direction, climbed to 9.17 percent from 9.10 percent
late Wednesday.
   The impact spilled onto Wall Street where stocks slumped, partly
because rising yields in the bond market tend to siphon investor
money out of stocks. But trading volume was the lightest in nearly
two years, since many investment professionals had taken the day off
for a four-day Thanksgiving weekend.
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 17.60 points to 2,074.68.
   The markets evidently saw little significance in a National
Association of Realtors report that showed sales of existing homes
fell in October for the second straight month, even though mortgage
rates declined. The report suggested the economy is slowing down.
   None of this news appeared to dampen consumer enthusiasm for
Christmas shopping, an annual rite on the day after Thanksgiving.
   A random spot check of stores nationwide by The Associated Press
suggested a surprisingly strong beginning to the traditional
Christmas selling season, a crucial time for retailers. The mood
contrasted with the cautious buying that has pervaded during the
previous few years.
</TEXT>
