<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1950EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     11-25 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise If OPEC Accord Signed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement to curtail OPEC's rampant oil
production could produce a temporary rise in petroleum prices, but
any change is likely to be short-lived, analysts say.
   Ministers from the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were expected to meet again Saturday in Vienna, Austria,
to ratify a proposed six-month oil reduction accord.
   But analysts remained skeptical over just how long the deal would
last or how much impact it would have on prices.
   ``In reality, we'll see whatever potential gains are going to
come from this accord on Monday,'' said William Byers, an analyst
with Bear, Stearns & Co. ``The market will level off after Monday.''
   On the International Petroleum Exchange in London Friday, prices
for January delivery of Brent, the benchmark North Sea crude oil,
climbed $1.65 a barrel to $14.42.
   U.S. petroleum exchanges closed early Wednesday for a four-day
Thanksgiving holiday, but analysts said U.S. markets would match the
European gains if the OPEC ministers signed a final accord over the
weekend.
   Futures prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange closed
slightly higher on Wednesday in anticipation that OPEC would reach
some sort of agreement. The contract for January delivery of West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, closed 11
cents higher at $13.97 a barrel after sharp swings during the
trading session.
   Prices had convulsed upward since Monday when OPEC convened its
winter meeting in Vienna. Analysts said the highly erratic trading
sessions reflected the dramatic twists and turns emanating from the
conference of ministers.
   Late Thursday, the ministers announced a tentative pact to reduce
output from the more than 22 million barrels a day estimated now to
18.5 million barrels. The meeting was recessed until Saturday night
to allow Iran's oil minister to return home to consult with his
government.
   One of the key provisions of the pact would grant Iraq production
parity with Iran, something Iran had fought bitterly. However, the
proposal also reportedly would allow Iran to increase its production
and maintain its 14 percent share of OPEC production.
   Analysts said they expect an agreement to bolster prices in the
short term, but said they doubted the accord would last long enough
to boost prices to OPEC's target of $18 a barrel.
   Cyrus H. Tahmassebi, chief economist for Ashland Oil Inc., said
he expected a short-term strengthening of prices if a deal is signed.
   ``But once the market fundamentals hit, prices will go down,'' he
said.
   Steve H. Hanke, chief economist of Friedberg Commodity Management
Inc. in Toronto and a professor of economics at Johns Hopkins
University, said a combination of excess capacity, a desperate need
by OPEC countries for oil export revenue and prices that still far
exceed production costs would drive prices down in both the short
and long term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
